ame]] [[defensive back]] in the NFL\n* [[Alfred C. Williams]] (1951\u20132015) \u2013 state representative for East Baton Rouge Parish (since 2015)\n* [[A. L. Williams (American football)|A. L. Williams]] (born 1934) \u2013 retired football coach\n* [[Brian \"Baby\" Williams]] (born 1969) \u2013 [[record executive]]; record producer; entrepreneur; musician\n* [[Chris Williams (offensive lineman)|Chris Williams]] (born 1985) \u2013 [[Guard (American football)|offensive guard]] for the [[Chicago Bears]]\n* [[Duke Williams (safety)|Duke Williams]] (born 1990) \u2013 [[Safety (gridiron football position)|safety]] for the [[Buffalo Bills]]\n* [[Gerald Williams (baseball)|Gerald Williams]] (born 1966) \u2013 former [[Major League Baseball]] [[outfielder]]\n* [[Hank Williams Jr.]] (born 1949) \u2013 singer\n* [[Kyle Williams (defensive tackle)|Kyle Williams]] (born 1983) \u2013 [[defensive tackle]] for the [[Buffalo Bills]]\n* [[Lucinda Williams]] (born 1963) \u2013 singer-songwriter; musician\n* [[Patrick Williams (Louisiana politician)|Patrick C. Williams]] (born 1963) \u2013 state representative for Caddo Parish\n* [[T. Harry Williams]] (1909\u20131979) \u2013 historian\n* [[Tramon Williams]] (born 1983) \u2013 [[cornerback]] for the [[Green Bay Packers]]\n* [[Norris C. Williamson]] (1874\u20131949) \u2013 politician\n* [[Edwin E. Willis]] (1904\u20131972) \u2013 [[United States House of Representatives|US Representative]] (1949\u201369)\n* [[Tom Willmott]] (born 1960) \u2013 [[Louisiana State Legislature|state representative]] from [[Jefferson Parish, Louisiana|Jefferson Parish]] (since 2008)\n* [[Harry Wilson (Louisiana politician)|Harry D. Wilson]] (1869\u20131948) \u2013 [[Louisiana Department of Agriculture and Forestry|Louisiana Commissioner of Agriculture and Forestry]] (1916\u201348)\n* [[Justin Wilson (chef)|Justin E. Wilson]] (1914\u20132001) \u2013 [[Cajun]]; [[raconteur]]; [[chef]]; humorist; politician\n* [[Peggy Wilson (Louisiana politician)|Peggy Wilson]] (born 1937) \u2013 Republican politician; former member of the New Orleans City Council\n* [[Riley J. Wilson]] (1871\u20131946) \u2013 U.S. representative\n* [[Rush Wimberly]] (1873\u20131943) \u2013 politician\n* [[Stephen J. Windhorst]] (born 1957) \u2013 judge; [[State legislature (United States)|state representative]]\n* [[John D. Winters]] (1917\u20131998) \u2013 historian\n* [[Tommy Wiseau]] (born 1968) \u2013 screenwriter; director; producer; executive producer; actor\n* [[Reese Witherspoon]] (born 1976) \u2013 Academy Award-winning actress\n* [[A. Baldwin Wood]] (1879\u20131956) \u2013 inventor; engineer\n* [[Susan Ward]] (born 1976) \u2013 actress; model\n* [[Ebony Woodruff]] (born 1980) \u2013 state representative for Jefferson Parish from 2013 to 2016\n* [[Xavier Woods (American football)|Xavier Woods]] (born 1995) \u2013 safety for the [[Dallas Cowboys]]\n* [[J. Robert Wooley]] (born 1953) \u2013 politician\n* [[Orlando Woolridge]] (1959\u20132012) \u2013 NBA [[Power forward (basketball)|power forward]] for several teams\n* [[G. L. P. Wren]] (1836\u20131901) \u2013 member of both houses of the Louisiana legislature; farmer in Webster Parish\n* [[Zelma Wyche]] (1918\u20131999) \u2013 politician; [[civil rights]] activist\n\n==Y==\n* [[Andrew Young]] (born 1932) \u2013 politician and [[civil rights]] advocate\n* [[Lester Young]] (1909\u20131959) \u2013 musician\n* [[Thaddeus Young]] (born 1988) \u2013 [[small forward]] for the [[Philadelphia 76ers]]\n* [[Peter Youree]] (1843\u20131914) \u2013 [[Shreveport]] businessman\n\n==Z==\n* [[Samuel Zemurray]] (1877\u20131961) \u2013 businessman; philanthropist\n* [[Jerome Zeringue]] (born 1962) \u2013 state representative for Lafourche and Terrebonne parishes, effective 2016\n* [[Buckwheat Zydeco]] (born 1947) \u2013 musician\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Biography|Lists|United States}}\n* [[Lists of Americans]]\n* [[List of people from New Orleans, Louisiana]] \n{{clear}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Louisiana}}\n{{Lists of people by U.S. state}}\n\n[[Category:Lists of people from Louisiana| ]]\n", "name_user": "Klutzygirl33", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_people_from_Louisiana"}
{"title_page": "Mario", "text_new": "{{short description|Fictional character from Nintendo's ''Mario'' franchise and the company's mascot}}\n{{About|the Nintendo character|the franchise featuring him|Super Mario|and|Mario (franchise)|other uses|Mario (given name)|and|Mario (disambiguation)}}\n{{pp-semi-indef|small=yes}}\n{{pp-move-indef}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=November 2018}}\n{{Infobox character\n| color          = #EC7365 <!-- From the Super Mario series logo (adjusted for contrast) -->\n| name           = Mario\n| franchise      = [[Mario (franchise)|Mario]]\n| image          = MarioNSMBUDeluxe.png\n| alt            = \n| caption        = Mario, as depicted in promotional artwork of ''[[New Super Mario Bros. U Deluxe]]''\n| first    = ''[[Donkey Kong (video game)|Donkey Kong]]'' (1981)\n| last = ''[[Mario & Sonic at the Olympic Games Tokyo 2020]]'' (2019)\n| creator        = [[Shigeru Miyamoto]]\n| adapted_by     = <!-- for character adaption articles -->\n| designer       = {{Unbulleted list|Shigeru Miyamoto|[[Y\u014dichi Kotabe]]|[[Shigefumi Hino]]}}\n| portrayer      = {{Unbulleted list|[[Lou Albano]] {{small|(''The Super Mario Bros. Super Show!'')}}|[[Bob Hoskins]] {{small|(''[[Super Mario Bros. (film)|Super Mario Bros.]]'')}}|[[John Lenahan]] {{small|(''The Super Mario Challenge'')}}}}\n| voice          = {{Collapsible list|title = English\n| Ronald B. Ruben {{small|(''[[Mario Teaches Typing]]'')}}\n| Marc Graue {{small|(''[[Hotel Mario]]'')}}\n| [[Charles Martinet]] {{small|(1990\u2013present)}}\n| [[Peter Cullen]] {{small|(''[[Saturday Supercade]]'')}}\n| [[Lou Albano]] {{small|(''[[The Super Mario Bros. Super Show!]]'')}}\n| Walker Boone {{small|(''[[The Adventures of Super Mario Bros. 3]]'' and ''[[Super Mario World (TV series)|Super Mario World]]'')}}}}\n{{Collapsible list|title = Japanese\n| [[T\u014dru Furuya]] {{small|(1986\u20131988; ''[[Super Mario Bros.: The Great Mission to Rescue Princess Peach!]]'' and ''[[Amada Anime Series: Super Mario Bros.]]'')}}\n| [[Takeshi Aono]] {{small|(1992\u20131993; ''[[Mario Paint]]'' and ''[[Super Mario All-Stars]]'')}}\n| [[Nozomu Sasaki]] {{small|(''Super Mario Bros. Special'' Drama CD)}}\n| [[K\u014dsei Tomita]] {{small|(Japanese dub of ''Super Mario Bros'' film)}}}}\n| motion_actor   = \n| full_name      = Mario Mario<ref name=\"full name\">Brian. [http://nintendoeverything.com/miyamoto-says-marios-full-name-is-mario-mario/ Miyamoto says Mario\u2019s full name is \u201cMario Mario\u201d]. ''Nintendo Everything'' (September 14, 2015). Retrieved September 14 2015</ref>\n| nickname       = Super Mario\n| alias          = <!-- or |aliases= -->\n| species        = <!-- or |race=; for non-humans only -->\n| gender         = Male\n| title          = \n| occupation     = [[Plumber]]\n| affiliation    = \n| fighting_style = \n| weapon         = \n| family         = \n| spouse         = <!-- or |spouses= -->\n| significant_other  = <!-- or |significant_others= -->\n| children       = \n| relatives      = [[Luigi]] {{small|(twin brother)}}\n| religion       = \n| origin         = The [[Mushroom Kingdom]]\n| nationality    = [[Italians|Italian]]\n}}\n\n{{nihongo|'''Mario'''|\u30de\u30ea\u30aa|Mario<!-- The Japanese transliteration name \"Mario\" appears in every game, so leave the Japanese transliteration as \"Mario\". -->|{{IPA-ja|ma\u027ei.o|pron}}; {{IPAc-en|lang|\u02c8|m|\u0251\u02d0r|i|o\u028a|,_|\u02c8|m|\u00e6r|-}}, {{IPA-it|\u02c8ma\u02d0rjo|lang}}|lead=yes}} is a fictional [[character (arts)|character]] in the [[Mario (franchise)|''Mario'' video game franchise]], owned by [[Nintendo]] and created by Japanese video game designer [[Shigeru Miyamoto]]. Acting as the company's mascot, as well as being the eponymous [[protagonist]] of the series, Mario has appeared in [[List of video games featuring Mario|over 200 video games]] since his creation. Depicted as a short, pudgy, [[Italians|Italian]] [[plumber]] who resides in the [[Mushroom Kingdom]], his adventures generally center upon rescuing [[Princess Peach]] from the Koopa villain [[Bowser (character)|Bowser]]. His fraternal twin brother and sidekick is [[Luigi]].\n\nWith more than 600 million units sold worldwide, the overall ''Mario'' franchise is the [[List of best-selling video game franchises|best-selling video game franchise]] of all time.<ref name=\"History of Mario\" /><ref name=\"10 best redbull\">{{cite web | title=The 10 best-selling video game franchises ever | date=December 26, 2016 | first=Mick | last=Fraser | url=https://www.redbull.com/gb-en/10-best-selling-video-game-franchises-of-all-time | accessdate=November 6, 2018}}</ref> Outside of the ''[[Super Mario]]'' platform series, other ''Mario'' genres include the ''[[Mario Kart]]'' racing series, sports games such as the ''[[List of Mario sports games#Mario Tennis series|Mario Tennis]]'' and ''[[List of Mario sports games#Mario Golf games|Mario Golf]]'' series,  [[Role-playing video game|role-playing games]] such as ''[[Mario & Luigi]]'', ''[[Super Mario RPG]]'' and ''[[Paper Mario]]'', and [[educational game]]s such as ''[[Mario Is Missing|Mario Is Missing!]]'', ''[[Mario's Time Machine]]'' and ''[[Mario Teaches Typing]]''. The franchise has branched into several media, including television shows, film, comics, and licensed merchandise. Since 1990, Mario has been voiced by [[Charles Martinet]].\n\n==Concept and creation==\n[[File:Mario emblem.svg|150px|thumb|Seen on his hat, Mario's emblem represents him in the interfaces of many of the games in which he has appeared.]]\n\n[[Shigeru Miyamoto]] created Mario while developing ''[[Donkey Kong (video game)|Donkey Kong]]'' in an attempt to produce a best-selling video game for [[Nintendo]]; previous games, such as ''[[Sheriff (arcade game)|Sheriff]],'' had not achieved the success of games such as [[Namco|Namco's]] ''[[Pac-Man]]''. Originally, Miyamoto wanted to create a game that used the characters [[Popeye]], [[Bluto]], and [[Olive Oyl]].<ref name=\"ign\" /> At the time, however, Miyamoto was unable to acquire a license to use the characters (and would not until 1982 with ''[[Popeye (video game)|Popeye]]''), so he ended up making an unnamed player character, [[Donkey Kong (character)|Donkey Kong]], and [[Pauline (Nintendo)|Lady]] (later known as Pauline).<ref name=\"ign\" /> In the early stages of ''Donkey Kong'', Mario was unable to jump, and the focus was to escape a maze. However, Miyamoto enabled Mario to jump, saying \"If you had a barrel rolling towards you, what would you do?\"<ref name=\"wired\">{{cite magazine|url=https://www.wired.com/gaming/gamingreviews/multimedia/2007/05/gallery_game_history?slide=18 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081020153928/http://www.wired.com/gaming/gamingreviews/multimedia/2007/05/gallery_game_history?slide=18 |url-status=dead |archive-date=October 20, 2008 |title=Console Portraits: A 40-Year Pictorial History of Gaming |magazine=[[Wired News]] |author=Orlando, Greg |accessdate=August 23, 2008 |date=May 15, 2007 }}</ref><ref name=\"wii-com1\">{{cite web |url=http://iwataasks.nintendo.com/interviews/#/wii/nsmb/0/0 |title=Iwata Asks: New Super Mario Bros. |work=Wii.com |publisher=[[Nintendo]] |accessdate=June 24, 2013 |page=1}}</ref>\n\nWhile the protagonist was unnamed in the Japanese release, he was named '''Jumpman''' in the game's English instructions<ref>{{cite magazine|last=|first= |title=Mario: Alive, Well, and Living in the Bronx?|magazine=[[Next Generation (magazine)|Next Generation]] |issue=26|publisher=[[Imagine Media]]|date=February 1997|page=46}}</ref> and '''Mario''' in the sales brochure.<ref name=tafa_dkusflyer>{{cite web|url=http://flyers.arcade-museum.com/?page=thumbs&db=videodb&id=316|title=Donkey Kong|website=The Arcade Flyers Archive}}</ref> Miyamoto originally named the character \"Mr. Video\", and he was to be used in every video game Miyamoto developed.<ref name=\"yahoo\">{{cite web|url=http://videogames.yahoo.com/events/playback/playback-93/1378336|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091211223939/http://videogames.yahoo.com/events/playback/playback-93/1378336|archivedate=December 11, 2009|title=Playback 93|date=December 2, 2009|publisher=Yahoo|accessdate=December 24, 2009}}</ref> According to a widely circulated story, during localization of ''Donkey Kong'' for American audiences, Nintendo of America's warehouse landlord [[Mario Segale]] confronted then-president [[Minoru Arakawa]], demanding back rent. Following a heated argument in which the Nintendo employees eventually convinced Segale he would be paid, they opted to name the character in the game Mario after him.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://technologizer.com/2010/04/25/mario/|title= The True Face of Mario |last= Edwards |first= Benj |date= April 25, 2010|work= [[Technologizer]] |accessdate=June 30, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title= Powerful Segale family has massive vision for Tukwila expanse |author= Eric Pryne |url= http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/businesstechnology/2011460764_segale28.html |newspaper= [[The Seattle Times]] |date= March 27, 2010 |accessdate=June 30, 2011}}</ref>\n\nMiyamoto commented that if he had named Mario \"Mr. Video\", Mario likely would have \"disappeared off the face of the Earth\".<ref name=\"wii-com1\"/> By Miyamoto's own account, Mario's profession was chosen to fit with the game design. Since ''Donkey Kong'' was set on a construction site, Mario was made into a carpenter. When he appeared again in ''[[Mario Bros.]]'', it was decided he should be a plumber, since a lot of the game is played in underground settings.<ref name=\"usatoday\">{{cite news|url=http://content.usatoday.com/communities/gamehunters/post/2010/11/qa-mario-creator-shigeru-miyamoto/1|title=Q&A: 'Mario' creator Shigeru Miyamoto|date=November 8, 2010|accessdate=November 9, 2010|author=Mike Snider|work=[[USA Today]]}}</ref> Mario's character design, particularly his large nose, draws on western influences; once he became a plumber, Miyamoto decided to \"put him in [[New York City|New York]]\" and make him Italian,<ref name=\"usatoday\" /> lightheartedly attributing Mario's nationality to his mustache.<ref name=\"IGN Miyamoto Interview\">{{cite web|last=Kohler|first=Chris|title=Q&A: 90 Minutes With Miyamoto, Nintendo\u2019s Master of Amusement|url=https://www.wired.com/gamelife/2008/06/interview-90-mi/|website=IGN.com|accessdate=July 30, 2010|date=June 27, 2008}}</ref> Other sources have Mario's profession chosen to be carpenter in an effort to depict the character as an ordinary hard worker, and make it easier for players to identify with him.<ref name=\"mariomania\">[[Minoru Arakawa|Arakawa, Minoru]] (1991). Mario Mania. Nintendo. pp. 30\u201332. [[ASIN]] B000BPL42C.</ref> After a colleague suggested that Mario more closely resembled a plumber, Miyamoto changed Mario's profession accordingly and developed ''Mario Bros.'',<ref name=\"ign\" /> featuring the character in the sewers of New York City.<ref>Grajqevci, Jeton (October 9, 2000). [http://www.n-sider.com/contentview.php?contentid=223 Profile: Shigeru Miyamoto]. N-Sider. Retrieved May 6, 2009</ref>\n\nDue to the graphical limitations of arcade hardware at the time, Miyamoto clothed the character in red overalls and a blue shirt to contrast against each other and the background. A red cap was added to let Miyamoto avoid drawing the character's hairstyle, forehead, and eyebrows, as well as to circumvent the issue of animating his hair as he jumped.<ref name=\"ign\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2010/09/14/ign-presents-the-history-of-super-mario-bros|title=IGN Presents: The History of Super Mario Bros.|author=McLaughlin, Rus|date=September 13, 2010|website=IGN|accessdate=June 24, 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"usatoday\" /> To give distinctly human facial features on an 8\u00d78 pixel head, Miyamoto drew a large nose and a mustache, which avoided the need to draw a mouth and facial expressions.<ref name=\"CNN\">Rao, Anjali (February 15, 2007). [http://www.cnn.com/2007/WORLD/asiapcf/02/14/miyamoto.script/index.html Sigeru Miyamao Talk Asia interview]. [[CNN]]. Retrieved February 28, 2009</ref>\n\nMiyamoto envisioned a \"go to\" character that could be put into any game as needed, albeit in cameo appearances, as at the time Miyamoto was not expecting the character to become singularly popular.<ref name=\"yahoo\"/> To this end, he originally called the character \"Mr. Video\", comparing his intent for appearances in later games to the cameos that [[Alfred Hitchcock]] had done within his films.<ref name=\"wii-com2\">{{cite web |url=http://iwataasks.nintendo.com/interviews/#/wii/nsmb/0/1 |title=Iwata Asks: New Super Mario Bros. |work=Wii.com |publisher=[[Nintendo]] |accessdate=June 24, 2013 |page=2}}</ref> Over time, Mario's appearance has become more defined; blue eyes, white gloves, brown shoes, a red \"M\" in a white circle on the front of his hat and gold buttons on his overalls have been added. The colors of his shirt and overalls were also reversed from a blue shirt with red overalls to a red shirt with blue overalls. Miyamoto attributed this process to the different development teams and artists for each game as well as advances in technology.<ref name=\"mariomania\" />\n\n==Appearances==\n{{main|List of Mario video games}}\n\n===1981\u20131990===\n[[File:SMB Supermario.png|thumb|Mario's idle [[Sprite (computer graphics)|sprite]] from ''[[Super Mario Bros.]]'' (1985).]]\n[[File:MarioSMBWalk.gif|thumb|Mario's walking sprite animation from ''Super Mario Bros.'' (1985).]]\n\nMario debuted as \"Jumpman\" in the arcade game ''[[Donkey Kong (video game)|Donkey Kong]]'' on July 9, 1981.<ref>{{cite journal |title=Retro Diary |journal=[[Retro Gamer]] |issue=104 |date=July 2012 |page=13 |issn=1742-3155 |oclc=489477015}}</ref> He is shown to be a carpenter and has a pet ape called Donkey Kong.<ref name=\"Kohler 39\">{{cite book |title=Power-Up: How Japanese Video Games Gave the World an Extra Life |last=Kohler |first=Chris |year=2005 |publisher=Brady Games |isbn=978-0-7440-0424-3 |page=39 }}</ref> The carpenter mistreats the ape and [[Donkey Kong (character)|Donkey Kong]] escapes to kidnap Jumpman's girlfriend, originally known as the Lady, but later named [[Recurring characters in the Mario series#Pauline|Pauline]]. The player must take the role of Jumpman and rescue the girl.\n\nJumpman was later renamed \"Mario\" in the 1982 arcade game ''[[Donkey Kong Jr.|Donkey Kong Junior]]'', the only game in which he has been portrayed as an antagonist. In the 1983 arcade game ''[[Mario Bros.]]'', Mario and his younger brother [[Luigi]] are portrayed as [[Italian-American]]<ref name=\"usatoday\" /> plumbers<ref name=\"mbvc\">{{cite web |title=Mario Bros. at Nintendo \u2013 Wii \u2013 Virtual Console |url=https://www.nintendo.com/games/detail/AN20FWaWbXNL-oWwUHwK0sMxrfq_plpD |publisher=[[Nintendo]] |accessdate=June 24, 2013 |website= |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181016175051/https://www.nintendo.com/games/detail/AN20FWaWbXNL-oWwUHwK0sMxrfq_plpD |archive-date=October 16, 2018 |url-status=dead }}</ref> who have to defeat creatures that have been coming from the sewers below [[New York City]].\n\nIn ''[[Super Mario Bros.]]'' for the [[Nintendo Entertainment System]], Mario saves [[Princess Peach|Princess Toadstool]] (later known as Princess Peach) of the [[Mushroom Kingdom]] from [[Bowser (character)|King Koopa]].<ref name=\"Booklet 7\">{{cite book| title = Super Mario Bros. Instruction Booklet| section = | publisher = [[Nintendo|Nintendo of America]]| year = 1986}}</ref> To save Princess Toadstool, Mario conquers the eight worlds of the Mushroom Kingdom by going to the castle in each to defeat a minion of King Koopa. To reach each castle, Mario battles through three sub-worlds by defeating King Koopa's henchmen. If Mario successfully fights his way through the castle and defeats the minion, he frees a [[Toad (Nintendo)|Mushroom Retainer]].{{citation needed|date=April 2018}} Inside the eighth castle, Mario has a final fight with King Koopa and frees Princess Toadstool. In ''[[Super Mario Bros. 2]]'', the player can choose between Mario, [[Luigi]], [[Toad (Nintendo)|Toad]], or [[Princess Peach]]. Each character possesses unique abilities (Luigi has stronger jumping ability, Toad can dig the fastest, and Peach can float), with Mario being the most well-rounded. In ''[[Super Mario Bros. 3]]'', Mario quests to save the rulers of seven kingdoms from [[Bowser (character)|Bowser]] and his children, the [[Koopalings]], and Mario travels across eight worlds to restore order to the Mushroom World and to rescue Princess Peach.<ref name=\"Manual-2\">{{cite book| title = Super Mario Bros. 3 Instruction Booklet| section = The Eight Kingdoms| publisher = [[Nintendo|Nintendo of America]]| date = February 12, 1990}}</ref> Mario is introduced to new [[power-up]]s that augment his abilities.<ref>{{cite journal| journal = [[Nintendo Power]]| title = Super Mario Bros. 3: Strategy Guide on the Way| issue = 12|date=May\u2013June 1990| pages = 94\u201395}}</ref>\n\n===1989\u20131995===\nIn ''[[Super Mario Land]]'', an alien named Tatanga appears, hypnotizes the inhabitants of an area called Sarasaland, and kidnaps its ruler, [[Princess Daisy (Nintendo)|Princess Daisy]]. Mario sets out to rescue her, traveling through the four geographical areas of Sarasaland and defeating Tatanga's minions along the way. He corners Tatanga in the skies of the Chai kingdom, bringing down the alien warship and rescuing Daisy.<ref>{{cite book | author=Nintendo | year=1989 | title=Super Mario Land Instruction Booklet | publisher=Nintendo of America, Inc. }}</ref> In ''[[Super Mario World]]'', Mario and Luigi take [[Princess Peach]] for a vacation in Dinosaur World sometime after the events of ''[[Super Mario Bros. 3]]''; during the vacation, Peach is kidnapped by [[Bowser (character)|Bowser]]. Mario and Luigi meet the [[Yoshi]]s, dinosaurs that live in Dinosaur World, and they help rescue Peach by allowing Mario and Luigi to ride them.<ref name=\"booklet\">{{cite book|title=Super Mario World Instruction Booklet|publisher=Nintendo}}</ref>\n\nIn ''[[Super Mario Land 2: 6 Golden Coins]]'', whose events take place immediately after the original ''Super Mario Land'', Mario's evil counterpart [[Wario]] has put an evil spell over Mario Land while Mario was away in Sarasaland, renaming the area Wario Land. The inhabitants are brainwashed into thinking that Wario is their master and Mario is their enemy. Wario's motive behind this sudden attack was to take control over Mario's castle in order to have one of his own. To stop Wario, Mario finds the 6 Golden Coins throughout Mario Land and regains access to his castle. In ''[[Super Mario World 2: Yoshi's Island]]'', a [[stork]] carries Baby Mario and Baby Luigi across the sea, but the evil Magikoopa [[Kamek]] steals Baby Luigi, and Baby Mario falls onto an island called Yoshi's Island, home to Yoshis. After Mario meets the Yoshis, the group journeys through the game's six worlds to rescue Baby Luigi and the stork from Baby Bowser and Kamek.\n\n===1996\u20132002===\n[[File:Mario64 - Dire Dire Docks.png|thumb|''[[Super Mario 64]]'' (1996) featured Mario's first [[3D computer graphics|3D]] rendering.]]\n\nMario made his [[3D computer graphics|3D]] debut in ''[[Super Mario 64]]'' for the [[Nintendo 64]].<ref>{{cite web| title = FEATURE: Galaxy Quest| work = [[Edge (magazine)|Edge]]| date = September 25, 2007| url = http://www.next-gen.biz/features/feature-galaxy-quest| archive-url = https://archive.today/20120908022305/http://www.next-gen.biz/features/feature-galaxy-quest| url-status = dead| archive-date = September 8, 2012| accessdate = February 16, 2010}}</ref> [[Princess Peach]] sends Mario a letter inviting him to join her at her castle for cake;<ref>Princess Peach's note: Dear Mario: Please come to the castle. I've baked a cake for you. Yours truly-- Princess Toadstool, Peach {{cite video game| title = Super Mario 64| developer = [[Nintendo EAD]]| publisher = Nintendo | date= September 29, 1996| platform= Nintendo 64}}</ref> however, when he arrives, Mario discovers that [[Bowser (character)|Bowser]] has invaded the castle and imprisoned the princess and her servants within it using the castle's 120 Power Stars. Many of the castle's paintings are portals to other worlds, in which Bowser's minions guard the stars. Mario explores the castle and other worlds to recover the stars. He gains access to more painting portals as he recovers more stars,<ref name=\"NP88\">{{Cite journal| date= September 1996| title= Full Coverage&nbsp;\u2014 Super Mario 64| journal= [[Nintendo Power]]| issue= 88| pages= 14\u201323}}</ref> and he traverses three obstacle courses that lead him to battles with Bowser. Defeating Bowser the first two times earns Mario keys that open new levels of the castle,<ref name=\"playersguide\"/> while the final battle releases Peach, who rewards Mario by baking the cake that she promised him.<ref name=\"playersguide\">{{cite book|year=1996|title=Official Super Mario 64 Player's Guide|publisher=Nintendo}}</ref><ref name=\"instructions\">{{cite book| year=1996|title=Super Mario 64 Instruction Booklet| publisher=Nintendo| id=NUS-NSME-USA}}</ref>\n\nIn ''[[Super Mario Sunshine]]'', Mario, [[Toadsworth]], and [[Princess Peach]] take a vacation to Isle Delfino, a [[tropical island]]. A person resembling Mario, known as \"Shadow Mario\", vandalizes and pollutes the entire island using a magic [[paintbrush]]. The vandalism has caused the Shine Sprites to flee from the island's main city, Delfino Plaza, and blanket the island in darkness. Blamed for the mess, Mario is arrested by the island authorities and ordered to clean up Isle Delfino. Mario is equipped with FLUDD, a robotic [[Hose|hosing]] device invented by [[Professor E. Gadd]], which he uses to clean up the pollution and collect the Shine Sprites.<ref>{{cite book|year=2002 |title=Super Mario Sunshine instruction booklet |publisher=Nintendo |pages=20\u201323}}</ref> Meanwhile, Peach is kidnapped by Shadow Mario, who reveals himself to be [[Bowser Jr.]], one of Bowser's children, having stolen the paintbrush from Professor E. Gadd. Mario eventually confronts Bowser and Bowser Jr. and rescues the princess. With the island cleaned up, Mario and Peach begin their vacation.<ref>{{cite video game|quote=FLUDD: The vacation starts now! |title=Super Mario Sunshine |developer=Nintendo EAD |publisher=Nintendo |date=August 26, 2002 |platform=Nintendo GameCube}}</ref>\n\n===2006\u2013present===\nMario went to [[2.5D]] in ''[[New Super Mario Bros.]]'' While Mario and Peach take a walk together through the Mushroom Kingdom, [[Bowser Jr.]] kidnaps Peach and flees.<ref name=manual>{{cite book|title=New Super Mario Bros. manual|publisher=Nintendo|page=10|date=May 16, 2006}}</ref> Mario gives chase, venturing through eight worlds. Mario eventually catches up, defeating both Bowser and Bowser Jr. and rescuing Peach.<ref name=game>{{cite video game|title=New Super Mario Bros|developer=Nintendo EAD|publisher=Nintendo|platform=Nintendo DS|date=May 15, 2006 }}</ref> In ''[[Super Mario Galaxy]]'', Mario is invited by Princess Peach to the [[centennial]] Star Festival in the [[Mushroom Kingdom]].<ref>{{cite book| title = Super Mario Galaxy Instruction Booklet| section = Prologue | publisher = [[Nintendo|Nintendo of America]]| year = 2007}}</ref> Upon arrival, [[Bowser (character)|Bowser]] invades the kingdom and rips Peach's castle from its foundations and lifts it into [[outer space]]. After failing to prevent the princess from being kidnapped, Mario meets star-like creatures called Lumas and their companion, [[Rosalina (Mario)|Rosalina]]. Rosalina tells Mario that Bowser has stolen the Power Stars, the source of power for Rosalina's mobile [[observatory]], and has taken Peach to the center of the universe. Mario then travels to various [[galaxies]] to reclaim the Power Stars to restore power to the observatory and reclaim Princess Peach.<ref>{{cite web| last = Casamassina| first = Matt| title = Super Mario Galaxy Review| website = IGN| date = November 7, 2007| url = http://wii.ign.com/articles/833/833298p1.html| pages= 1\u20132| accessdate = January 25, 2009}}</ref>\n\nIn ''[[New Super Mario Bros. Wii]]'', another [[2.5D]] game, Mario, Luigi, and two Toads are attending Princess Peach's birthday party when Bowser Jr. and the other seven [[Koopaling]]s ambush the princess and kidnap her. Mario, Luigi, and the two Toads chase after them across eight worlds, defeating each Koopaling as they progress. The quartet eventually confronts Bowser, defeating him and saving the princess.<ref>{{cite magazine|title=New Super Mario Bros. Wii: Your Questions Answered! |magazine=[[Official Nintendo Magazine]] |url=http://www.officialnintendomagazine.co.uk/article.php?id=12629 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091025102607/http://www.officialnintendomagazine.co.uk/article.php?id=12629 |url-status=dead |archive-date=October 25, 2009 |date=October 23, 2009 |accessdate=November 11, 2009 }}</ref> In ''[[Super Mario Galaxy 2]]'', Bowser, who has transformed himself into a giant using the Power Stars, attacks the Mushroom Kingdom and abducts Peach, taking her to the center of the universe. With the help of the Lumas, Mario pilots Starship Mario, a mobile planet in the shape of his head, in order to travel to various galaxies and gather the Power Stars, used to fuel the ship. After multiple battles against both Bowser and Bowser Jr., Mario eventually arrives at Bowser's lair at the center of the universe, where he defeats him and rescues the princess.<ref>{{cite web|author=Matt Wales |url=http://uk.wii.ign.com/articles/109/1096123p1.html |title=Super Mario Galaxy 2 \u2013 Wii Review |publisher=Uk.wii.ign.com |date=June 10, 2010 |accessdate=August 20, 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn 2012, Mario returned in ''[[New Super Mario Bros. 2]]'' where he collects several coins scattered across the Mushroom Kingdom in addition to saving Princess Peach from the evil clutches of Bowser and the Koopalings. Mario returns to defeat Bowser and his minions in ''[[New Super Mario Bros. U]]''. Mario is one of the playable characters in ''[[Super Mario 3D World]]'', where he has average running speed and jump height compared to other characters. Mario is the protagonist of the [[Nintendo Switch]] game ''[[Super Mario Odyssey]]'', where the character Cappy replaces Mario's traditional hat, allowing Mario to throw it like a long-range weapon, and \"capture\" enemies to gain their abilities.\n\n===Other ''Mario'' games===\n''Mario'' games of other genres include various ''[[Game & Watch]]'' games; ''[[Mario Pinball Land]]'', a [[pinball]] game for the Game Boy Advance;<ref>{{cite web| last = Byron| first = Tom| title = Mario Pinball Land (Game Boy Advance)| website = [[1UP.com]]| date = November 20, 2004| url = http://www.1up.com/do/reviewPage?cId=3147289&p=19| archive-url = https://archive.today/20120723155031/http://www.1up.com/do/reviewPage?cId=3147289&p=19| url-status = dead| archive-date = July 23, 2012| accessdate = January 25, 2010}}</ref> various educational games; and the ''[[Dr. Mario (video game)|Dr. Mario]]'' [[puzzle video game]], (with ''Dr. Mario'' itself first released in 1990).<ref name=\"drmario\" /> In these games, Dr. Mario throws [[vitamins]] that the player must align to destroy the [[viruses]] that populate the playing field.<ref name=\"drmario\">{{cite web| title = Dr. Mario| website = IGN| url = http://cheats.ign.com/objects/007/007157.html| accessdate = January 24, 2010}}</ref> 1996's ''[[Super Mario RPG]]'' is the first ''Mario'' [[role-playing game]];<ref>{{cite magazine|last=East |first=Tom |title=Virtual Console Review: Super Mario RPG |magazine=[[Official Nintendo Magazine]] |date=September 19, 2008 |url=http://www.officialnintendomagazine.co.uk/5883/reviews/super-mario-rpg-review/ |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110518115539/http://www.officialnintendomagazine.co.uk/5883/reviews/super-mario-rpg-review/ |url-status=dead |archive-date=May 18, 2011 |accessdate=February 17, 2010 }}</ref> ten games have followed, including five in the ''[[List of Mario role-playing games|Paper Mario]]'' series (''[[Paper Mario]]'' for the Nintendo 64, ''[[Paper Mario: The Thousand-Year Door]]'' for the GameCube, ''[[Super Paper Mario]]'' for the Wii, ''[[Paper Mario: Sticker Star]]'' for the Nintendo 3DS, and ''[[Paper Mario: Color Splash]]'' for the Wii U) and six in the ''[[List of Mario role-playing games|Mario & Luigi]]'' series (''[[Mario & Luigi: Superstar Saga]]'' for the Game Boy Advance, ''[[Mario & Luigi: Partners in Time]]'' and ''[[Mario & Luigi: Bowser's Inside Story]]'' for the Nintendo DS, ''[[Mario & Luigi: Dream Team]]'', ''[[Mario & Luigi: Paper Jam]]'', and [[Mario & Luigi: Superstar Saga|''Mario & Luigi: Superstar Saga + Bowser's Minions'']] for the Nintendo 3DS).\n\nSeveral other sub-series of ''Mario'' video games, especially those inspired from [[sports]], have been released. The ''[[Mario Kart]]'' franchise, which began with ''[[Super Mario Kart]]'' for the Super Nintendo Entertainment System in 1992, is the most successful and longest-running [[kart racing]] franchise.<ref name=\"Sutra M#1\">{{cite web | last = Jenkins | first = David | title = Mario Tops Best Selling Game Franchise List | website = [[Gamasutra]] | date = January 10, 2007 | url = http://www.gamasutra.com/php-bin/news_index.php?story=12349 | accessdate = January 1, 2009}}</ref> Other ''Mario'' sports games include the [[Camelot Software Planning|Camelot]]-developed series ''[[Mario Golf]]'' and ''[[Mario Tennis]]'', and, respectively, the [[baseball]] and [[soccer]] games ''[[Mario Superstar Baseball]]'' and ''[[Super Mario Strikers]]''. In 1999, [[Hudson Soft]] developed the ''[[Mario Party]]'' series, which began on the Nintendo 64. The games revolve around a set of [[minigames]] and are playable with up to four players.\n\n''[[Mario & Sonic at the Olympic Games]]'', released for both Nintendo DS and Wii, is a collection of 24 events based on the [[2008 Summer Olympic Games]] from [[Beijing]], in which characters from [[Sega]]'s [[Sonic the Hedgehog|''Sonic the Hedgehog'' series]] compete with ''Mario'' characters. This was followed in 2009 by ''[[Mario & Sonic at the Olympic Winter Games]]'' on both systems, based on the [[2010 Winter Olympics]] in [[Vancouver]]. Two more sports games for the Wii were released in 2011, ''[[Mario Sports Mix]]'' and the third ''Mario & Sonic'' game, ''[[Mario & Sonic at the London 2012 Olympic Games]]'' while the latter was released for the [[Nintendo 3DS]] in February 2012, which is based on the [[2012 Summer Olympics]] in [[London]]. The fourth edition of the ''Mario & Sonic'' series for the [[Wii U]] is called ''[[Mario & Sonic at the Sochi 2014 Olympic Winter Games]]'', which is based on the [[2014 Winter Olympics]] in [[Sochi]]. A fifth game, ''[[Mario & Sonic at the Rio 2016 Olympic Games]]'', based on the [[2016 Summer Olympics]] in [[Rio de Janeiro]], was released in 2016 for the [[Nintendo 3DS]], [[Wii U]] and [[Arcade game|Arcade]].\n\n===In other media===\n[[File:Mario SSBU.png|thumb|Artwork of Mario from ''[[Super Smash Bros. Ultimate]]''.]]\nApart from his platformer and spin-off game appearances, Mario has made guest appearances in non-''Mario'' games, such as ''[[Punch-Out!! (NES)|Mike Tyson's Punch-Out!!]]'', where Mario is a [[referee]].<ref>{{cite web| last = Pigna| first = Kris| title = Mario Included in NES Punch-Out!! Without Miyamoto's Permission| website = [[1UP.com]]| date = August 9, 2009| url = http://www.1up.com/do/newsStory?cId=3175501| archive-url = https://archive.today/20120718043018/http://www.1up.com/do/newsStory?cId=3175501| url-status = dead| archive-date = July 18, 2012| accessdate = January 28, 2009}}</ref> Mario appears as a playable character in ''[[NBA Street V3]]''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gamespot.com/news/2005/01/05/news_6115715.html |archive-url=http://web.archive.bibalex.org/web/20050112112705/http://www.gamespot.com/news/2005/01/05/news_6115715.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=January 12, 2005 |title=Mario to hoop it up in NBA Street V3 |website=GameSpot |accessdate=May 4, 2009 }}</ref> and ''[[SSX on Tour]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gamespot.com/gamecube/sports/ssx4/news.html?sid=6132098&mode=previews |title=SSX On Tour Character Spotlight: Mario, Luigi, and Peach |website=GameSpot |accessdate=May 4, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060114224521/http://www.gamespot.com/gamecube/sports/ssx4/news.html?sid=6132098 |archivedate=January 14, 2006 }}</ref> He makes countless cameo appearances in many forms in many games, such as portraits and statues in ''[[The Legend of Zelda: A Link to the Past]]'', ''[[The Legend of Zelda: Ocarina of Time]]'', and ''[[Metal Gear Solid: The Twin Snakes]]''.<ref>{{cite web| url = http://mentalfloss.com/article/553600/nintendo-fans-mispronouncing-nes | title=9 Hidden Mario Cameos and References in Videogames | last=Obias | first=Rubie | access-date = August 8, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Television===\nThe first appearance of Mario in media other than games was ''[[Saturday Supercade]]'', an animated television series produced by Ruby-Spears Productions in 1983. Each episode was composed of several shorter segments featuring video game characters from the golden age of video arcade games. Mario (voiced by [[Peter Cullen]]) appeared in Donkey Kong segments where he and Pauline tried to recapture Donkey Kong.\n\nMario stars in ''[[The Super Mario Bros. Super Show!]]'', played by [[Lou Albano|\"Captain\" Lou Albano]].\n\nMario stars in ''[[The Adventures of Super Mario Bros. 3]]'' and ''[[Super Mario World (TV series)|Super Mario World]]'', voiced by Walker Boone.\n\n===Film===\nMario appears in the [[live-action]] film ''[[Super Mario Bros. (film)|Super Mario Bros.]]'' as played by [[Bob Hoskins]]. Mario finds himself in an alternate universe in which dinosaurs rule where he must save the Earth from invasion. The film was a commercial failure at the box office.<ref>{{cite web|title=At the Movies:Super Mario Bros. |url=http://bventertainment.go.com/tv/buenavista/ebertandroeper/index2.html?sec=6&subsec=Super+Mario+Bros. |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5mr94yVaA?url=http://bventertainment.go.com/tv/buenavista/ebertandroeper/index2.html?sec=6 |archivedate=January 17, 2010 |accessdate=January 25, 2010 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nOutside the original games, television shows, and film, Mario has influenced the creation of a line of licensed merchandise and has appeared in popular culture. The Nintendo Comics System series, along with the [[Nintendo Adventure Books]], were created due to Mario as well.{{citation needed|date=October 2014|reason=Nintendo Adventure Books article does not correlate this.}}\n\n===Theme parks===\nMario will appear at [[Universal Studios Japan]] in [[Osaka]] in the upcoming section of [[Super Nintendo World]], which is scheduled to open in 2020 in time of the [[2020 Summer Olympics]] in [[Tokyo]]. One of the rides will be themed to ''[[Mario Kart]]''. [[Universal Parks & Resorts]] also has plans to import Super Nintendo World to [[Universal Studios Hollywood]] in [[Los Angeles|Los Angeles, California]] and [[Universal Orlando]] Resort in [[Orlando, Florida]].\n\n==Characteristics==\nMario is depicted as a portly plumber who lives in the fictional land of the [[Mushroom Kingdom]] with [[Luigi]], his younger, taller brother.<ref name=\"ign\" /><ref name=\"mariobioign\"/><ref name=\"luigibioign\">{{cite web| title = Luigi Biography| website = IGN| url = http://stars.ign.com/objects/924/924288_biography.html| accessdate = January 26, 2010| url-status = dead| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20090817041854/http://stars.ign.com/objects/924/924288_biography.html| archivedate = August 17, 2009}}</ref> In the television series and film, Mario and Luigi are originally from [[Brooklyn|Brooklyn, New York]].<ref name=\"mariobioign\"/> Little is known of Mario's childhood, though the infant version of Mario, Baby Mario, first appeared in 1995 in ''[[Super Mario World 2: Yoshi's Island]]'', and has often appeared in Nintendo sports games since then. Baby Mario has a major role along with [[Luigi|Baby Luigi]] in ''[[Mario & Luigi: Partners in Time]]'' and appears in ''[[Yoshi's Island DS]]''. He, along with the adult Mario, is voiced by [[Charles Martinet]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Charles Martinet: Voice Over|url=http://www.charlesmartinet.com/voiceover.html|accessdate=March 16, 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Savage|first1=Mark|title=The actors hiding inside your video games|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/entertainment-arts-19664003|accessdate=July 3, 2017|work=BBC News}}</ref>\n\nHe wears a longsleeved red shirt, a pair of blue overalls with yellow buttons, brown shoes, white gloves and a red cap with a red \"M\" printed on a white circle. In ''[[Donkey Kong (video game)|Donkey Kong]]'', he wore a pair of red overalls, and a blue shirt. In ''[[Super Mario Bros.]]'', he wore a brown shirt with red overalls. He has blue eyes, and, like [[Luigi]], has brown hair, and a dark brown or black mustache. This consistent difference in color is attributed to being a relic from designing the characters for their original platforms, wherein certain features were actively distinguished while others had to be curtailed due to technical limitations.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://archive.beefjack.com/index.html?p=148496.html|title=BeefJack \u2013 An alternative gaming website \u2013 Video game news, reviews and features, from a different perspective.|website=archive.beefjack.com|access-date=November 2, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171107021606/http://archive.beefjack.com/index.html?p=148496.html|archive-date=November 7, 2017|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In a 2005 interview, Miyamoto stated that Mario's physical age was about 24\u201325 years old.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Mendelsohn |first1=Tom |title=Mario is only 24 years old, according to creator Shigeru Miyamoto |url=https://arstechnica.com/gaming/2016/09/mario-24-years-old/ |accessdate=August 6, 2018 |work=Ars Technica |date=September 30, 2016 |language=en-us}}</ref>\n\n=== Surname ===\nNintendo did not initially reveal Mario's full name. In a 1989 interview, his full name was stated not to be \"Mario Mario\" though it may be inferred from the title of the ''Mario Bros.'' series.<ref>{{cite episode |title=Inside Super Mario Bros |series=[[Inside Edition]] |first=Joel |last=Loy |network=[[CBS Television Distribution]] |airdate=1989}}</ref> The first notable use of \"Mario Mario\" is in the [[Super Mario Bros. (film)|1993 live-action film adaptation]]. This was again used in two of [[Prima Games|Prima]]'s official strategy guides, in 2000<ref>{{cite book |title=Mario Party 2: Prima's Official Strategy Guide |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=_XFa3rPUvSMC |date=2000|isbn=9780761527671 |last1=Tica |first1=Don |last2=Govia |first2=Mario De |last3=Pham |first3=Tri }}</ref> for ''[[Mario Party 2]]'' and in 2003<ref>{{cite book |title=Mario & Luigi: Superstar Saga : Prima's Official Strategy Guide |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=8bpFw-oJTqgC |date=2003 |page=21|isbn=9780761544234 |last1=Stratton |first1=Stephen |last2=Buchanan |first2=Levi }}</ref> for ''[[Mario and Luigi: Superstar Saga]]''. In 2012, after [[Charles Martinet]] voiced Mario declaring himself \"Mario Mario\" at the [[San Diego Comic-Con]],<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=AAjhjLuWbC8&t=1m15s |title=Mario reveals his last name & other tales \u2013 San Diego Comic Con 2012 |date=July 16, 2012 |quote=What's my last name? That's a very good question. That's right, it's Mario! My name's-a Mario Mario. Of course, my brother's name, a-Luigi Mario. And of course, my mama's-a Mama Mia Mario; my papa Papa Pio Mario. Of course, my grandmama Grandmama Mia Mario and my greatpapa et cetera, et cetera. Yeah, first name Mario, last name Mario. Yahoo!}}</ref> the next month [[Satoru Iwata]] said he had no last name,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://kotaku.com/5935721/super-marios-boss-doesnt-want-to-overdo-it-with-mr-video-game-and-wont-deceive-you-with-dlc |title=Nintendo Chief: Mario Is Part Of Gamers' DNA |date=August 17, 2012 |quote=Could that mean that Mario's last name is \"Video Game\"? No, Iwata replied. \"He does not have a last name.\"}}</ref> which [[Shigeru Miyamoto]] agreed with the month after.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gameinformer.com/b/features/archive/2012/09/24/miyamoto-tezuka-interview.aspx |title=Mario's Creators Answer Burning Questions About The Series |date=September 24, 2012 |access-date=December 20, 2017 |archive-url=https://archive.today/20130123161706/http://www.gameinformer.com/b/features/archive/2012/09/24/miyamoto-tezuka-interview.aspx |archive-date=January 23, 2013 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Two months after Iwata's death in July 2015, Miyamoto changed his stance September 2015 at the Super Mario Bros. 30th Anniversary festival, asserting that his name was indeed Mario Mario.<ref name=\"getnews.jp\">{{cite web |url=http://getnews.jp/archives/1144379 |date=September 14, 2015 |language=Japanese |title=\u3010\u885d\u6483\u4e8b\u5b9f\u3011\u3064\u3044\u306b\u4efb\u5929\u5802\u516c\u5f0f\u306e\u30de\u30ea\u30aa\u306e\u672c\u540d\u304c\u5224\u660e\uff01\u4efb\u5929\u5802\u306e\u4ee3\u8868\u53d6\u7de0\u5f79\u30fb\u5bae\u672c\u8302\u6c0f\u304c\u660e\u304b\u3059 |trans-title=[Impact] fact finally found real name of Nintendo official of Mario! Reveal the representative director, Shigeru Miyamoto of Nintendo}}</ref><ref name=\"nintendoeverything.com\">{{cite web |url=http://nintendoeverything.com/miyamoto-says-marios-full-name-is-mario-mario/ |title=Miyamoto says Mario's full name is \"Mario Mario\" |date=September 14, 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Occupation and hobbies===\nMario's occupation is plumbing, though in the original ''[[Donkey Kong (series)|Donkey Kong]]'' games he is a [[carpenter]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nintendo.co.uk/Corporate/Nintendo-History/Nintendo-History-625945.html|title=History of Nintendo Worldwide 1980\u20131990|publisher=[[Nintendo of Europe]]|year=2013|accessdate=June 24, 2013}}</ref> Mario has had several other occupations: in the ''[[Dr. Mario (video game)|Dr. Mario]]'' series of [[puzzle video game|puzzle games]], which debuted in 1990,<ref name=\"drmario\" /> Mario is portrayed as a medical physician named \"Dr. Mario\";<ref>{{cite web| title = Top Ten Mario Games| publisher = [[GameTrailers]]| date = July 24, 2007| url = http://www.gametrailers.com/video/top-ten-screwattack/22754| accessdate = January 30, 2010}}</ref> in the [[Game Boy]] game ''[[Mario's Picross]]'', Mario is an [[Archaeology|archaeologist]]; and in ''[[Mario vs. Donkey Kong 2: March of the Minis]]'', Mario is the president of a profitable toy-making company.<ref>{{cite book| title = Mario vs. Donkey Kong 2: March of the Minis Instruction Booklet| section = Story and Characters| publisher = [[Nintendo|Nintendo of America]]| date = September 25, 2006}}</ref> Mario is an athlete in [[List of Mario sports games|''Mario'' sports games]] including ''[[Mario Sports Mix]]'', ''[[Mario Strikers Charged]]'', and ''[[Mario Tennis Aces]]''; as well as a [[kart racer]] in the ''[[Mario Kart]]'' series. Mario usually saves [[Princess Peach]] and the [[Mushroom Kingdom]] and purges antagonists, such as [[Bowser (character)|Bowser]], from various areas. Mario has gained fame in the Mushroom Kingdom due to his heroic deeds, as shown in ''[[Mario & Luigi: Superstar Saga]]'', where the brothers are referred to as \"superstars\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://marioandluigi.gameboy.com/flash.jsp|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071021031417/http://marioandluigi.gameboy.com/flash.jsp|archivedate=October 21, 2007|title=Mario and Luigi: Superstar Saga|publisher=[[Nintendo]]}}</ref> In September 2017, Nintendo confirmed on their official Japanese profile for the character that Mario was no longer considered a plumber, most likely due to his various occupations and hobbies.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://kotaku.com/mario-is-officially-no-longer-a-plumber-1799118840|title=Mario Is Officially No Longer A Plumber|last=Ashcraft|first=Brian|website=Kotaku|date=September 4, 2017|accessdate=September 4, 2017}}</ref> However as of March 2018, the Japanese profile has since been changed to state that Mario's occupation is still a plumber.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://kotaku.com/mario-is-officially-a-plumber-again-1823545849|title=Mario Is Officially A Plumber Again|last=Schreier|first=Jason|website=Kotaku|date=March 6, 2018|accessdate=March 19, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Relationships===\nSince his first game, Mario has usually had the role of saving the [[damsel in distress]].<ref name=\"mariobioign\">{{cite web| title = Mario Biography| website = IGN| url = http://stars.ign.com/objects/923/923448_biography.html| accessdate = January 23, 2010| url-status = dead| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20091220083249/http://stars.ign.com/objects/923/923448_biography.html| archivedate = December 20, 2009}}</ref> Originally, he had to rescue his girlfriend [[Recurring characters in the Mario series#Pauline|Pauline]] in ''[[Donkey Kong (video game)|Donkey Kong]]'' from Donkey Kong.<ref name=\"dkhist\" /> Pauline was soon replaced by a new damsel in distress, [[Princess Peach]], in ''[[Super Mario Bros.]]'',<ref name=\"ign\" /> but returned in the [[Game Boy]] remake of ''[[Donkey Kong (Game Boy)|Donkey Kong]]'' in 1994, and in ''[[Mario vs. Donkey Kong 2: March of the Minis]]'' in 2006, although the character is now described as \"Mario's friend\".<ref name=\"Mario vs. DK 2\">{{cite web|url=http://uk.videogames.games.yahoo.com/ds/previews/mario-vs--donkey-kong-2--march-of-the-minis-902997.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110927233733/http://uk.videogames.games.yahoo.com/ds/previews/mario-vs--donkey-kong-2--march-of-the-minis-902997.html|archivedate=September 27, 2011|title=Mario vs. DK 2: March of the Minis|publisher=[[Yahoo! Games]]|accessdate=August 23, 2008}}</ref> Mario has rescued Princess Peach multiple times since ''Super Mario Bros.''<ref name=\"mariobioign\" /> In a [[role reversal]], Peach rescues Mario in ''[[Super Princess Peach]]''.<ref>{{cite web| last = Bozon| first = Mark | title = Hands-On: Super Princess Peach| website = IGN| date = February 1, 2006| url = http://ds.ign.com/articles/685/685051p1.html| accessdate = January 23, 2010}}</ref> Mario rescued [[Princess Daisy (Mario)|Princess Daisy]] of Sarasaraland in ''[[Super Mario Land]]'',<ref>{{cite web| title = Princess Daisy Biography| website = IGN| url = http://stars.ign.com/objects/963/963167_biography.html| accessdate = January 27, 2009| url-status = dead| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20071129224132/http://stars.ign.com/objects/963/963167_biography.html| archivedate = November 29, 2007}}</ref> but Luigi seems to be more linked to her. In ''[[Super Smash Bros. Melee]]'', the text explaining Daisy's trophy states that \"after her appearance in ''[[Mario Golf]]'', gossips portrayed her as Luigi's answer to Mario's Peach\".<ref>{{cite video game|title=Super Smash Bros. Melee|developer=HAL Laboratory|publisher=Nintendo|date=December 3, 2001|platform=Nintendo GameCube}}</ref>\n\n[[Luigi]] is Mario's younger fraternal twin brother.<ref name=\"luigibioign\" /> He is a companion in the ''Mario'' games,<ref name=\"luigibioign\" /> and the character whom the second player controls in two-player sessions of many of the video games,<ref name=\"luigiprofileign\">{{cite web| title = Luigi Profile| website = IGN| url = http://stars.ign.com/objects/924/924288.html| accessdate = January 26, 2010| url-status = dead| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20090225211747/http://stars.ign.com/objects/924/924288.html| archivedate = February 25, 2009}}</ref> though he occasionally rescues Mario, as seen in ''[[Mario Is Missing!]]'' and ''[[Luigi's Mansion]]''.<ref>{{cite web| last = Buchanan| first = Levi| title = The Other Mario Games, Vol. 2| website = IGN| date = August 7, 2008| url = http://retro.ign.com/articles/897/897225p1.html| accessdate = January 23, 2010}}</ref> ''[[Super Mario Land 2: 6 Golden Coins]]'' for the Game Boy saw the arrival of [[Wario]], Mario's greedy [[wikt:counterpart|counterpart]], who is often Mario's antagonist or an [[antihero]].<ref>{{cite web| title = Wario Biography| website = IGN| url = http://stars.ign.com/objects/924/924285_biography.html| accessdate = January 23, 2010| url-status = dead| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20090712120508/http://stars.ign.com/objects/924/924285_biography.html| archivedate = July 12, 2009}}</ref> [[Yoshi]] is a dinosaur whose species is also named Yoshi.<ref name=\"yoshibio\" /> They vary in color, though the original Yoshi is green.<ref name=\"yoshibio\">{{cite web | title =Yoshi Biography | url =http://stars.ign.com/objects/924/924294_biography.html | website =IGN | accessdate =January 23, 2009 | url-status =dead | archiveurl =https://web.archive.org/web/20100602142520/http://stars.ign.com/objects/924/924294_biography.html | archivedate =June 2, 2010 }}</ref> Yoshi serves as Mario's steed in games such as ''[[Super Mario World]]'',<ref name=\"yoshibio\" /> and is depicted as an independent character in games like ''[[Super Mario Kart]]'' and ''[[Super Mario World 2: Yoshi's Island]]''.\n\n=={{anchor|Ground pound|Wall jump|Spin jump}}Abilities==\nDuring the development of ''[[Donkey Kong (video game)|Donkey Kong]]'', Mario was known as ''Jumpman''.<ref name=\"ign\" /> Jumping\u2014both to access places and as an offensive move\u2014is a common gameplay element in ''Mario'' games, especially the ''[[Super Mario]]'' series. By the time ''[[Super Mario RPG]]'' was released, jumping became such a signature act of Mario that the player was often tasked with jumping to prove to [[non-player character]]s that he was Mario. Mario's most commonly portrayed form of attack is jumping to stomp on the heads of enemies, first used in ''[[Super Mario Bros.]]'' This jump-stomp move may entirely crush smaller enemies on the stage, and usually deals damage to larger ones, sometimes causing secondary effects.<ref name=\"ign\" />\n\nThis attack often enables Mario to knock the turtle-like [[Koopa Troopa]]s into or out of their shells, which can be used as weapons.<ref name=\"ign\" /> Subsequent games have elaborated on Mario's jumping-related abilities. ''[[Super Mario World]]'' added the ability to spin-jump, which allows Mario to break blocks beneath him. The Game Boy version of ''[[Donkey Kong (Game Boy)|Donkey Kong]]'' allows Mario to jump higher with consecutive jumps, and perform a back-flip. In ''[[Super Mario 64]]'', Mario gains new jumping abilities such as a sideways somersault; a ground pound, which is a high-impact downward thrusting motion; and the \"Wall Kick\", which propels him upwards by kicking off walls.\n\n===Power-ups===\n[[File:Tanooki Mario.jpg|upright|thumb|Mario seen wearing the Tanooki Suit in [[Super Mario Bros. 3]]. The suit is derived from the [[Japanese raccoon dog]], tanuki.]]\n\nMario uses items, which give him various powers, and differ between the games he is in. The first power-up Mario used was the Hammer in ''[[Donkey Kong (video game)|Donkey Kong]]''.<ref name=\"dkhist\">{{cite web|last=Trueman |first=Doug |title=GameSpot Presents: The History of Donkey Kong |website=[[GameSpot]] |url=http://www.gamespot.com/gamespot/features/video/dk_history/p03.html |archiveurl=http://web.archive.bibalex.org/web/20010710164559/http://gamespot.com/gamespot/features/video/dk_history/p03.html |archivedate=July 10, 2001 |accessdate=January 1, 2010 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n''[[Super Mario Bros.]]'' introduced the basic three power-ups that have become staples for the series, especially the 2D games \u2014 the Super Mushroom, which causes Mario to grow larger; the Fire Flower, which allows Mario to throw [[fire]]balls; and the Starman, which gives Mario temporary invincibility. These powers have appeared regularly throughout the series.<ref name=\"ign\" /> Throughout the series' history, there have been several kinds of Mushroom power-ups, including the [[1-up]] Mushroom, which gives Mario an extra life; the Poison Mushroom, which causes Mario to either shrink or die;<ref>{{cite web|last=Suellentrop |first=Chris |url=http://www.slate.com/id/2177082/ |title=Super Mario Bros.: The Lost Levels reviewed. \u2013 By Chris Suellentrop \u2013 Slate Magazine |work=Slate |date=November 5, 2007 |accessdate=April 4, 2009}}</ref> the Mega Mushroom, which causes Mario to grow very large; and the Mini Mushroom, which causes Mario to shrink.<ref>{{cite web|last=Harris |first=Craig |url=http://uk.ds.ign.com/articles/705/705537p2.html |title=IGN: New Super Mario Bros. Review |publisher=Uk.ds.ign.com |accessdate=April 4, 2009}}</ref>\n\nA reoccurring power-up throughout the series is an item that gives Mario the ability of flight. The first of this type was introduced in ''[[Super Mario Bros. 3]]'': one power-up, which gives Mario a raccoon suit, is called the Super Leaf,<ref>{{cite web|last=Provo |first=Frank |url=http://uk.gamespot.com/wii/action/supermariobros3/review.html |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090310191431/http://uk.gamespot.com/wii/action/supermariobros3/review.html |archivedate=March 10, 2009 |title=Super Mario Bros. 3 Review for Wii \u2013 GameSpot |publisher=Uk.gamespot.com |date=November 9, 2007 |accessdate=April 4, 2009}}</ref>  while another is called the Tanooki Suit (a transliteration of [[Japanese raccoon dog|tanuki]]) and grants Mario the ability to fly or turn into a statue.<ref name=\"ignsuits\">{{cite web| title = Top 10 Mario Suits| website = IGN| date = November 16, 2009| url = http://wii.ign.com/articles/104/1045630p1.html| accessdate = January 23, 2010| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20100309115558/http://wii.ign.com/articles/104/1045630p1.html| archive-date = March 9, 2010| url-status = dead| df = mdy-all}}</ref> In ''[[Super Mario World]]'', an item called the Cape Feather was introduced that gave Mario a cape.<ref>{{cite web|last=Navarro |first=Alex |url=http://uk.gamespot.com/wii/action/supermarioworldsnes/review.html |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070714100606/http://uk.gamespot.com/wii/action/supermarioworldsnes/review.html |archivedate=July 14, 2007 |title=Super Mario World for Wii Review \u2013 GameSpot |publisher=Uk.gamespot.com |date=February 9, 2007 |accessdate=April 4, 2009 |url-status=dead }}</ref> In ''[[Super Mario Land 2: 6 Golden Coins]]'', a carrot was available that gave Mario rabbit ears that allowed him to fly,<ref name=\"ignsuits\" /> and in ''[[Super Mario 64]]'', Mario could acquire an item called the Wing Cap, which temporarily gave him the ability of flight.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nintendo.com/games/detail/48czfMMYIp_0_alQYMIOS7sgrvUdDq1O |title=Super Mario 64 at Nintendo :: Wii :: Virtual Console :: Games |publisher=Nintendo.com |accessdate=June 24, 2013}}</ref> ''[[Super Mario Sunshine]]'' introduces a pump-water spraying device named \"F.L.U.D.D.\", which abilities included spraying water and hovering.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://uk.gamespot.com/gamecube/action/supermariosunshine/review.html?om_act=convert&om_clk=gssummary&tag=summary;read-review |archive-url=https://archive.today/20120716210856/http://uk.gamespot.com/gamecube/action/supermariosunshine/review.html?om_act=convert&om_clk=gssummary&tag=summary;read-review |url-status=dead |archive-date=July 16, 2012 |title=Super Mario Sunshine Review for GameCube \u2013 GameSpot |publisher=Uk.gamespot.com |date=October 4, 2002 |accessdate=April 4, 2009}}</ref>\n\n''[[Super Mario Galaxy]]'' introduced new power-ups, including the Bee Mushroom, which turned Mario into a bee and allowed him to fly temporarily; the Boo Mushroom, which turned Mario into a ghost, allowing him to float and pass through walls; the Spring Mushroom, which encased Mario in a spring, allowing him to jump higher; and the Ice Flower, which allowed the player to temporarily walk on water and lava without sinking or taking damage.<ref>{{cite book| title = Super Mario Galaxy Instruction Booklet| section = Mario's Special Moves | publisher = [[Nintendo|Nintendo of America]]| year = 2007}}</ref> ''[[Super Mario Galaxy 2]]'' introduced more power ups, including the Cloud Flower which allows Mario to create platforms in midair and Rock Mario, which transforms Mario into a boulder that could be used to break through barriers.<ref>{{cite book| title = Super Mario Galaxy 2 Instruction Booklet| section = Mario's Special Moves | publisher = [[Nintendo|Nintendo of America]]| year = 2010}}</ref>\n\n''[[New Super Mario Bros. Wii]]'' updated the Ice Flower, which allows Mario to shoot ice balls that temporally freeze enemies; and introduced the Propeller Mushroom, which allows him to fly; as well as the Penguin Suit, which allows Mario to easily traverse ice and swim through water in addition to shooting ice balls. ''[[Super Mario 3D Land]]'' introduced the Boomerang Flower, which allows Mario to throw boomerangs at nearby enemies; and the Statue Leaf, which allows Mario to turn to a statue. In ''[[New Super Mario Bros. U]]'', a Super Acorn makes its debut. This transforms Mario to his new [[Flying squirrel]] form where he can glide and stick on walls. ''[[Super Mario 3D World]]'' introduced the Super Bell, which transforms Mario into his cat form as well as a Double Cherry to make multiple copies of himself.\n\n=={{anchor | Reception and legacy}}Reception==\n\n===Critical response===\n[[File:Supermario Kungsbacka.jpg|thumb|upright|Mario in [[Kungsbacka]], Sweden]]\n\nAs Nintendo's primary mascot, Mario is widely considered to be the most famous video game character in history, and has been called an icon of the gaming industry.<ref name=\"History of Mario\">{{cite web|url=http://www.gamecubicle.com/features-mario-nintendo_shining_star.htm|title=Nintendo's Shining Star: The History of Mario|publisher=Gamecubicle|accessdate=August 23, 2008}}</ref><ref name=\"wired\" /><ref>{{cite web |last=Buchanan |first=Levi |title=Is There a Bad Mario Game? |website=IGN |date=February 13, 2009 |url=http://retro.ign.com/articles/954/954165p1.html |accessdate=January 23, 2010}}</ref> The ''Mario'' series of video games has sold more than 510 million copies, making it the [[List of best-selling video game franchises|best-selling video game franchise]].<ref name=\"ign\" /> Mario was one of the first video game character inductees at the [[Walk of Game]] in 2005, alongside [[Link (The Legend of Zelda)|Link]] and [[Sonic the Hedgehog (character)|Sonic the Hedgehog]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.walkofgame.com/inductees/inductees2005.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080121064109/http://www.walkofgame.com/inductees/inductees2005.html|archivedate=January 21, 2008|title=Past Inductees 2005 Games / Characters|publisher=[[Walk of Game]]|accessdate=February 21, 2008}}</ref> Mario was the first video game character to be honored with a wax figure in the [[Hollywood Wax Museum]] in 2003. In 1990, a national survey found that Mario was more recognizable to American children than [[Mickey Mouse]].<ref name=\"Recentering Globalization\">{{cite book|last=Iwabuchi|first=Koichi|title=Recentering globalization: Popular culture and Japanese transnationalism|publisher=Duke University Press|isbn=978-0-8223-2891-9|url=http://www.dukeupress.edu/Catalog/ViewProduct.php?productid=8083&viewby=title|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100709183746/http://www.dukeupress.edu/Catalog/ViewProduct.php?productid=8083&viewby=title|url-status=dead|archive-date=July 9, 2010|page=30|chapter=1. Taking Japanization seriously: Cultural globalization reconsidered|chapterurl=https://books.google.com/books/p/dukeupress?vid=978-0-8223-2891-9&pg=PA30|accessdate=February 20, 2017|date=2002-11-08}}</ref><ref>https://www.baltimoresun.com/news/bs-xpm-1993-05-18-1993138174-story.html</ref> Mario has also been called the \"most recognisable\" figure in the gaming industry.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://kotaku.com/5636283/happy-25th-birthday-super-mario-bros |title=Happy 25th Birthday, Super Mario Bros. |accessdate=October 18, 2010 |last=Plunkett |first=Luke |date=September 13, 2010 |publisher=Kotaku |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100921225033/http://kotaku.com/5636283/happy-25th-birthday-super-mario-bros |archivedate=September 21, 2010 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nCreator Shigeru Miyamoto has stated that Mario is his favorite out of all characters that he has created.<ref>{{cite magazine |title= Exclusive Interview With Nintendo Gaming Mastermind Shigeru Miyamoto |url=http://www.popularmechanics.com/technology/gadgets/video-games/4334387 |magazine=[[Popular Mechanics]] |accessdate=October 21, 2009 |date=October 19, 2009}}</ref> ''[[Electronic Gaming Monthly]]'' gave Mario their \"Coolest Mascot\" award for 1996, calling him \"an age-old friend.\"<ref>{{cite magazine |title=The Best of '96 |magazine=[[Electronic Gaming Monthly]] |issue=92|publisher=[[Ziff Davis]]|date=March 1997 |page=90}}</ref> ''[[Nintendo Power]]'' listed Mario as their favorite hero, citing his defining characteristics as his mustache, red cap, plumbing prowess, and his mushrooms.<ref>{{cite book |title=Nintendo Power 250th issue! |year=2010 |publisher=[[Future US]] |location=[[South San Francisco, California]] |pages=40, 41 |url= |title-link=Nintendo Power }}</ref> In a poll conducted in 2008 by [[Oricon]], Mario was voted the most popular video game character in Japan.<ref>{{cite web|author=Brian Ashcraft|title=And Japan's Favorite Video Game Characters Are...?|date=August 23, 2008|url=http://kotaku.com/5035884/and-japans-favorite-video-game-characters-are|accessdate=August 23, 2008|publisher=Kotaku}}</ref>\n\n[[GameDaily]] listed the \"unlikely hero\" on its top 25 video game archetypes, and used Mario as an example of this. It stated that in spite of the fact that he should have run out of energy through the first level, he kept going.<ref>{{cite web| last = Buffa| first = Chris| title = Top 25 Game Archetypes| publisher = [[GameDaily]]| date = January 23, 2009| url = http://www.gamedaily.com/articles/galleries/top-25-video-game-characters-archetypes/?page=25| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20181106132148/http://www.gamedaily.com/articles/galleries/top-25-video-game-characters-archetypes/?page=25| url-status = dead| archive-date = November 6, 2018| accessdate = January 1, 2010}}</ref> Mario ranked fourth on [[GameDaily]]'s top ten ''Smash Bros.'' characters list.<ref>{{cite web |title=Top 10 Smash Bros. Characters \u2013 Page 7 |url=http://www.gamedaily.com/articles/galleries/top-ten-super-smash-bros-characters/?page=7 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091023030816/http://www.gamedaily.com/articles/galleries/top-ten-super-smash-bros-characters/?page=7 |archivedate=October 23, 2009 |publisher=[[GameDaily]] |accessdate=August 7, 2009}}</ref> Mario was fourth on [[UGO]]'s list of the \"Top 100 Heroes of All Time\".<ref>{{cite web|author=Staff |date=September 24, 2007 |url=http://www.ugo.com/games/top-heroes-in-entertainment/shows.asp?groupID=shows20-1&showID=mario |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071011002607/http://www.ugo.com/games/top-heroes-in-entertainment/shows.asp?groupID=shows20-1&showID=mario |url-status=dead |archive-date=October 11, 2007 |title=Best Heroes of All Time: Mario |publisher=[[UGO Networks]] |accessdate=November 8, 2009 }}</ref> They also listed Mario's hat twenty-first on their list of \"The Coolest Helmets and Headgear in Video Games\", stating \"there's always somebody at your Halloween party wearing one.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ugo.com/games/the-coolest-helmets-and-headgear-in-video-games?page=2 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110311040052/http://www.ugo.com/games/the-coolest-helmets-and-headgear-in-video-games?page=2 |url-status=dead |archive-date=March 11, 2011 |title=The Coolest Helmets and Headgear in Video Games |publisher=[[UGO.com]] |author=Marissa Meli |date=March 4, 2011 |accessdate=March 21, 2011 }}</ref> [[CNET]] listed him first on its list of the \"Top 5 video game characters\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cnettv.cnet.com/8301-13415_53-10410413-11.html |title=Top 5 video game characters |date=December 7, 2009 |author=Tom Merritt |website=[[CNET]] |accessdate=April 25, 2010}}</ref> He was voted 100th in [[IGN]]'s Top 100 Villains for his appearance in ''[[Donkey Kong Junior]]'', adding \"This Mario is a total jerk, holding Donkey Kong Jr.'s dad hostage\",<ref>{{cite web|url=http://uk.ign.com/videogame-villains/100.html |title=Top 100 Villains| website=IGN |accessdate=May 13, 2010|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120106080555/http://uk.ign.com/videogame-villains/100.html|archivedate=January 6, 2012}}</ref> and he has also been elected by [[GamesRadar]] as the 90th \"most dastardly ne'er-do-wells\" villain in video games in their \"top 100\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gamesradar.com/top-100-villains-video-games/ |title=100 best villains in video games |date=May 17, 2013 |publisher=[[GamesRadar]] |accessdate=July 28, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.today/20130624192529/http://www.gamesradar.com/top-100-villains-video-games/ |archivedate=June 24, 2013 }}</ref>\n\n===Legacy===\n{{multiple image\n | align = right\n|direction=vertical\n | total_width =200\n\n | image1 = Cerim\u00f4nia de encerramento dos Jogos Ol\u00edmpicos Rio 2016 1039534-21082016- mg 8618 (cropped).jpg\n | width1 = 100 | height1 = 136\n | alt1 =\n | caption1 = Japanese prime minister [[Shinz\u014d Abe]] holding Mario's cap.\n\n | image2 = Cerim\u00f4nia de encerramento dos Jogos Ol\u00edmpicos Rio 2016 1039540-21082016- mg 8837.jpg\n | width2 = 200 | height2 = 156\n | alt2 =\n | caption2 = Dancers performing alongside an oversized Warp Pipe.\n\n | header= The [[2016 Summer Olympics closing ceremony#Warming up! Tokyo 2020|2016 Olympics closing ceremony]] featured Mario-inspired imagery.\n}}\n\nMario has been established as a [[popular culture|pop culture]] icon, and has starred in numerous television shows, comic books, and in a feature film. He has appeared on lunch boxes, T-shirts, magazines, commercials (notably, in a [[Got Milk?]] commercial),<ref>Weiss, Jodi & Kahn, Russell (2004). In ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=Mp0LRxu0ibsC&pg=PA25&dq=%22got+milk%22+mario&ei=-_b0Sr7sG5PyNJ3B1YoF#v=onepage&q=%22got%20milk%22%20mario&f=false 145 Things to Be When You Grow Up]''. Princeton Review Publishing. p. 25. {{ISBN|0-375-76369-4}}. Google Book Search. Retrieved November 6, 2009.</ref> in candy form, on shampoo bottles, cereal, badges, board games, and as a plush toy.<ref name=\"History of Mario\" /> Nintendo produced a 60-minute [[anime]] film based on the original ''Super Mario Bros.,'' ''[[Super Mario Bros.: Peach-Hime Kyushutsu Dai Sakusen!]],'' in 1986, although this film has not been released outside Japan and has not been released on any home video format except [[VHS]].\n\nThe animated series ''[[The Super Mario Bros. Super Show!]]'' featured a live-action series of skits which starred former WWF manager [[Lou Albano|\"Captain\" Lou Albano]] as Mario and [[Danny Wells]] as Luigi. Mario appeared in a book series, the [[Nintendo Adventure Books]]. Mario has inspired unlicensed paintings,<ref>{{cite web| title=10 Works of Art Inspired By ''Super Mario Bros.'' |url=http://pixelatedgeek.com/2009/04/10-works-of-art-inspired-by-super-mario-bros/ |publisher=Pixelated Geek |accessdate=May 5, 2009}}</ref> performances on [[talent show]]s such as ''[[India's Got Talent]]'',<ref>{{cite web|last=Ashcraft|first=Brian|title=India's Got Mario Talent|url=http://kotaku.com/5313073/indias-got-mario-talent|publisher=Kotaku|accessdate=May 17, 2012|date=July 13, 2009}}</ref> and short films, which have been viewed hundreds of thousands of times.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://kotaku.com/5870843/32-nintendo-fans-made-these-8-short-movies-in-24-hours/|title=32 Nintendo Fans made these 8 Short Movies in 24 Hours|last=Totilo|first=Stephen|date=December 23, 2011|accessdate=December 14, 2015}}</ref> The character has been present in a number of works created by third parties other than Nintendo, such as in the [[iOS]] and [[Android (operating system)|Android]] video game ''[[Platform Panic]]'', in which one of the purchasable skins is a reference to him.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gamezebo.com/2014/12/30/platform-panic-review-infinite-platforms-infinite-pleasure/|title=Platform Panic Review: Infinite Platforms, Infinite Pleasure|last=Spencer|first=Spanner|date=December 30, 2014|website=Gamezebo|access-date=July 4, 2016}}</ref>\n\nMany people and places have been named or nicknamed after Mario. [[Bergsala]], the distributor of Nintendo's products in the [[Nordic countries|Nordic]] and the [[Baltic countries]], is located at Marios Gata 21 (Mario's Street 21) in [[Kungsbacka]], [[Sweden]], named after Mario.<ref>{{cite web|title=Bergsala AB, Contact page|url=http://www.nintendo.se/kontakt|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100817232653/http://www.nintendo.se/kontakt|url-status=dead|archive-date=August 17, 2010|accessdate=June 24, 2013}}</ref> Many sports stars, including [[Bundesliga]] [[Association football|football]] players [[Mario G\u00f6tze]] and [[Mario G\u00f3mez]], [[National Hockey League]] player [[Mario Lemieux]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/sportscentury/features/00016068.html |title=ESPN.com: Mario was super despite the obstacles |publisher=ESPN |accessdate=April 4, 2009}}</ref> [[Football in Italy|Italian footballer]] [[Mario Balotelli]],<ref>[http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-1298803/Carlo-Ancelotti-Mario-Balotelli-win-title-Manchester-City.html Super Mario Balotelli can win title for Manchester City] ''Daily Mail'', July 29, 2010</ref> and Italian cyclist [[Mario Cipollini]] have been given the nickname \"Super Mario\". In a suburb of the Spanish city of [[Zaragoza]], streets were named after video games, including \"Avenida de Super Mario Bros\".<ref>{{cite news |last1=Shoichet |first1=Catherine E. |title=Spanish neighborhood unveils 'Super Mario' street |url=http://edition.cnn.com/2010/WORLD/europe/11/08/spain.super.mario.subdivision/index.html |accessdate=August 27, 2018 |publisher=CNN |date=November 8, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kotaku.com/2010/11/mario-gets-serious-street-cred-in-spain|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110713165342/http://www.kotaku.com/2010/11/mario-gets-serious-street-cred-in-spain|archivedate=July 13, 2011|title=What Were Your Greatest Gaming Moments of 2010?|author=Brian Crecente|publisher=Kotaku}}</ref>\n\nMario's legacy is recognized by [[Guinness World Records]], who awarded the Nintendo mascot, and the series of platform games he has appeared in, seven world records in the ''Guinness World Records: Gamer's Edition 2008''. These records include \"Best Selling Video Game Series of All Time\", \"First Movie Based on an Existing Video Game\", and \"Most Prolific Video Game Character\", with Mario appearing in 116 original games.<ref>{{cite book| editor= Craig Glenday| title= Guinness World Records Gamer's Edition 2008| series= [[Guinness World Records]]| date= March 11, 2008| publisher= Guinness| isbn= 978-1-904994-21-3| url= https://archive.org/details/guinnessworldrec00guin_0}}</ref> In 2011, readers of ''Guinness World Records Gamer's Edition'' voted Mario as the top video game character of all time.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.gameinformer.com/b/news/archive/2011/02/16/guinness-names-top-50-video-game-characters-of-all-time.aspx |title=Guinness Names Top 50 Video Game Characters Of All Time |newspaper=[[Game Informer]] |first=Jeff |last=Marchiafava |date=February 16, 2011 |access-date=February 2, 2018}}</ref>\n\nMario appeared in the [[2016 Summer Olympics closing ceremony]] to promote the [[2020 Summer Olympics]] in [[Tokyo]]. In a pre-recorded video, the prime minister [[Shinz\u014d Abe]] became Mario to use a [[Warp pipe]] planted by [[Doraemon (character)|Doraemon]] from [[Shibuya#Shibuya Crossing|Shibuya Crossing]] to [[Maracan\u00e3 Stadium]]. Abe then appeared dressed as Mario in an oversized Warp Pipe in the middle of the stadium.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Palazzo|first1=Chiara|title=Shinzo Abe emerges from a green pipe disguised as Super Mario during Rio Closing Ceremony|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/olympics/2016/08/22/shinzo-abe-emerges-from-a-green-pipe-disguised-as-super-mario-du/|accessdate=August 22, 2016|date=August 22, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"TIME.com\">{{cite news|url=http://time.com/4460923/super-mario-japan-prime-minister-shinzo-abe/|title=Shinzo Abe Dresses as Super Mario for Rio Closing Ceremony|date=August 22, 2016|work=Time|last1=Samuelson|first1=Kate|accessdate=August 22, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Palazzo|first1=Chiara|title=Shinzo Abe emerges from a green pipe disguised as Super Mario during Rio Closing Ceremony|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/olympics/2016/08/22/shinzo-abe-emerges-from-a-green-pipe-disguised-as-super-mario-du/|work=The Daily Telegraph|accessdate=August 22, 2016|date=August 22, 2016}}</ref>\n\nMario Day (previously known as National{{where|date=March 2020}} Mario Day) is celebrated on March 10,<ref>\n{{citation|author=Schuyler J. Dievendorf|url=http://www.escapistmagazine.com/articles/view/features/galleryoftheday/11094-8-Best-Ways-To-Celebrate-National-Mario-Day |title=8 Best Ways To Celebrate National Mario Day|work=[[The Escapist (magazine)|The Escapist]] |date=March 10, 2014 |accessdate=March 9, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{citation|url=http://www.4players.de/4players.php/spielinfonews/Allgemein/326/2156909/Nintendo-Video_zum_heutigen_National_Mario_Day.html |title=Nintendo: Video zum heutigen National Mario Day |author=Alice Wilczynski|publisher=[[4Players]] |date= March 10, 2016|accessdate=March 9, 2017 | language = German}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tristateupdate.com/story/31432843/national-mario-day|title=National Mario Day|publisher=Tristate Update, [[WOWK-TV]]|date=March 10, 2016|accessdate=March 9, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170312031758/http://www.tristateupdate.com/story/31432843/national-mario-day|archive-date=March 12, 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref> as when that date is presented as Mar 10 it resembles the name MARIO.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.timeanddate.com/holidays/fun/mario-day |title=Fun Holiday \u2013 Mario Day |publisher=Timeanddate.com |accessdate=March 9, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{citation|author=Dani Werner |url=http://www.startribune.com/jump-start-your-week/371088501/ |title=Jump-start your week with some items of interest |work=[[Star Tribune]] |date=March 7, 2016 |accessdate=March 9, 2017}}</ref> Since 2016, the day was officially observed by Nintendo,<ref>{{cite web|title=Celebrate Mar 10 - Mario Day!|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=uoj1d8x2H6c|website=YouTube|publisher=Nintendo (Nintendo of America)|accessdate=March 13, 2018}}</ref> and celebrates this day annually by promoting ''Mario'' games and holding ''Mario''-related events.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Burch|first1=Jennifer|title=Nintendo celebrates Mario Day with panache|url=https://nintendowire.com/news/2018/03/09/nintendo-celebrates-mario-day-panache/|accessdate=March 13, 2018|work=Nintendo Wire|date=March 9, 2018}}</ref>\n\n{{Clear}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikipedia books|Mario franchise characters}}\n{{Portal|Video games}}\n* {{commons category-inline|Mario (character)}}\n* {{Wikiquote-inline|Mario (franchise)|Mario}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20170511193109/http://www.imdb.com/character/ch0039169/ Mario] on [[IMDb]]\n* [https://www.mariowiki.com/Mario Mario] on Super Mario Wiki\n* [http://mario.nintendo.com/ Official website for the ''Mario'' series]\n* [https://www.nintendo.com/sites/mario Mario entry on Nintendo.com]\n\n{{Mario franchise}}\n{{Donkey Kong series}}\n{{Forbes Fictional 15}}\n{{Raving Rabbids series}}\n{{Super Smash Bros.}}\n\n[[Category:Action video game characters]]\n[[Category:Animated human characters]]\n[[Category:Characters created by Shigeru Miyamoto]]\n[[Category:Corporate mascots]]\n[[Category:Toy mascots]]\n[[Category:Video game mascots]]\n[[Category:Culture of Brooklyn]]\n[[Category:Fictional American people of European descent in video games]]\n[[Category:Fictional American people of Italian descent]]\n[[Category:Fictional characters from New York City]]\n[[Category:Fictional Italian people in video games]]\n[[Category:Fictional physicians]]\n[[Category:Fictional plumbers]]\n[[Category:Fictional male sportspeople]]\n[[Category:Fictional twins]]\n[[Category:Twin characters in video games]]\n[[Category:Fictional victims of kidnapping]]\n[[Category:Male characters in video games]]\n[[Category:Mario characters]]\n[[Category:Nintendo protagonists]]\n[[Category:Super Smash Bros. fighters]]\n[[Category:Video game bosses]]\n[[Category:Video game characters in comics]]\n[[Category:Video game characters in film]]\n[[Category:Video game characters in television]]\n[[Category:Video game characters introduced in 1981]]\n[[Category:Video game characters with fire or heat abilities]]\n[[Category:Video game secret characters]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Fictional character from Nintendo's ''Mario'' franchise and the company's mascot}}\n{{About|the Nintendo character|the franchise featuring him|Super Mario|and|Mario (franchise)|other uses|Mario (given name)|and|Mario (disambiguation)}}\n{{pp-semi-indef|small=yes}}\n{{pp-move-indef}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=November 2018}}\n{{Infobox character\n| color          = #EC7365 <!-- From the Super Mario series logo (adjusted for contrast) -->\n| name           = Mario\n| franchise      = [[Mario (franchise)|Mario]]\n| image          = MarioNSMBUDeluxe.png\n| alt            = \n| caption        = Mario, as depicted in promotional artwork of ''[[New Super Mario Bros. U Deluxe]]''\n| first    = ''[[Donkey Kong (video game)|Donkey Kong]]'' (1981)\n| last = ''[[Mario & Sonic at the Olympic Games Tokyo 2020]]'' (2019)\n| creator        = [[Shigeru Miyamoto]]\n| adapted_by     = <!-- for character adaption articles -->\n| designer       = {{Unbulleted list|Shigeru Miyamoto|[[Y\u014dichi Kotabe]]|[[Shigefumi Hino]]}}\n| portrayer      = {{Unbulleted list|[[Lou Albano]] {{small|(''The Super Mario Bros. Super Show!'')}}|[[Bob Hoskins]] {{small|(''[[Super Mario Bros. (film)|Super Mario Bros.]]'')}}|[[John Lenahan]] {{small|(''The Super Mario Challenge'')}}}}\n| voice          = {{Collapsible list|title = English\n| Ronald B. Ruben {{small|(''[[Mario Teaches Typing]]'')}}\n| Marc Graue {{small|(''[[Hotel Mario]]'')}}\n| [[Charles Martinet]] {{small|(1990\u2013present)}}\n| [[Peter Cullen]] {{small|(''[[Saturday Supercade]]'')}}\n| [[Lou Albano]] {{small|(''[[The Super Mario Bros. Super Show!]]'')}}\n| Walker Boone {{small|(''[[The Adventures of Super Mario Bros. 3]]'' and ''[[Super Mario World (TV series)|Super Mario World]]'')}}}}\n{{Collapsible list|title = Japanese\n| [[T\u014dru Furuya]] {{small|(1986\u20131988; ''[[Super Mario Bros.: The Great Mission to Rescue Princess Peach!]]'' and ''[[Amada Anime Series: Super Mario Bros.]]'')}}\n| [[Takeshi Aono]] {{small|(1992\u20131993; ''[[Mario Paint]]'' and ''[[Super Mario All-Stars]]'')}}\n| [[Nozomu Sasaki]] {{small|(''Super Mario Bros. Special'' Drama CD)}}\n| [[K\u014dsei Tomita]] {{small|(Japanese dub of ''Super Mario Bros'' film)}}}}\n| motion_actor   = \n| full_name      = Mario Mario<ref name=\"full name\">Brian. [http://nintendoeverything.com/miyamoto-says-marios-full-name-is-mario-mario/ Miyamoto says Mario\u2019s full name is \u201cMario Mario\u201d]. ''Nintendo Everything'' (September 14, 2015). Retrieved September 14 2015</ref>\n| nickname       = Super Mario\n| alias          = <!-- or |aliases= -->\n| species        = <!-- or |race=; for non-humans only -->\n| gender         = Male\n| title          = \n| occupation     = [[Plumber]]\n| affiliation    = \n| fighting_style = \n| weapon         = \n| family         = \n| spouse         = <!-- or |spouses= -->\n| significant_other  = <!-- or |significant_others= -->\n| children       = \n| relatives      = [[Luigi]] {{small|(twin brother)}}\n| religion       = \n| origin         = The [[Mushroom Kingdom]]\n| nationality    = [[Italians|Italian]]\n}}\n\n{{nihongo|'''Mario'''|\u30de\u30ea\u30aa|Mario<!-- The Japanese transliteration name \"Mario\" appears in every game, so leave the Japanese transliteration as \"Mario\". -->|{{IPA-ja|ma\u027ei.o|pron}}; {{IPAc-en|lang|\u02c8|m|\u0251\u02d0r|i|o\u028a|,_|\u02c8|m|\u00e6r|-}}, {{IPA-it|\u02c8ma\u02d0rjo|lang}}|lead=yes}} is a fictional [[character (arts)|character]] in the [[Mario (franchise)|''Mario'' video game franchise]], owned by [[Nintendo]] and created by Japanese video game designer [[Shigeru Miyamoto]]. Acting as the company's mascot, as well as being the eponymous [[protagonist]] of the series, Mario has appeared in [[List of video games featuring Mario|over 200 video games]] since his creation. Depicted as a short, pudgy, [[Italians|Italian]] [[plumber]] who resides in the [[Mushroom Kingdom]], his adventures generally center upon rescuing [[Princess Peach]] from the Koopa villain [[Bowser (character)|Bowser]]. His fraternal twin brother and sidekick is [[Luigi]].\n\nWith more than 600 million units sold worldwide, the overall ''Mario'' franchise is the [[List of best-selling video game franchises|best-selling video game franchise]] of all time.<ref name=\"History of Mario\" /><ref name=\"10 best redbull\">{{cite web | title=The 10 best-selling video game franchises ever | date=December 26, 2016 | first=Mick | last=Fraser | url=https://www.redbull.com/gb-en/10-best-selling-video-game-franchises-of-all-time | accessdate=November 6, 2018}}</ref> Outside of the ''[[Super Mario]]'' platform series, other ''Mario'' genres include the ''[[Mario Kart]]'' racing series, sports games such as the ''[[List of Mario sports games#Mario Tennis series|Mario Tennis]]'' and ''[[List of Mario sports games#Mario Golf games|Mario Golf]]'' series,  [[Role-playing video game|role-playing games]] such as ''[[Mario & Luigi]]'', ''[[Super Mario RPG]]'' and ''[[Paper Mario]]'', and [[educational game]]s such as ''[[Mario Is Missing|Mario Is Missing!]]'', ''[[Mario's Time Machine]]'' and ''[[Mario Teaches Typing]]''. The franchise has branched into several media, including television shows, film, comics, and licensed merchandise. Since 1990, Mario has been voiced by [[Charles Martinet]].\n\n==Concept and creation==\n[[File:Mario emblem.svg|150px|thumb|Seen on his hat, Mario's emblem represents him in the interfaces of many of the games in which he has appeared.]]\n\n[[Shigeru Miyamoto]] created Mario while developing ''[[Donkey Kong (video game)|Donkey Kong]]'' in an attempt to produce a best-selling video game for [[Nintendo]]; previous games, such as ''[[Sheriff (arcade game)|Sheriff]],'' had not achieved the success of games such as [[Namco|Namco's]] ''[[Pac-Man]]''. Originally, Miyamoto wanted to create a game that used the characters [[Popeye]], [[Bluto]], and [[Olive Oyl]].<ref name=\"ign\" /> At the time, however, Miyamoto was unable to acquire a license to use the characters (and would not until 1982 with ''[[Popeye (video game)|Popeye]]''), so he ended up making an unnamed player character, [[Donkey Kong (character)|Donkey Kong]], and [[Pauline (Nintendo)|Lady]] (later known as Pauline).<ref name=\"ign\" /> In the early stages of ''Donkey Kong'', Mario was unable to jump, and the focus was to escape a maze. However, Miyamoto enabled Mario to jump, saying \"If you had a barrel rolling towards you, what would you do?\"<ref name=\"wired\">{{cite magazine|url=https://www.wired.com/gaming/gamingreviews/multimedia/2007/05/gallery_game_history?slide=18 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081020153928/http://www.wired.com/gaming/gamingreviews/multimedia/2007/05/gallery_game_history?slide=18 |url-status=dead |archive-date=October 20, 2008 |title=Console Portraits: A 40-Year Pictorial History of Gaming |magazine=[[Wired News]] |author=Orlando, Greg |accessdate=August 23, 2008 |date=May 15, 2007 }}</ref><ref name=\"wii-com1\">{{cite web |url=http://iwataasks.nintendo.com/interviews/#/wii/nsmb/0/0 |title=Iwata Asks: New Super Mario Bros. |work=Wii.com |publisher=[[Nintendo]] |accessdate=June 24, 2013 |page=1}}</ref>\n\nWhile the protagonist was unnamed in the Japanese release, he was named '''Jumpman''' in the game's English instructions<ref>{{cite magazine|last=|first= |title=Mario: Alive, Well, and Living in the Bronx?|magazine=[[Next Generation (magazine)|Next Generation]] |issue=26|publisher=[[Imagine Media]]|date=February 1997|page=46}}</ref> and '''Mario''' in the sales brochure.<ref name=tafa_dkusflyer>{{cite web|url=http://flyers.arcade-museum.com/?page=thumbs&db=videodb&id=316|title=Donkey Kong|website=The Arcade Flyers Archive}}</ref> Miyamoto originally named the character \"Mr. Video\", and he was to be used in every video game Miyamoto developed.<ref name=\"yahoo\">{{cite web|url=http://videogames.yahoo.com/events/playback/playback-93/1378336|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091211223939/http://videogames.yahoo.com/events/playback/playback-93/1378336|archivedate=December 11, 2009|title=Playback 93|date=December 2, 2009|publisher=Yahoo|accessdate=December 24, 2009}}</ref> According to a widely circulated story, during localization of ''Donkey Kong'' for American audiences, Nintendo of America's warehouse landlord [[Mario Segale]] confronted then-president [[Minoru Arakawa]], demanding back rent. Following a heated argument in which the Nintendo employees eventually convinced Segale he would be paid, they opted to name the character in the game Mario after him.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://technologizer.com/2010/04/25/mario/|title= The True Face of Mario |last= Edwards |first= Benj |date= April 25, 2010|work= [[Technologizer]] |accessdate=June 30, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title= Powerful Segale family has massive vision for Tukwila expanse |author= Eric Pryne |url= http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/businesstechnology/2011460764_segale28.html |newspaper= [[The Seattle Times]] |date= March 27, 2010 |accessdate=June 30, 2011}}</ref>\n\nMiyamoto commented that if he had named Mario \"Mr. Video\", Mario likely would have \"disappeared off the face of the Earth\".<ref name=\"wii-com1\"/> By Miyamoto's own account, Mario's profession was chosen to fit with the game design. Since ''Donkey Kong'' was set on a construction site, Mario was made into a carpenter. When he appeared again in ''[[Mario Bros.]]'', it was decided he should be a plumber, since a lot of the game is played in underground settings.<ref name=\"usatoday\">{{cite news|url=http://content.usatoday.com/communities/gamehunters/post/2010/11/qa-mario-creator-shigeru-miyamoto/1|title=Q&A: 'Mario' creator Shigeru Miyamoto|date=November 8, 2010|accessdate=November 9, 2010|author=Mike Snider|work=[[USA Today]]}}</ref> Mario's character design, particularly his large nose, draws on western influences; once he became a plumber, Miyamoto decided to \"put him in [[New York City|New York]]\" and make him Italian,<ref name=\"usatoday\" /> lightheartedly attributing Mario's nationality to his mustache.<ref name=\"IGN Miyamoto Interview\">{{cite web|last=Kohler|first=Chris|title=Q&A: 90 Minutes With Miyamoto, Nintendo\u2019s Master of Amusement|url=https://www.wired.com/gamelife/2008/06/interview-90-mi/|website=IGN.com|accessdate=July 30, 2010|date=June 27, 2008}}</ref> Other sources have Mario's profession chosen to be carpenter in an effort to depict the character as an ordinary hard worker, and make it easier for players to identify with him.<ref name=\"mariomania\">[[Minoru Arakawa|Arakawa, Minoru]] (1991). Mario Mania. Nintendo. pp. 30\u201332. [[ASIN]] B000BPL42C.</ref> After a colleague suggested that Mario more closely resembled a plumber, Miyamoto changed Mario's profession accordingly and developed ''Mario Bros.'',<ref name=\"ign\" /> featuring the character in the sewers of New York City.<ref>Grajqevci, Jeton (October 9, 2000). [http://www.n-sider.com/contentview.php?contentid=223 Profile: Shigeru Miyamoto]. N-Sider. Retrieved May 6, 2009</ref>\n\nDue to the graphical limitations of arcade hardware at the time, Miyamoto clothed the character in red overalls and a blue shirt to contrast against each other and the background. A red cap was added to let Miyamoto avoid drawing the character's hairstyle, forehead, and eyebrows, as well as to circumvent the issue of animating his hair as he jumped.<ref name=\"ign\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2010/09/14/ign-presents-the-history-of-super-mario-bros|title=IGN Presents: The History of Super Mario Bros.|author=McLaughlin, Rus|date=September 13, 2010|website=IGN|accessdate=June 24, 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"usatoday\" /> To give distinctly human facial features on an 8\u00d78 pixel head, Miyamoto drew a large nose and a mustache, which avoided the need to draw a mouth and facial expressions.<ref name=\"CNN\">Rao, Anjali (February 15, 2007). [http://www.cnn.com/2007/WORLD/asiapcf/02/14/miyamoto.script/index.html Sigeru Miyamao Talk Asia interview]. [[CNN]]. Retrieved February 28, 2009</ref>\n\nMiyamoto envisioned a \"go to\" character that could be put into any game as needed, albeit in cameo appearances, as at the time Miyamoto was not expecting the character to become singularly popular.<ref name=\"yahoo\"/> To this end, he originally called the character \"Mr. Video\", comparing his intent for appearances in later games to the cameos that [[Alfred Hitchcock]] had done within his films.<ref name=\"wii-com2\">{{cite web |url=http://iwataasks.nintendo.com/interviews/#/wii/nsmb/0/1 |title=Iwata Asks: New Super Mario Bros. |work=Wii.com |publisher=[[Nintendo]] |accessdate=June 24, 2013 |page=2}}</ref> Over time, Mario's appearance has become more defined; blue eyes, white gloves, brown shoes, a red \"M\" in a white circle on the front of his hat and gold buttons on his overalls have been added. The colors of his shirt and overalls were also reversed from a blue shirt with red overalls to a red shirt with blue overalls. Miyamoto attributed this process to the different development teams and artists for each game as well as advances in technology.<ref name=\"mariomania\" />\n\n==Appearances==\n{{main|List of Mario video games}}\n\n===1981\u20131990===\n[[File:SMB Supermario.png|thumb|Mario's idle [[Sprite (computer graphics)|sprite]] from ''[[Super Mario Bros.]]'' (1985).]]\n[[File:MarioSMBWalk.gif|thumb|Mario's walking sprite animation from ''Super Mario Bros.'' (1985).]]\n\nMario debuted as \"Jumpman\" in the arcade game ''[[Donkey Kong (video game)|Donkey Kong]]'' on July 9, 1981.<ref>{{cite journal |title=Retro Diary |journal=[[Retro Gamer]] |issue=104 |date=July 2012 |page=13 |issn=1742-3155 |oclc=489477015}}</ref> He is shown to be a carpenter and has a pet ape called Donkey Kong.<ref name=\"Kohler 39\">{{cite book |title=Power-Up: How Japanese Video Games Gave the World an Extra Life |last=Kohler |first=Chris |year=2005 |publisher=Brady Games |isbn=978-0-7440-0424-3 |page=39 }}</ref> The carpenter mistreats the ape and [[Donkey Kong (character)|Donkey Kong]] escapes to kidnap Jumpman's girlfriend, originally known as the Lady, but later named [[Recurring characters in the Mario series#Pauline|Pauline]]. The player must take the role of Jumpman and rescue the girl.\n\nJumpman was later renamed \"Mario\" in the 1982 arcade game ''[[Donkey Kong Jr.|Donkey Kong Junior]]'', the only game in which he has been portrayed as an antagonist. In the 1983 arcade game ''[[Mario Bros.]]'', Mario and his younger brother [[Luigi]] are portrayed as [[Italian-American]]<ref name=\"usatoday\" /> plumbers<ref name=\"mbvc\">{{cite web |title=Mario Bros. at Nintendo \u2013 Wii \u2013 Virtual Console |url=https://www.nintendo.com/games/detail/AN20FWaWbXNL-oWwUHwK0sMxrfq_plpD |publisher=[[Nintendo]] |accessdate=June 24, 2013 |website= |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181016175051/https://www.nintendo.com/games/detail/AN20FWaWbXNL-oWwUHwK0sMxrfq_plpD |archive-date=October 16, 2018 |url-status=dead }}</ref> who have to defeat creatures that have been coming from the sewers below [[New York City]].\n\nIn ''[[Super Mario Bros.]]'' for the [[Nintendo Entertainment System]], Mario saves [[Princess Peach|Princess Toadstool]] (later known as Princess Peach) of the [[Mushroom Kingdom]] from [[Bowser (character)|King Koopa]].<ref name=\"Booklet 7\">{{cite book| title = Super Mario Bros. Instruction Booklet| section = | publisher = [[Nintendo|Nintendo of America]]| year = 1986}}</ref> To save Princess Toadstool, Mario conquers the eight worlds of the Mushroom Kingdom by going to the castle in each to defeat a minion of King Koopa. To reach each castle, Mario battles through three sub-worlds by defeating King Koopa's henchmen. If Mario successfully fights his way through the castle and defeats the minion, he frees a [[Toad (Nintendo)|Mushroom Retainer]].{{citation needed|date=April 2018}} Inside the eighth castle, Mario has a final fight with King Koopa and frees Princess Toadstool. In ''[[Super Mario Bros. 2]]'', the player can choose between Mario, [[Luigi]], [[Toad (Nintendo)|Toad]], or [[Princess Peach]]. Each character possesses unique abilities (Luigi has stronger jumping ability, Toad can dig the fastest, and Peach can float), with Mario being the most well-rounded. In ''[[Super Mario Bros. 3]]'', Mario quests to save the rulers of seven kingdoms from [[Bowser (character)|Bowser]] and his children, the [[Koopalings]], and Mario travels across eight worlds to restore order to the Mushroom World and to rescue Princess Peach.<ref name=\"Manual-2\">{{cite book| title = Super Mario Bros. 3 Instruction Booklet| section = The Eight Kingdoms| publisher = [[Nintendo|Nintendo of America]]| date = February 12, 1990}}</ref> Mario is introduced to new [[power-up]]s that augment his abilities.<ref>{{cite journal| journal = [[Nintendo Power]]| title = Super Mario Bros. 3: Strategy Guide on the Way| issue = 12|date=May\u2013June 1990| pages = 94\u201395}}</ref>\n\n===1989\u20131995===\nIn ''[[Super Mario Land]]'', an alien named Tatanga appears, hypnotizes the inhabitants of an area called Sarasaland, and kidnaps its ruler, [[Princess Daisy (Nintendo)|Princess Daisy]]. Mario sets out to rescue her, traveling through the four geographical areas of Sarasaland and defeating Tatanga's minions along the way. He corners Tatanga in the skies of the Chai kingdom, bringing down the alien warship and rescuing Daisy.<ref>{{cite book | author=Nintendo | year=1989 | title=Super Mario Land Instruction Booklet | publisher=Nintendo of America, Inc. }}</ref> In ''[[Super Mario World]]'', Mario and Luigi take [[Princess Peach]] for a vacation in Dinosaur World sometime after the events of ''[[Super Mario Bros. 3]]''; during the vacation, Peach is kidnapped by [[Bowser (character)|Bowser]]. Mario and Luigi meet the [[Yoshi]]s, dinosaurs that live in Dinosaur World, and they help rescue Peach by allowing Mario and Luigi to ride them.<ref name=\"booklet\">{{cite book|title=Super Mario World Instruction Booklet|publisher=Nintendo}}</ref>\n\nIn ''[[Super Mario Land 2: 6 Golden Coins]]'', whose events take place immediately after the original ''Super Mario Land'', Mario's evil counterpart [[Wario]] has put an evil spell over Mario Land while Mario was away in Sarasaland, renaming the area Wario Land. The inhabitants are brainwashed into thinking that Wario is their master and Mario is their enemy. Wario's motive behind this sudden attack was to take control over Mario's castle in order to have one of his own. To stop Wario, Mario finds the 6 Golden Coins throughout Mario Land and regains access to his castle. In ''[[Super Mario World 2: Yoshi's Island]]'', a [[stork]] carries Baby Mario and Baby Luigi across the sea, but the evil Magikoopa [[Kamek]] steals Baby Luigi, and Baby Mario falls onto an island called Yoshi's Island, home to Yoshis. After Mario meets the Yoshis, the group journeys through the game's six worlds to rescue Baby Luigi and the stork from Baby Bowser and Kamek.\n\n===1996\u20132002===\n[[File:Mario64 - Dire Dire Docks.png|thumb|''[[Super Mario 64]]'' (1996) featured Mario's first [[3D computer graphics|3D]] rendering.]]\n\nMario made his [[3D computer graphics|3D]] debut in ''[[Super Mario 64]]'' for the [[Nintendo 64]].<ref>{{cite web| title = FEATURE: Galaxy Quest| work = [[Edge (magazine)|Edge]]| date = September 25, 2007| url = http://www.next-gen.biz/features/feature-galaxy-quest| archive-url = https://archive.today/20120908022305/http://www.next-gen.biz/features/feature-galaxy-quest| url-status = dead| archive-date = September 8, 2012| accessdate = February 16, 2010}}</ref> [[Princess Peach]] sends Mario a letter inviting him to join her at her castle for cake;<ref>Princess Peach's note: Dear Mario: Please come to the castle. I've baked a cake for you. Yours truly-- Princess Toadstool, Peach {{cite video game| title = Super Mario 64| developer = [[Nintendo EAD]]| publisher = Nintendo | date= September 29, 1996| platform= Nintendo 64}}</ref> however, when he arrives, Mario discovers that [[Bowser (character)|Bowser]] has invaded the castle and imprisoned the princess and her servants within it using the castle's 120 Power Stars. Many of the castle's paintings are portals to other worlds, in which Bowser's minions guard the stars. Mario explores the castle and other worlds to recover the stars. He gains access to more painting portals as he recovers more stars,<ref name=\"NP88\">{{Cite journal| date= September 1996| title= Full Coverage&nbsp;\u2014 Super Mario 64| journal= [[Nintendo Power]]| issue= 88| pages= 14\u201323}}</ref> and he traverses three obstacle courses that lead him to battles with Bowser. Defeating Bowser the first two times earns Mario keys that open new levels of the castle,<ref name=\"playersguide\"/> while the final battle releases Peach, who rewards Mario by baking the cake that she promised him.<ref name=\"playersguide\">{{cite book|year=1996|title=Official Super Mario 64 Player's Guide|publisher=Nintendo}}</ref><ref name=\"instructions\">{{cite book| year=1996|title=Super Mario 64 Instruction Booklet| publisher=Nintendo| id=NUS-NSME-USA}}</ref>\n\nIn ''[[Super Mario Sunshine]]'', Mario, [[Toadsworth]], and [[Princess Peach]] take a vacation to Isle Delfino, a [[tropical island]]. A person resembling Mario, known as \"Shadow Mario\", vandalizes and pollutes the entire island using a magic [[paintbrush]]. The vandalism has caused the Shine Sprites to flee from the island's main city, Delfino Plaza, and blanket the island in darkness. Blamed for the mess, Mario is arrested by the island authorities and ordered to clean up Isle Delfino. Mario is equipped with FLUDD, a robotic [[Hose|hosing]] device invented by [[Professor E. Gadd]], which he uses to clean up the pollution and collect the Shine Sprites.<ref>{{cite book|year=2002 |title=Super Mario Sunshine instruction booklet |publisher=Nintendo |pages=20\u201323}}</ref> Meanwhile, Peach is kidnapped by Shadow Mario, who reveals himself to be [[Bowser Jr.]], one of Bowser's children, having stolen the paintbrush from Professor E. Gadd. Mario eventually confronts Bowser and Bowser Jr. and rescues the princess. With the island cleaned up, Mario and Peach begin their vacation.<ref>{{cite video game|quote=FLUDD: The vacation starts now! |title=Super Mario Sunshine |developer=Nintendo EAD |publisher=Nintendo |date=August 26, 2002 |platform=Nintendo GameCube}}</ref>\n\n===2006\u2013present===\nMario went to [[2.5D]] in ''[[New Super Mario Bros.]]'' While Mario and Peach take a walk together through the Mushroom Kingdom, [[Bowser Jr.]] kidnaps Peach and flees.<ref name=manual>{{cite book|title=New Super Mario Bros. manual|publisher=Nintendo|page=10|date=May 16, 2006}}</ref> Mario gives chase, venturing through eight worlds. Mario eventually catches up, defeating both Bowser and Bowser Jr. and rescuing Peach.<ref name=game>{{cite video game|title=New Super Mario Bros|developer=Nintendo EAD|publisher=Nintendo|platform=Nintendo DS|date=May 15, 2006 }}</ref> In ''[[Super Mario Galaxy]]'', Mario is invited by Princess Peach to the [[centennial]] Star Festival in the [[Mushroom Kingdom]].<ref>{{cite book| title = Super Mario Galaxy Instruction Booklet| section = Prologue | publisher = [[Nintendo|Nintendo of America]]| year = 2007}}</ref> Upon arrival, [[Bowser (character)|Bowser]] invades the kingdom and rips Peach's castle from its foundations and lifts it into [[outer space]]. After failing to prevent the princess from being kidnapped, Mario meets star-like creatures called Lumas and their companion, [[Rosalina (Mario)|Rosalina]]. Rosalina tells Mario that Bowser has stolen the Power Stars, the source of power for Rosalina's mobile [[observatory]], and has taken Peach to the center of the universe. Mario then travels to various [[galaxies]] to reclaim the Power Stars to restore power to the observatory and reclaim Princess Peach.<ref>{{cite web| last = Casamassina| first = Matt| title = Super Mario Galaxy Review| website = IGN| date = November 7, 2007| url = http://wii.ign.com/articles/833/833298p1.html| pages= 1\u20132| accessdate = January 25, 2009}}</ref>\n\nIn ''[[New Super Mario Bros. Wii]]'', another [[2.5D]] game, Mario, Luigi, and two Toads are attending Princess Peach's birthday party when Bowser Jr. and the other seven [[Koopaling]]s ambush the princess and kidnap her. Mario, Luigi, and the two Toads chase after them across eight worlds, defeating each Koopaling as they progress. The quartet eventually confronts Bowser, defeating him and saving the princess.<ref>{{cite magazine|title=New Super Mario Bros. Wii: Your Questions Answered! |magazine=[[Official Nintendo Magazine]] |url=http://www.officialnintendomagazine.co.uk/article.php?id=12629 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091025102607/http://www.officialnintendomagazine.co.uk/article.php?id=12629 |url-status=dead |archive-date=October 25, 2009 |date=October 23, 2009 |accessdate=November 11, 2009 }}</ref> In ''[[Super Mario Galaxy 2]]'', Bowser, who has transformed himself into a giant using the Power Stars, attacks the Mushroom Kingdom and abducts Peach, taking her to the center of the universe. With the help of the Lumas, Mario pilots Starship Mario, a mobile planet in the shape of his head, in order to travel to various galaxies and gather the Power Stars, used to fuel the ship. After multiple battles against both Bowser and Bowser Jr., Mario eventually arrives at Bowser's lair at the center of the universe, where he defeats him and rescues the princess.<ref>{{cite web|author=Matt Wales |url=http://uk.wii.ign.com/articles/109/1096123p1.html |title=Super Mario Galaxy 2 \u2013 Wii Review |publisher=Uk.wii.ign.com |date=June 10, 2010 |accessdate=August 20, 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn 2012, Mario returned in ''[[New Super Mario Bros. 2]]'' where he collects several coins scattered across the Mushroom Kingdom in addition to saving Princess Peach from the evil clutches of Bowser and the Koopalings. Mario returns to defeat Bowser and his minions in ''[[New Super Mario Bros. U]]''. Mario is one of the playable characters in ''[[Super Mario 3D World]]'', where he has average running speed and jump height compared to other characters. Mario is the protagonist of the [[Nintendo Switch]] game ''[[Super Mario Odyssey]]'', where the character Cappy replaces Mario's traditional hat, allowing Mario to throw it like a long-range weapon, and \"capture\" enemies to gain their abilities.\n\n===Other ''Mario'' games===\n''Mario'' games of other genres include various ''[[Game & Watch]]'' games; ''[[Mario Pinball Land]]'', a [[pinball]] game for the Game Boy Advance;<ref>{{cite web| last = Byron| first = Tom| title = Mario Pinball Land (Game Boy Advance)| website = [[1UP.com]]| date = November 20, 2004| url = http://www.1up.com/do/reviewPage?cId=3147289&p=19| archive-url = https://archive.today/20120723155031/http://www.1up.com/do/reviewPage?cId=3147289&p=19| url-status = dead| archive-date = July 23, 2012| accessdate = January 25, 2010}}</ref> various educational games; and the ''[[Dr. Mario (video game)|Dr. Mario]]'' [[puzzle video game]], (with ''Dr. Mario'' itself first released in 1990).<ref name=\"drmario\" /> In these games, Dr. Mario throws [[vitamins]] that the player must align to destroy the [[viruses]] that populate the playing field.<ref name=\"drmario\">{{cite web| title = Dr. Mario| website = IGN| url = http://cheats.ign.com/objects/007/007157.html| accessdate = January 24, 2010}}</ref> 1996's ''[[Super Mario RPG]]'' is the first ''Mario'' [[role-playing game]];<ref>{{cite magazine|last=East |first=Tom |title=Virtual Console Review: Super Mario RPG |magazine=[[Official Nintendo Magazine]] |date=September 19, 2008 |url=http://www.officialnintendomagazine.co.uk/5883/reviews/super-mario-rpg-review/ |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110518115539/http://www.officialnintendomagazine.co.uk/5883/reviews/super-mario-rpg-review/ |url-status=dead |archive-date=May 18, 2011 |accessdate=February 17, 2010 }}</ref> ten games have followed, including five in the ''[[List of Mario role-playing games|Paper Mario]]'' series (''[[Paper Mario]]'' for the Nintendo 64, ''[[Paper Mario: The Thousand-Year Door]]'' for the GameCube, ''[[Super Paper Mario]]'' for the Wii, ''[[Paper Mario: Sticker Star]]'' for the Nintendo 3DS, and ''[[Paper Mario: Color Splash]]'' for the Wii U) and six in the ''[[List of Mario role-playing games|Mario & Luigi]]'' series (''[[Mario & Luigi: Superstar Saga]]'' for the Game Boy Advance, ''[[Mario & Luigi: Partners in Time]]'' and ''[[Mario & Luigi: Bowser's Inside Story]]'' for the Nintendo DS, ''[[Mario & Luigi: Dream Team]]'', ''[[Mario & Luigi: Paper Jam]]'', and [[Mario & Luigi: Superstar Saga|''Mario & Luigi: Superstar Saga + Bowser's Minions'']] for the Nintendo 3DS).\n\nSeveral other sub-series of ''Mario'' video games, especially those inspired from [[sports]], have been released. The ''[[Mario Kart]]'' franchise, which began with ''[[Super Mario Kart]]'' for the Super Nintendo Entertainment System in 1992, is the most successful and longest-running [[kart racing]] franchise.<ref name=\"Sutra M#1\">{{cite web | last = Jenkins | first = David | title = Mario Tops Best Selling Game Franchise List | website = [[Gamasutra]] | date = January 10, 2007 | url = http://www.gamasutra.com/php-bin/news_index.php?story=12349 | accessdate = January 1, 2009}}</ref> Other ''Mario'' sports games include the [[Camelot Software Planning|Camelot]]-developed series ''[[Mario Golf]]'' and ''[[Mario Tennis]]'', and, respectively, the [[baseball]] and [[soccer]] games ''[[Mario Superstar Baseball]]'' and ''[[Super Mario Strikers]]''. In 1999, [[Hudson Soft]] developed the ''[[Mario Party]]'' series, which began on the Nintendo 64. The games revolve around a set of [[minigames]] and are playable with up to four players.\n\n''[[Mario & Sonic at the Olympic Games]]'', released for both Nintendo DS and Wii, is a collection of 24 events based on the [[2008 Summer Olympic Games]] from [[Beijing]], in which characters from [[Sega]]'s [[Sonic the Hedgehog|''Sonic the Hedgehog'' series]] compete with ''Mario'' characters. This was followed in 2009 by ''[[Mario & Sonic at the Olympic Winter Games]]'' on both systems, based on the [[2010 Winter Olympics]] in [[Vancouver]]. Two more sports games for the Wii were released in 2011, ''[[Mario Sports Mix]]'' and the third ''Mario & Sonic'' game, ''[[Mario & Sonic at the London 2012 Olympic Games]]'' while the latter was released for the [[Nintendo 3DS]] in February 2012, which is based on the [[2012 Summer Olympics]] in [[London]]. The fourth edition of the ''Mario & Sonic'' series for the [[Wii U]] is called ''[[Mario & Sonic at the Sochi 2014 Olympic Winter Games]]'', which is based on the [[2014 Winter Olympics]] in [[Sochi]]. A fifth game, ''[[Mario & Sonic at the Rio 2016 Olympic Games]]'', based on the [[2016 Summer Olympics]] in [[Rio de Janeiro]], was released in 2016 for the [[Nintendo 3DS]], [[Wii U]] and [[Arcade game|Arcade]].\n\n===In other media===\n[[File:Mario SSBU.png|thumb|Artwork of Mario from ''[[Super Smash Bros. Ultimate]]''.]]\nApart from his platformer and spin-off game appearances, Mario has made guest appearances in non-''Mario'' games, such as ''[[Punch-Out!! (NES)|Mike Tyson's Punch-Out!!]]'', where Mario is a [[referee]].<ref>{{cite web| last = Pigna| first = Kris| title = Mario Included in NES Punch-Out!! Without Miyamoto's Permission| website = [[1UP.com]]| date = August 9, 2009| url = http://www.1up.com/do/newsStory?cId=3175501| archive-url = https://archive.today/20120718043018/http://www.1up.com/do/newsStory?cId=3175501| url-status = dead| archive-date = July 18, 2012| accessdate = January 28, 2009}}</ref> Mario appears as a playable character in ''[[NBA Street V3]]''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gamespot.com/news/2005/01/05/news_6115715.html |archive-url=http://web.archive.bibalex.org/web/20050112112705/http://www.gamespot.com/news/2005/01/05/news_6115715.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=January 12, 2005 |title=Mario to hoop it up in NBA Street V3 |website=GameSpot |accessdate=May 4, 2009 }}</ref> and ''[[SSX on Tour]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gamespot.com/gamecube/sports/ssx4/news.html?sid=6132098&mode=previews |title=SSX On Tour Character Spotlight: Mario, Luigi, and Peach |website=GameSpot |accessdate=May 4, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060114224521/http://www.gamespot.com/gamecube/sports/ssx4/news.html?sid=6132098 |archivedate=January 14, 2006 }}</ref> He makes countless cameo appearances in many forms in many games, such as portraits and statues in ''[[The Legend of Zelda: A Link to the Past]]'', ''[[The Legend of Zelda: Ocarina of Time]]'', and ''[[Metal Gear Solid: The Twin Snakes]]''.<ref>{{cite web| url = http://mentalfloss.com/article/553600/nintendo-fans-mispronouncing-nes | title=9 Hidden Mario Cameos and References in Videogames | last=Obias | first=Rubie | access-date = August 8, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Television===\nThe first appearance of Mario in media other than games was ''[[Saturday Supercade]]'', an animated television series produced by Ruby-Spears Productions in 1983. Each episode was composed of several shorter segments featuring video game characters from the golden age of video arcade games. Mario (voiced by [[Peter Cullen]]) appeared in Donkey Kong segments where he and Pauline tried to recapture Donkey Kong.\n\nMario stars in ''[[The Super Mario Bros. Super Show!]]'', played by [[Lou Albano|\"Captain\" Lou Albano]].\n\nMario stars in ''[[The Adventures of Super Mario Bros. 3]]'' and ''[[Super Mario World (TV series)|Super Mario World]]'', voiced by Walker Boone.\n\n===Film===\nMario appears in the [[live-action]] film ''[[Super Mario Bros. (film)|Super Mario Bros.]]'' as played by [[Bob Hoskins]]. Mario finds himself in an alternate universe in which dinosaurs rule where he must save the Earth from invasion. The film was a commercial failure at the box office.<ref>{{cite web|title=At the Movies:Super Mario Bros. |url=http://bventertainment.go.com/tv/buenavista/ebertandroeper/index2.html?sec=6&subsec=Super+Mario+Bros. |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5mr94yVaA?url=http://bventertainment.go.com/tv/buenavista/ebertandroeper/index2.html?sec=6 |archivedate=January 17, 2010 |accessdate=January 25, 2010 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nOutside the original games, television shows, and film, Mario has influenced the creation of a line of licensed merchandise and has appeared in popular culture. The Nintendo Comics System series, along with the [[Nintendo Adventure Books]], were created due to Mario as well.{{citation needed|date=October 2014|reason=Nintendo Adventure Books article does not correlate this.}}\n\n===Theme parks===\nMario will appear at [[Universal Studios Japan]] in [[Osaka]] in the upcoming section of [[Super Nintendo World]], which is scheduled to open in 2020 in time of the [[2020 Summer Olympics]] in [[Tokyo]]. One of the rides will be themed to ''[[Mario Kart]]''. [[Universal Parks & Resorts]] also has plans to import Super Nintendo World to [[Universal Studios Hollywood]] in [[Los Angeles|Los Angeles, California]] and [[Universal Orlando]] Resort in [[Orlando, Florida]].\n\n==Characteristics==\nMario is depicted as a portly plumber who lives in the fictional land of the [[Mushroom Kingdom]] with [[Luigi]], his younger, taller brother.<ref name=\"ign\" /><ref name=\"mariobioign\"/><ref name=\"luigibioign\">{{cite web| title = Luigi Biography| website = IGN| url = http://stars.ign.com/objects/924/924288_biography.html| accessdate = January 26, 2010| url-status = dead| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20090817041854/http://stars.ign.com/objects/924/924288_biography.html| archivedate = August 17, 2009}}</ref> In the television series and film, Mario and Luigi are originally from [[Brooklyn|Brooklyn, New York]].<ref name=\"mariobioign\"/> Little is known of Mario's childhood, though the infant version of Mario, Baby Mario, first appeared in 1995 in ''[[Super Mario World 2: Yoshi's Island]]'', and has often appeared in Nintendo sports games since then. Baby Mario has a major role along with [[Luigi|Baby Luigi]] in ''[[Mario & Luigi: Partners in Time]]'' and appears in ''[[Yoshi's Island DS]]''. He, along with the adult Mario, is voiced by [[Charles Martinet]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Charles Martinet: Voice Over|url=http://www.charlesmartinet.com/voiceover.html|accessdate=March 16, 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Savage|first1=Mark|title=The actors hiding inside your video games|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/entertainment-arts-19664003|accessdate=July 3, 2017|work=BBC News}}</ref>\n\nHe wears a longsleeved red shirt, a pair of blue overalls with yellow buttons, brown shoes, white gloves and a red cap with a red \"M\" printed on a white circle. In ''[[Donkey Kong (video game)|Donkey Kong]]'', he wore a pair of red overalls, and a blue shirt. In ''[[Super Mario Bros.]]'', he wore a brown shirt with red overalls. He has blue eyes, and, like [[Luigi]], has brown hair, and a dark brown or black mustache. This consistent difference in color is attributed to being a relic from designing the characters for their original platforms, wherein certain features were actively distinguished while others had to be curtailed due to technical limitations.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://archive.beefjack.com/index.html?p=148496.html|title=BeefJack \u2013 An alternative gaming website \u2013 Video game news, reviews and features, from a different perspective.|website=archive.beefjack.com|access-date=November 2, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171107021606/http://archive.beefjack.com/index.html?p=148496.html|archive-date=November 7, 2017|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In a 2005 interview, Miyamoto stated that Mario's physical age was about 24\u201325 years old.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Mendelsohn |first1=Tom |title=Mario is only 24 years old, according to creator Shigeru Miyamoto |url=https://arstechnica.com/gaming/2016/09/mario-24-years-old/ |accessdate=August 6, 2018 |work=Ars Technica |date=September 30, 2016 |language=en-us}}</ref>\n\n=== Surname ===\nNintendo did not initially reveal Mario's full name. In a 1989 interview, his full name was stated not to be \"Mario Mario\" though it may be inferred from the title of the ''Mario Bros.'' series.<ref>{{cite episode |title=Inside Super Mario Bros |series=[[Inside Edition]] |first=Joel |last=Loy |network=[[CBS Television Distribution]] |airdate=1989}}</ref> The first notable use of \"Mario Mario\" is in the [[Super Mario Bros. (film)|1993 live-action film adaptation]]. This was again used in two of [[Prima Games|Prima]]'s official strategy guides, in 2000<ref>{{cite book |title=Mario Party 2: Prima's Official Strategy Guide |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=_XFa3rPUvSMC |date=2000|isbn=9780761527671 |last1=Tica |first1=Don |last2=Govia |first2=Mario De |last3=Pham |first3=Tri }}</ref> for ''[[Mario Party 2]]'' and in 2003<ref>{{cite book |title=Mario & Luigi: Superstar Saga : Prima's Official Strategy Guide |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=8bpFw-oJTqgC |date=2003 |page=21|isbn=9780761544234 |last1=Stratton |first1=Stephen |last2=Buchanan |first2=Levi }}</ref> for ''[[Mario and Luigi: Superstar Saga]]''. In 2012, after [[Charles Martinet]] voiced Mario declaring himself \"Mario Mario\" at the [[San Diego Comic-Con]],<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=AAjhjLuWbC8&t=1m15s |title=Mario reveals his last name & other tales \u2013 San Diego Comic Con 2012 |date=July 16, 2012 |quote=What's my last name? That's a very good question. That's right, it's Mario! My name's-a Mario Mario. Of course, my brother's name, a-Luigi Mario. And of course, my mama's-a Mama Mia Mario; my papa Papa Pio Mario. Of course, my grandmama Grandmama Mia Mario and my greatpapa et cetera, et cetera. Yeah, first name Mario, last name Mario. Yahoo!}}</ref> the next month [[Satoru Iwata]] said he had no last name,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://kotaku.com/5935721/super-marios-boss-doesnt-want-to-overdo-it-with-mr-video-game-and-wont-deceive-you-with-dlc |title=Nintendo Chief: Mario Is Part Of Gamers' DNA |date=August 17, 2012 |quote=Could that mean that Mario's last name is \"Video Game\"? No, Iwata replied. \"He does not have a last name.\"}}</ref> which [[Shigeru Miyamoto]] agreed with the month after.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gameinformer.com/b/features/archive/2012/09/24/miyamoto-tezuka-interview.aspx |title=Mario's Creators Answer Burning Questions About The Series |date=September 24, 2012 |access-date=December 20, 2017 |archive-url=https://archive.today/20130123161706/http://www.gameinformer.com/b/features/archive/2012/09/24/miyamoto-tezuka-interview.aspx |archive-date=January 23, 2013 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Two months after Iwata's death in July 2015, Miyamoto changed his stance September 2015 at the Super Mario Bros. 30th Anniversary festival, asserting that his name was indeed Mario Mario.<ref name=\"getnews.jp\">{{cite web |url=http://getnews.jp/archives/1144379 |date=September 14, 2015 |language=Japanese |title=\u3010\u885d\u6483\u4e8b\u5b9f\u3011\u3064\u3044\u306b\u4efb\u5929\u5802\u516c\u5f0f\u306e\u30de\u30ea\u30aa\u306e\u672c\u540d\u304c\u5224\u660e\uff01\u4efb\u5929\u5802\u306e\u4ee3\u8868\u53d6\u7de0\u5f79\u30fb\u5bae\u672c\u8302\u6c0f\u304c\u660e\u304b\u3059 |trans-title=[Impact] fact finally found real name of Nintendo official of Mario! Reveal the representative director, Shigeru Miyamoto of Nintendo}}</ref><ref name=\"nintendoeverything.com\">{{cite web |url=http://nintendoeverything.com/miyamoto-says-marios-full-name-is-mario-mario/ |title=Miyamoto says Mario's full name is \"Mario Mario\" |date=September 14, 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Occupation and hobbies===\nMario's occupation is plumbing, though in the original ''[[Donkey Kong (series)|Donkey Kong]]'' games he is a [[carpenter]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nintendo.co.uk/Corporate/Nintendo-History/Nintendo-History-625945.html|title=History of Nintendo Worldwide 1980\u20131990|publisher=[[Nintendo of Europe]]|year=2013|accessdate=June 24, 2013}}</ref> Mario has had several other occupations: in the ''[[Dr. Mario (video game)|Dr. Mario]]'' series of [[puzzle video game|puzzle games]], which debuted in 1990,<ref name=\"drmario\" /> Mario is portrayed as a medical physician named \"Dr. Mario\";<ref>{{cite web| title = Top Ten Mario Games| publisher = [[GameTrailers]]| date = July 24, 2007| url = http://www.gametrailers.com/video/top-ten-screwattack/22754| accessdate = January 30, 2010}}</ref> in the [[Game Boy]] game ''[[Mario's Picross]]'', Mario is an [[Archaeology|archaeologist]]; and in ''[[Mario vs. Donkey Kong 2: March of the Minis]]'', Mario is the president of a profitable toy-making company.<ref>{{cite book| title = Mario vs. Donkey Kong 2: March of the Minis Instruction Booklet| section = Story and Characters| publisher = [[Nintendo|Nintendo of America]]| date = September 25, 2006}}</ref> Mario is an athlete in [[List of Mario sports games|''Mario'' sports games]] including ''[[Mario Sports Mix]]'', ''[[Mario Strikers Charged]]'', and ''[[Mario Tennis Aces]]''; as well as a [[kart racer]] in the ''[[Mario Kart]]'' series. Mario usually saves [[Princess Peach]] and the [[Mushroom Kingdom]] and purges antagonists, such as [[Bowser (character)|Bowser]], from various areas. Mario has gained fame in the Mushroom Kingdom due to his heroic deeds, as shown in ''[[Mario & Luigi: Superstar Saga]]'', where the brothers are referred to as \"superstars\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://marioandluigi.gameboy.com/flash.jsp|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071021031417/http://marioandluigi.gameboy.com/flash.jsp|archivedate=October 21, 2007|title=Mario and Luigi: Superstar Saga|publisher=[[Nintendo]]}}</ref> In September 2017, Nintendo confirmed on their official Japanese profile for the character that Mario was no longer considered a plumber, most likely due to his various occupations and hobbies.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://kotaku.com/mario-is-officially-no-longer-a-plumber-1799118840|title=Mario Is Officially No Longer A Plumber|last=Ashcraft|first=Brian|website=Kotaku|date=September 4, 2017|accessdate=September 4, 2017}}</ref> However as of March 2018, the Japanese profile has since been changed to state that Mario's occupation is still a plumber.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://kotaku.com/mario-is-officially-a-plumber-again-1823545849|title=Mario Is Officially A Plumber Again|last=Schreier|first=Jason|website=Kotaku|date=March 6, 2018|accessdate=March 19, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Relationships===\nSince his first game, Mario has usually had the role of saving the [[damsel in distress]].<ref name=\"mariobioign\">{{cite web| title = Mario Biography| website = IGN| url = http://stars.ign.com/objects/923/923448_biography.html| accessdate = January 23, 2010| url-status = dead| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20091220083249/http://stars.ign.com/objects/923/923448_biography.html| archivedate = December 20, 2009}}</ref> Originally, he had to rescue his girlfriend [[Recurring characters in the Mario series#Pauline|Pauline]] in ''[[Donkey Kong (video game)|Donkey Kong]]'' from Donkey Kong.<ref name=\"dkhist\" /> Pauline was soon replaced by a new damsel in distress, [[Princess Peach]], in ''[[Super Mario Bros.]]'',<ref name=\"ign\" /> but returned in the [[Game Boy]] remake of ''[[Donkey Kong (Game Boy)|Donkey Kong]]'' in 1994, and in ''[[Mario vs. Donkey Kong 2: March of the Minis]]'' in 2006, although the character is now described as \"Mario's friend\".<ref name=\"Mario vs. DK 2\">{{cite web|url=http://uk.videogames.games.yahoo.com/ds/previews/mario-vs--donkey-kong-2--march-of-the-minis-902997.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110927233733/http://uk.videogames.games.yahoo.com/ds/previews/mario-vs--donkey-kong-2--march-of-the-minis-902997.html|archivedate=September 27, 2011|title=Mario vs. DK 2: March of the Minis|publisher=[[Yahoo! Games]]|accessdate=August 23, 2008}}</ref> Mario has rescued Princess Peach multiple times since ''Super Mario Bros.''<ref name=\"mariobioign\" /> In a [[role reversal]], Peach rescues Mario in ''[[Super Princess Peach]]''.<ref>{{cite web| last = Bozon| first = Mark | title = Hands-On: Super Princess Peach| website = IGN| date = February 1, 2006| url = http://ds.ign.com/articles/685/685051p1.html| accessdate = January 23, 2010}}</ref> Mario rescued [[Princess Daisy (Mario)|Princess Daisy]] of Sarasaraland in ''[[Super Mario Land]]'',<ref>{{cite web| title = Princess Daisy Biography| website = IGN| url = http://stars.ign.com/objects/963/963167_biography.html| accessdate = January 27, 2009| url-status = dead| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20071129224132/http://stars.ign.com/objects/963/963167_biography.html| archivedate = November 29, 2007}}</ref> but Luigi seems to be more linked to her. In ''[[Super Smash Bros. Melee]]'', the text explaining Daisy's trophy states that \"after her appearance in ''[[Mario Golf]]'', gossips portrayed her as Luigi's answer to Mario's Peach\".<ref>{{cite video game|title=Super Smash Bros. Melee|developer=HAL Laboratory|publisher=Nintendo|date=December 3, 2001|platform=Nintendo GameCube}}</ref>\n\n[[Luigi]] is Mario's younger fraternal twin brother.<ref name=\"luigibioign\" /> He is a companion in the ''Mario'' games,<ref name=\"luigibioign\" /> and the character whom the second player controls in two-player sessions of many of the video games,<ref name=\"luigiprofileign\">{{cite web| title = Luigi Profile| website = IGN| url = http://stars.ign.com/objects/924/924288.html| accessdate = January 26, 2010| url-status = dead| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20090225211747/http://stars.ign.com/objects/924/924288.html| archivedate = February 25, 2009}}</ref> though he occasionally rescues Mario, as seen in ''[[Mario Is Missing!]]'' and ''[[Luigi's Mansion]]''.<ref>{{cite web| last = Buchanan| first = Levi| title = The Other Mario Games, Vol. 2| website = IGN| date = August 7, 2008| url = http://retro.ign.com/articles/897/897225p1.html| accessdate = January 23, 2010}}</ref> ''[[Super Mario Land 2: 6 Golden Coins]]'' for the Game Boy saw the arrival of [[Wario]], Mario's greedy [[wikt:counterpart|counterpart]], who is often Mario's antagonist or an [[antihero]].<ref>{{cite web| title = Wario Biography| website = IGN| url = http://stars.ign.com/objects/924/924285_biography.html| accessdate = January 23, 2010| url-status = dead| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20090712120508/http://stars.ign.com/objects/924/924285_biography.html| archivedate = July 12, 2009}}</ref> [[Yoshi]] is a dinosaur whose species is also named Yoshi.<ref name=\"yoshibio\" /> They vary in color, though the original Yoshi is green.<ref name=\"yoshibio\">{{cite web | title =Yoshi Biography | url =http://stars.ign.com/objects/924/924294_biography.html | website =IGN | accessdate =January 23, 2009 | url-status =dead | archiveurl =https://web.archive.org/web/20100602142520/http://stars.ign.com/objects/924/924294_biography.html | archivedate =June 2, 2010 }}</ref> Yoshi serves as Mario's steed in games such as ''[[Super Mario World]]'',<ref name=\"yoshibio\" /> and is depicted as an independent character in games like ''[[Super Mario Kart]]'' and ''[[Super Mario World 2: Yoshi's Island]]''.\n\n=={{anchor|Ground pound|Wall jump|Spin jump}}Abilities==\nDuring the development of ''[[Donkey Kong (video game)|Donkey Kong]]'', Mario was known as ''Jumpman''.<ref name=\"ign\" /> Jumping\u2014both to access places and as an offensive move\u2014is a common gameplay element in ''Mario'' games, especially the ''[[Super Mario]]'' series. By the time ''[[Super Mario RPG]]'' was released, jumping became such a signature act of Mario that the player was often tasked with jumping to prove to [[non-player character]]s that he was Mario. Mario's most commonly portrayed form of attack is jumping to stomp on the heads of enemies, first used in ''[[Super Mario Bros.]]'' This jump-stomp move may entirely crush smaller enemies on the stage, and usually deals damage to larger ones, sometimes causing secondary effects.<ref name=\"ign\" />\n\nThis attack often enables Mario to knock the turtle-like [[Koopa Troopa]]s into or out of their shells, which can be used as weapons.<ref name=\"ign\" /> Subsequent games have elaborated on Mario's jumping-related abilities. ''[[Super Mario World]]'' added the ability to spin-jump, which allows Mario to break blocks beneath him. The Game Boy version of ''[[Donkey Kong (Game Boy)|Donkey Kong]]'' allows Mario to jump higher with consecutive jumps, and perform a back-flip. In ''[[Super Mario 64]]'', Mario gains new jumping abilities such as a sideways somersault; a ground pound, which is a high-impact downward thrusting motion; and the \"Wall Kick\", which propels him upwards by kicking off walls.\n\n===Power-ups===\n[[File:Tanooki Mario.jpg|upright|thumb|Mario seen wearing the Tanooki Suit. The suit is derived from the [[Japanese raccoon dog]], tanuki.]]\n\nMario uses items, which give him various powers, and differ between the games he is in. The first power-up Mario used was the Hammer in ''[[Donkey Kong (video game)|Donkey Kong]]''.<ref name=\"dkhist\">{{cite web|last=Trueman |first=Doug |title=GameSpot Presents: The History of Donkey Kong |website=[[GameSpot]] |url=http://www.gamespot.com/gamespot/features/video/dk_history/p03.html |archiveurl=http://web.archive.bibalex.org/web/20010710164559/http://gamespot.com/gamespot/features/video/dk_history/p03.html |archivedate=July 10, 2001 |accessdate=January 1, 2010 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n''[[Super Mario Bros.]]'' introduced the basic three power-ups that have become staples for the series, especially the 2D games \u2014 the Super Mushroom, which causes Mario to grow larger; the Fire Flower, which allows Mario to throw [[fire]]balls; and the Starman, which gives Mario temporary invincibility. These powers have appeared regularly throughout the series.<ref name=\"ign\" /> Throughout the series' history, there have been several kinds of Mushroom power-ups, including the [[1-up]] Mushroom, which gives Mario an extra life; the Poison Mushroom, which causes Mario to either shrink or die;<ref>{{cite web|last=Suellentrop |first=Chris |url=http://www.slate.com/id/2177082/ |title=Super Mario Bros.: The Lost Levels reviewed. \u2013 By Chris Suellentrop \u2013 Slate Magazine |work=Slate |date=November 5, 2007 |accessdate=April 4, 2009}}</ref> the Mega Mushroom, which causes Mario to grow very large; and the Mini Mushroom, which causes Mario to shrink.<ref>{{cite web|last=Harris |first=Craig |url=http://uk.ds.ign.com/articles/705/705537p2.html |title=IGN: New Super Mario Bros. Review |publisher=Uk.ds.ign.com |accessdate=April 4, 2009}}</ref>\n\nA reoccurring power-up throughout the series is an item that gives Mario the ability of flight. The first of this type was introduced in ''[[Super Mario Bros. 3]]'': one power-up, which gives Mario a raccoon suit, is called the Super Leaf,<ref>{{cite web|last=Provo |first=Frank |url=http://uk.gamespot.com/wii/action/supermariobros3/review.html |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090310191431/http://uk.gamespot.com/wii/action/supermariobros3/review.html |archivedate=March 10, 2009 |title=Super Mario Bros. 3 Review for Wii \u2013 GameSpot |publisher=Uk.gamespot.com |date=November 9, 2007 |accessdate=April 4, 2009}}</ref>  while another is called the Tanooki Suit (a transliteration of [[Japanese raccoon dog|tanuki]]) and grants Mario the ability to fly or turn into a statue.<ref name=\"ignsuits\">{{cite web| title = Top 10 Mario Suits| website = IGN| date = November 16, 2009| url = http://wii.ign.com/articles/104/1045630p1.html| accessdate = January 23, 2010| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20100309115558/http://wii.ign.com/articles/104/1045630p1.html| archive-date = March 9, 2010| url-status = dead| df = mdy-all}}</ref> In ''[[Super Mario World]]'', an item called the Cape Feather was introduced that gave Mario a cape.<ref>{{cite web|last=Navarro |first=Alex |url=http://uk.gamespot.com/wii/action/supermarioworldsnes/review.html |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070714100606/http://uk.gamespot.com/wii/action/supermarioworldsnes/review.html |archivedate=July 14, 2007 |title=Super Mario World for Wii Review \u2013 GameSpot |publisher=Uk.gamespot.com |date=February 9, 2007 |accessdate=April 4, 2009 |url-status=dead }}</ref> In ''[[Super Mario Land 2: 6 Golden Coins]]'', a carrot was available that gave Mario rabbit ears that allowed him to fly,<ref name=\"ignsuits\" /> and in ''[[Super Mario 64]]'', Mario could acquire an item called the Wing Cap, which temporarily gave him the ability of flight.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nintendo.com/games/detail/48czfMMYIp_0_alQYMIOS7sgrvUdDq1O |title=Super Mario 64 at Nintendo :: Wii :: Virtual Console :: Games |publisher=Nintendo.com |accessdate=June 24, 2013}}</ref> ''[[Super Mario Sunshine]]'' introduces a pump-water spraying device named \"F.L.U.D.D.\", which abilities included spraying water and hovering.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://uk.gamespot.com/gamecube/action/supermariosunshine/review.html?om_act=convert&om_clk=gssummary&tag=summary;read-review |archive-url=https://archive.today/20120716210856/http://uk.gamespot.com/gamecube/action/supermariosunshine/review.html?om_act=convert&om_clk=gssummary&tag=summary;read-review |url-status=dead |archive-date=July 16, 2012 |title=Super Mario Sunshine Review for GameCube \u2013 GameSpot |publisher=Uk.gamespot.com |date=October 4, 2002 |accessdate=April 4, 2009}}</ref>\n\n''[[Super Mario Galaxy]]'' introduced new power-ups, including the Bee Mushroom, which turned Mario into a bee and allowed him to fly temporarily; the Boo Mushroom, which turned Mario into a ghost, allowing him to float and pass through walls; the Spring Mushroom, which encased Mario in a spring, allowing him to jump higher; and the Ice Flower, which allowed the player to temporarily walk on water and lava without sinking or taking damage.<ref>{{cite book| title = Super Mario Galaxy Instruction Booklet| section = Mario's Special Moves | publisher = [[Nintendo|Nintendo of America]]| year = 2007}}</ref> ''[[Super Mario Galaxy 2]]'' introduced more power ups, including the Cloud Flower which allows Mario to create platforms in midair and Rock Mario, which transforms Mario into a boulder that could be used to break through barriers.<ref>{{cite book| title = Super Mario Galaxy 2 Instruction Booklet| section = Mario's Special Moves | publisher = [[Nintendo|Nintendo of America]]| year = 2010}}</ref>\n\n''[[New Super Mario Bros. Wii]]'' updated the Ice Flower, which allows Mario to shoot ice balls that temporally freeze enemies; and introduced the Propeller Mushroom, which allows him to fly; as well as the Penguin Suit, which allows Mario to easily traverse ice and swim through water in addition to shooting ice balls. ''[[Super Mario 3D Land]]'' introduced the Boomerang Flower, which allows Mario to throw boomerangs at nearby enemies; and the Statue Leaf, which allows Mario to turn to a statue. In ''[[New Super Mario Bros. U]]'', a Super Acorn makes its debut. This transforms Mario to his new [[Flying squirrel]] form where he can glide and stick on walls. ''[[Super Mario 3D World]]'' introduced the Super Bell, which transforms Mario into his cat form as well as a Double Cherry to make multiple copies of himself.\n\n=={{anchor | Reception and legacy}}Reception==\n\n===Critical response===\n[[File:Supermario Kungsbacka.jpg|thumb|upright|Mario in [[Kungsbacka]], Sweden]]\n\nAs Nintendo's primary mascot, Mario is widely considered to be the most famous video game character in history, and has been called an icon of the gaming industry.<ref name=\"History of Mario\">{{cite web|url=http://www.gamecubicle.com/features-mario-nintendo_shining_star.htm|title=Nintendo's Shining Star: The History of Mario|publisher=Gamecubicle|accessdate=August 23, 2008}}</ref><ref name=\"wired\" /><ref>{{cite web |last=Buchanan |first=Levi |title=Is There a Bad Mario Game? |website=IGN |date=February 13, 2009 |url=http://retro.ign.com/articles/954/954165p1.html |accessdate=January 23, 2010}}</ref> The ''Mario'' series of video games has sold more than 510 million copies, making it the [[List of best-selling video game franchises|best-selling video game franchise]].<ref name=\"ign\" /> Mario was one of the first video game character inductees at the [[Walk of Game]] in 2005, alongside [[Link (The Legend of Zelda)|Link]] and [[Sonic the Hedgehog (character)|Sonic the Hedgehog]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.walkofgame.com/inductees/inductees2005.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080121064109/http://www.walkofgame.com/inductees/inductees2005.html|archivedate=January 21, 2008|title=Past Inductees 2005 Games / Characters|publisher=[[Walk of Game]]|accessdate=February 21, 2008}}</ref> Mario was the first video game character to be honored with a wax figure in the [[Hollywood Wax Museum]] in 2003. In 1990, a national survey found that Mario was more recognizable to American children than [[Mickey Mouse]].<ref name=\"Recentering Globalization\">{{cite book|last=Iwabuchi|first=Koichi|title=Recentering globalization: Popular culture and Japanese transnationalism|publisher=Duke University Press|isbn=978-0-8223-2891-9|url=http://www.dukeupress.edu/Catalog/ViewProduct.php?productid=8083&viewby=title|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100709183746/http://www.dukeupress.edu/Catalog/ViewProduct.php?productid=8083&viewby=title|url-status=dead|archive-date=July 9, 2010|page=30|chapter=1. Taking Japanization seriously: Cultural globalization reconsidered|chapterurl=https://books.google.com/books/p/dukeupress?vid=978-0-8223-2891-9&pg=PA30|accessdate=February 20, 2017|date=2002-11-08}}</ref><ref>https://www.baltimoresun.com/news/bs-xpm-1993-05-18-1993138174-story.html</ref> Mario has also been called the \"most recognisable\" figure in the gaming industry.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://kotaku.com/5636283/happy-25th-birthday-super-mario-bros |title=Happy 25th Birthday, Super Mario Bros. |accessdate=October 18, 2010 |last=Plunkett |first=Luke |date=September 13, 2010 |publisher=Kotaku |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100921225033/http://kotaku.com/5636283/happy-25th-birthday-super-mario-bros |archivedate=September 21, 2010 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nCreator Shigeru Miyamoto has stated that Mario is his favorite out of all characters that he has created.<ref>{{cite magazine |title= Exclusive Interview With Nintendo Gaming Mastermind Shigeru Miyamoto |url=http://www.popularmechanics.com/technology/gadgets/video-games/4334387 |magazine=[[Popular Mechanics]] |accessdate=October 21, 2009 |date=October 19, 2009}}</ref> ''[[Electronic Gaming Monthly]]'' gave Mario their \"Coolest Mascot\" award for 1996, calling him \"an age-old friend.\"<ref>{{cite magazine |title=The Best of '96 |magazine=[[Electronic Gaming Monthly]] |issue=92|publisher=[[Ziff Davis]]|date=March 1997 |page=90}}</ref> ''[[Nintendo Power]]'' listed Mario as their favorite hero, citing his defining characteristics as his mustache, red cap, plumbing prowess, and his mushrooms.<ref>{{cite book |title=Nintendo Power 250th issue! |year=2010 |publisher=[[Future US]] |location=[[South San Francisco, California]] |pages=40, 41 |url= |title-link=Nintendo Power }}</ref> In a poll conducted in 2008 by [[Oricon]], Mario was voted the most popular video game character in Japan.<ref>{{cite web|author=Brian Ashcraft|title=And Japan's Favorite Video Game Characters Are...?|date=August 23, 2008|url=http://kotaku.com/5035884/and-japans-favorite-video-game-characters-are|accessdate=August 23, 2008|publisher=Kotaku}}</ref>\n\n[[GameDaily]] listed the \"unlikely hero\" on its top 25 video game archetypes, and used Mario as an example of this. It stated that in spite of the fact that he should have run out of energy through the first level, he kept going.<ref>{{cite web| last = Buffa| first = Chris| title = Top 25 Game Archetypes| publisher = [[GameDaily]]| date = January 23, 2009| url = http://www.gamedaily.com/articles/galleries/top-25-video-game-characters-archetypes/?page=25| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20181106132148/http://www.gamedaily.com/articles/galleries/top-25-video-game-characters-archetypes/?page=25| url-status = dead| archive-date = November 6, 2018| accessdate = January 1, 2010}}</ref> Mario ranked fourth on [[GameDaily]]'s top ten ''Smash Bros.'' characters list.<ref>{{cite web |title=Top 10 Smash Bros. Characters \u2013 Page 7 |url=http://www.gamedaily.com/articles/galleries/top-ten-super-smash-bros-characters/?page=7 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091023030816/http://www.gamedaily.com/articles/galleries/top-ten-super-smash-bros-characters/?page=7 |archivedate=October 23, 2009 |publisher=[[GameDaily]] |accessdate=August 7, 2009}}</ref> Mario was fourth on [[UGO]]'s list of the \"Top 100 Heroes of All Time\".<ref>{{cite web|author=Staff |date=September 24, 2007 |url=http://www.ugo.com/games/top-heroes-in-entertainment/shows.asp?groupID=shows20-1&showID=mario |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071011002607/http://www.ugo.com/games/top-heroes-in-entertainment/shows.asp?groupID=shows20-1&showID=mario |url-status=dead |archive-date=October 11, 2007 |title=Best Heroes of All Time: Mario |publisher=[[UGO Networks]] |accessdate=November 8, 2009 }}</ref> They also listed Mario's hat twenty-first on their list of \"The Coolest Helmets and Headgear in Video Games\", stating \"there's always somebody at your Halloween party wearing one.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ugo.com/games/the-coolest-helmets-and-headgear-in-video-games?page=2 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110311040052/http://www.ugo.com/games/the-coolest-helmets-and-headgear-in-video-games?page=2 |url-status=dead |archive-date=March 11, 2011 |title=The Coolest Helmets and Headgear in Video Games |publisher=[[UGO.com]] |author=Marissa Meli |date=March 4, 2011 |accessdate=March 21, 2011 }}</ref> [[CNET]] listed him first on its list of the \"Top 5 video game characters\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cnettv.cnet.com/8301-13415_53-10410413-11.html |title=Top 5 video game characters |date=December 7, 2009 |author=Tom Merritt |website=[[CNET]] |accessdate=April 25, 2010}}</ref> He was voted 100th in [[IGN]]'s Top 100 Villains for his appearance in ''[[Donkey Kong Junior]]'', adding \"This Mario is a total jerk, holding Donkey Kong Jr.'s dad hostage\",<ref>{{cite web|url=http://uk.ign.com/videogame-villains/100.html |title=Top 100 Villains| website=IGN |accessdate=May 13, 2010|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120106080555/http://uk.ign.com/videogame-villains/100.html|archivedate=January 6, 2012}}</ref> and he has also been elected by [[GamesRadar]] as the 90th \"most dastardly ne'er-do-wells\" villain in video games in their \"top 100\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gamesradar.com/top-100-villains-video-games/ |title=100 best villains in video games |date=May 17, 2013 |publisher=[[GamesRadar]] |accessdate=July 28, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.today/20130624192529/http://www.gamesradar.com/top-100-villains-video-games/ |archivedate=June 24, 2013 }}</ref>\n\n===Legacy===\n{{multiple image\n | align = right\n|direction=vertical\n | total_width =200\n\n | image1 = Cerim\u00f4nia de encerramento dos Jogos Ol\u00edmpicos Rio 2016 1039534-21082016- mg 8618 (cropped).jpg\n | width1 = 100 | height1 = 136\n | alt1 =\n | caption1 = Japanese prime minister [[Shinz\u014d Abe]] holding Mario's cap.\n\n | image2 = Cerim\u00f4nia de encerramento dos Jogos Ol\u00edmpicos Rio 2016 1039540-21082016- mg 8837.jpg\n | width2 = 200 | height2 = 156\n | alt2 =\n | caption2 = Dancers performing alongside an oversized Warp Pipe.\n\n | header= The [[2016 Summer Olympics closing ceremony#Warming up! Tokyo 2020|2016 Olympics closing ceremony]] featured Mario-inspired imagery.\n}}\n\nMario has been established as a [[popular culture|pop culture]] icon, and has starred in numerous television shows, comic books, and in a feature film. He has appeared on lunch boxes, T-shirts, magazines, commercials (notably, in a [[Got Milk?]] commercial),<ref>Weiss, Jodi & Kahn, Russell (2004). In ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=Mp0LRxu0ibsC&pg=PA25&dq=%22got+milk%22+mario&ei=-_b0Sr7sG5PyNJ3B1YoF#v=onepage&q=%22got%20milk%22%20mario&f=false 145 Things to Be When You Grow Up]''. Princeton Review Publishing. p. 25. {{ISBN|0-375-76369-4}}. Google Book Search. Retrieved November 6, 2009.</ref> in candy form, on shampoo bottles, cereal, badges, board games, and as a plush toy.<ref name=\"History of Mario\" /> Nintendo produced a 60-minute [[anime]] film based on the original ''Super Mario Bros.,'' ''[[Super Mario Bros.: Peach-Hime Kyushutsu Dai Sakusen!]],'' in 1986, although this film has not been released outside Japan and has not been released on any home video format except [[VHS]].\n\nThe animated series ''[[The Super Mario Bros. Super Show!]]'' featured a live-action series of skits which starred former WWF manager [[Lou Albano|\"Captain\" Lou Albano]] as Mario and [[Danny Wells]] as Luigi. Mario appeared in a book series, the [[Nintendo Adventure Books]]. Mario has inspired unlicensed paintings,<ref>{{cite web| title=10 Works of Art Inspired By ''Super Mario Bros.'' |url=http://pixelatedgeek.com/2009/04/10-works-of-art-inspired-by-super-mario-bros/ |publisher=Pixelated Geek |accessdate=May 5, 2009}}</ref> performances on [[talent show]]s such as ''[[India's Got Talent]]'',<ref>{{cite web|last=Ashcraft|first=Brian|title=India's Got Mario Talent|url=http://kotaku.com/5313073/indias-got-mario-talent|publisher=Kotaku|accessdate=May 17, 2012|date=July 13, 2009}}</ref> and short films, which have been viewed hundreds of thousands of times.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://kotaku.com/5870843/32-nintendo-fans-made-these-8-short-movies-in-24-hours/|title=32 Nintendo Fans made these 8 Short Movies in 24 Hours|last=Totilo|first=Stephen|date=December 23, 2011|accessdate=December 14, 2015}}</ref> The character has been present in a number of works created by third parties other than Nintendo, such as in the [[iOS]] and [[Android (operating system)|Android]] video game ''[[Platform Panic]]'', in which one of the purchasable skins is a reference to him.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gamezebo.com/2014/12/30/platform-panic-review-infinite-platforms-infinite-pleasure/|title=Platform Panic Review: Infinite Platforms, Infinite Pleasure|last=Spencer|first=Spanner|date=December 30, 2014|website=Gamezebo|access-date=July 4, 2016}}</ref>\n\nMany people and places have been named or nicknamed after Mario. [[Bergsala]], the distributor of Nintendo's products in the [[Nordic countries|Nordic]] and the [[Baltic countries]], is located at Marios Gata 21 (Mario's Street 21) in [[Kungsbacka]], [[Sweden]], named after Mario.<ref>{{cite web|title=Bergsala AB, Contact page|url=http://www.nintendo.se/kontakt|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100817232653/http://www.nintendo.se/kontakt|url-status=dead|archive-date=August 17, 2010|accessdate=June 24, 2013}}</ref> Many sports stars, including [[Bundesliga]] [[Association football|football]] players [[Mario G\u00f6tze]] and [[Mario G\u00f3mez]], [[National Hockey League]] player [[Mario Lemieux]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/sportscentury/features/00016068.html |title=ESPN.com: Mario was super despite the obstacles |publisher=ESPN |accessdate=April 4, 2009}}</ref> [[Football in Italy|Italian footballer]] [[Mario Balotelli]],<ref>[http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-1298803/Carlo-Ancelotti-Mario-Balotelli-win-title-Manchester-City.html Super Mario Balotelli can win title for Manchester City] ''Daily Mail'', July 29, 2010</ref> and Italian cyclist [[Mario Cipollini]] have been given the nickname \"Super Mario\". In a suburb of the Spanish city of [[Zaragoza]], streets were named after video games, including \"Avenida de Super Mario Bros\".<ref>{{cite news |last1=Shoichet |first1=Catherine E. |title=Spanish neighborhood unveils 'Super Mario' street |url=http://edition.cnn.com/2010/WORLD/europe/11/08/spain.super.mario.subdivision/index.html |accessdate=August 27, 2018 |publisher=CNN |date=November 8, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kotaku.com/2010/11/mario-gets-serious-street-cred-in-spain|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110713165342/http://www.kotaku.com/2010/11/mario-gets-serious-street-cred-in-spain|archivedate=July 13, 2011|title=What Were Your Greatest Gaming Moments of 2010?|author=Brian Crecente|publisher=Kotaku}}</ref>\n\nMario's legacy is recognized by [[Guinness World Records]], who awarded the Nintendo mascot, and the series of platform games he has appeared in, seven world records in the ''Guinness World Records: Gamer's Edition 2008''. These records include \"Best Selling Video Game Series of All Time\", \"First Movie Based on an Existing Video Game\", and \"Most Prolific Video Game Character\", with Mario appearing in 116 original games.<ref>{{cite book| editor= Craig Glenday| title= Guinness World Records Gamer's Edition 2008| series= [[Guinness World Records]]| date= March 11, 2008| publisher= Guinness| isbn= 978-1-904994-21-3| url= https://archive.org/details/guinnessworldrec00guin_0}}</ref> In 2011, readers of ''Guinness World Records Gamer's Edition'' voted Mario as the top video game character of all time.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.gameinformer.com/b/news/archive/2011/02/16/guinness-names-top-50-video-game-characters-of-all-time.aspx |title=Guinness Names Top 50 Video Game Characters Of All Time |newspaper=[[Game Informer]] |first=Jeff |last=Marchiafava |date=February 16, 2011 |access-date=February 2, 2018}}</ref>\n\nMario appeared in the [[2016 Summer Olympics closing ceremony]] to promote the [[2020 Summer Olympics]] in [[Tokyo]]. In a pre-recorded video, the prime minister [[Shinz\u014d Abe]] became Mario to use a [[Warp pipe]] planted by [[Doraemon (character)|Doraemon]] from [[Shibuya#Shibuya Crossing|Shibuya Crossing]] to [[Maracan\u00e3 Stadium]]. Abe then appeared dressed as Mario in an oversized Warp Pipe in the middle of the stadium.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Palazzo|first1=Chiara|title=Shinzo Abe emerges from a green pipe disguised as Super Mario during Rio Closing Ceremony|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/olympics/2016/08/22/shinzo-abe-emerges-from-a-green-pipe-disguised-as-super-mario-du/|accessdate=August 22, 2016|date=August 22, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"TIME.com\">{{cite news|url=http://time.com/4460923/super-mario-japan-prime-minister-shinzo-abe/|title=Shinzo Abe Dresses as Super Mario for Rio Closing Ceremony|date=August 22, 2016|work=Time|last1=Samuelson|first1=Kate|accessdate=August 22, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Palazzo|first1=Chiara|title=Shinzo Abe emerges from a green pipe disguised as Super Mario during Rio Closing Ceremony|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/olympics/2016/08/22/shinzo-abe-emerges-from-a-green-pipe-disguised-as-super-mario-du/|work=The Daily Telegraph|accessdate=August 22, 2016|date=August 22, 2016}}</ref>\n\nMario Day (previously known as National{{where|date=March 2020}} Mario Day) is celebrated on March 10,<ref>\n{{citation|author=Schuyler J. Dievendorf|url=http://www.escapistmagazine.com/articles/view/features/galleryoftheday/11094-8-Best-Ways-To-Celebrate-National-Mario-Day |title=8 Best Ways To Celebrate National Mario Day|work=[[The Escapist (magazine)|The Escapist]] |date=March 10, 2014 |accessdate=March 9, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{citation|url=http://www.4players.de/4players.php/spielinfonews/Allgemein/326/2156909/Nintendo-Video_zum_heutigen_National_Mario_Day.html |title=Nintendo: Video zum heutigen National Mario Day |author=Alice Wilczynski|publisher=[[4Players]] |date= March 10, 2016|accessdate=March 9, 2017 | language = German}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tristateupdate.com/story/31432843/national-mario-day|title=National Mario Day|publisher=Tristate Update, [[WOWK-TV]]|date=March 10, 2016|accessdate=March 9, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170312031758/http://www.tristateupdate.com/story/31432843/national-mario-day|archive-date=March 12, 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref> as when that date is presented as Mar 10 it resembles the name MARIO.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.timeanddate.com/holidays/fun/mario-day |title=Fun Holiday \u2013 Mario Day |publisher=Timeanddate.com |accessdate=March 9, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{citation|author=Dani Werner |url=http://www.startribune.com/jump-start-your-week/371088501/ |title=Jump-start your week with some items of interest |work=[[Star Tribune]] |date=March 7, 2016 |accessdate=March 9, 2017}}</ref> Since 2016, the day was officially observed by Nintendo,<ref>{{cite web|title=Celebrate Mar 10 - Mario Day!|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=uoj1d8x2H6c|website=YouTube|publisher=Nintendo (Nintendo of America)|accessdate=March 13, 2018}}</ref> and celebrates this day annually by promoting ''Mario'' games and holding ''Mario''-related events.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Burch|first1=Jennifer|title=Nintendo celebrates Mario Day with panache|url=https://nintendowire.com/news/2018/03/09/nintendo-celebrates-mario-day-panache/|accessdate=March 13, 2018|work=Nintendo Wire|date=March 9, 2018}}</ref>\n\n{{Clear}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikipedia books|Mario franchise characters}}\n{{Portal|Video games}}\n* {{commons category-inline|Mario (character)}}\n* {{Wikiquote-inline|Mario (franchise)|Mario}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20170511193109/http://www.imdb.com/character/ch0039169/ Mario] on [[IMDb]]\n* [https://www.mariowiki.com/Mario Mario] on Super Mario Wiki\n* [http://mario.nintendo.com/ Official website for the ''Mario'' series]\n* [https://www.nintendo.com/sites/mario Mario entry on Nintendo.com]\n\n{{Mario franchise}}\n{{Donkey Kong series}}\n{{Forbes Fictional 15}}\n{{Raving Rabbids series}}\n{{Super Smash Bros.}}\n\n[[Category:Action video game characters]]\n[[Category:Animated human characters]]\n[[Category:Characters created by Shigeru Miyamoto]]\n[[Category:Corporate mascots]]\n[[Category:Toy mascots]]\n[[Category:Video game mascots]]