<br>2003 ''[[Infernal Affairs]]''}}{{awards|award=[[Golden Bauhinia Awards]]|name='''Best Actor'''<br>1998 ''[[Happy Together (1997 film)|Happy Together]]''<br>2003 ''[[Infernal Affairs]]''<br>2005 ''[[2046 (film)|2046]]''}}{{awards|award=[[Hong Kong Film Critics Society Awards]]|name='''Best Actor'''<br>2004 ''[[2046 (film)|2046]]''}}{{awards|award=[[Asian Film Awards]]|name='''Best Actor'''<br>2008 ''[[Lust, Caution]]''}}{{awards|award=[[Golden Horse Film Festival and Awards|Golden Horse Awards]]|name='''Best Actor'''<br>1994 ''[[Chungking Express]]''<br>2002 ''[[Infernal Affairs]]''<br>2007 ''[[Lust, Caution]]}}\n| website            = <!-- {{URL|example.com}} -->\n| module             = {{infobox musical artist|embed=yes\n | background = solo_singer\n| label = Capital Artists Music Limited (1985\u20131992)<br/>Music Impact Entertainment Ltd (1994\u20131997)<br/>Universal Music (Hong Kong) Limited (2000\u20132002)<br/>Jet Tone Film Production<ref name=\"baidu\">{{cite web|url=http://baike.baidu.com/view/4996.htm|website=baike.baidu.com|title=\u6881\u671d\u4f1f_\u767e\u5ea6\u767e\u79d1 (Baidu Profile)|accessdate=17 September 2017}}</ref>\n| associated_acts = [[Five Tiger Generals (TVB)|Five Tiger Generals]]\n}}\n| module2            = {{Infobox Chinese|child=yes\n| t = {{linktext|\u6881|\u671d|\u5049}}\n| s = {{linktext|\u6881|\u671d|\u4f1f}}\n| p = Li\u00e1ng Ch\u00e1ow\u011bi\n| y = L\u00e8uhng Ch\u00ecuhw\u00e1ih\n| j = Leong4 Ciu4wai5\n}}\n| module3            = \n| module4            = \n| module5            = \n| module6            = \n| signature          = \n| signature_size     = \n| signature_alt      = \n| footnotes          = \n}}\n\n'''Tony Leung Chiu-wai''' (born 27 June 1962) is a [[Hong Kong people|Hong Kong]] actor and singer. He is considered one of Asia's most successful and internationally recognised actors and was named as \"Small Tiger\"  among [[Five Tiger Generals of TVB]]. He has won many international acting prizes, including the [[Cannes Film Festival]] award for Best Actor for his performance in Wong Kar-wai's film ''[[In the Mood for Love]]''. Leung is widely considered the best native Hong Kong actor of his generation. He was named by [[CNN]] as one of \"Asia's 25 Greatest Actors of All Time\".<ref>{{cite web|title=Asia's 25 greatest actors of all time|url=http://travel.cnn.com/explorations/none/asias-25-greatest-actors-all-time-223697/|publisher=CNN}}</ref>\n\nLeung is known for his collaborations with director [[Wong Kar-wai]], with whom he has worked in seven films including ''[[Chungking Express]]'' (1994), ''[[Happy Together (1997 film)|Happy Together]]'' (1997), ''[[In the Mood for Love]]'' (2000), and ''[[The Grandmaster (film)|The Grandmaster]]'' (2013).  He also appeared in three [[Venice Film Festival]] [[Golden Lion]]-winning films, including ''[[A City of Sadness]]'' (1989), ''[[Cyclo (film)|Cyclo]]'' (1995) and ''[[Lust, Caution]]'' (2007), directed by [[Ang Lee]]. Leung also stars in the [[Academy Award]]-nominated film ''[[Hero (2002 film)|Hero]]'', and the box office hits ''[[Hard Boiled]]'' (1992) and ''[[Infernal Affairs]]'' (2002). Leung was cast as the [[Mandarin (character)|Mandarin]] in the [[Marvel Cinematic Universe]] and will appear in ''[[Shang-Chi and the Legend of the Ten Rings]]'' (2021).\n\nFor ''In the Mood for Love'', Leung earned the [[Cannes Film Festival Award for Best Actor|Best Actor]] award at the [[Cannes Film Festival]]. He is also a seven-time winner at the [[Hong Kong Film Awards]] and three-time winner at the [[Golden Horse Film Awards]], holding the record for most awards in the Best Actor category. The 2002 book ''East Asian Film Stars'' describes Leung as \"undoubtedly one of the most successful and widely-acclaimed Hong Kong actors of his generation, with a broad and diverse filmography.\"<ref>{{cite book|last=Martin|first=Daniel|editor=Leung, Wing-fai |editor2=Willis, Andy|title=East Asian Film Stars|date=2014|chapter=Body of Action, Face of Authenticity: Symbolic Stars in the Transnational Marketing and Reception of East Asian Cinema|publisher=Palgrave Macmillan|location=New York|isbn=1137029188|page=21}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nLeung was born in Hong Kong. Leung's early childhood was punctuated with parents' quarrels and arguments about money. A mischievous boy in his early years, Leung's personality changed when his father, a chronic [[gambler]], left the family when he was eight; he and his younger sister were brought up by their mother.<ref name=\"Born To Act\">{{cite web|url=http://www.chinadaily.com.cn/en/doc/2003-11/20/content_283096.htm |title=HK Mr Charming Tony Leung born to be an actor |date=20 November 2003 |work=[[China Daily]] |accessdate=20 June 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"The Times\">{{cite news| url=http://entertainment.timesonline.co.uk/tol/arts_and_entertainment/film/london_film_festival/article2678331.ece | work=The Times | location=London | title=Why Tony Leung is in the mood for lust | first=Damon | last=Wise | date=18 October 2007 | accessdate=25 May 2010}}</ref>\n\nLeung was a reticent, quiet child.<ref name=\"nopart2\">{{cite news|first=Karen |last=Durbin| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2005/08/07/movies/07durb.html?_r=1&oref=slogin |title=Still in the Mood for a Collaboration |work= [[The New York Times]]|date=7 August 2005}}</ref> He has said that his childhood experiences paved the way for his acting career, which allows him to openly express his feelings:\n\n{{Cquote|<blockquote>\"You don't know what happened, just one day your pop disappears. And from that day on I try not to communicate with anyone. I'm so afraid to talk to my classmates, afraid that if someone says something about family I won't know what to do. So I became very isolated. So that's why I love acting, because I can express all my feelings the way I couldn't for so long.\" \"I'm a quiet person. And then when I went to TV it all came out; I cried and I wasn't ashamed. The audience thinks it's the character's feelings, but really it's my feelings, all coming out in a rush.\"<ref name=\"Born To Act\" /></blockquote>}}\n\nLeung went to private school, but he quit at the age of 15 due to financial difficulties. He was a well-behaved teenager who was very close to his mother. During an interview on the making of ''Hero'', he says that he sees his mother as his definition of a \"hero[ine]\" for having brought up two children alone.{{Citation needed|date=April 2017}}\n\n==Television career==\nAfter quitting his studies, Leung worked in a variety of jobs, first as a grocer's runner at his uncle's shop, then a showroom salesman in a Hong Kong shopping centre. Around the age of 16 he met future actor and comedian [[Stephen Chow]] who influenced his decision to become an actor and remains a good friend.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tonyleung.info/tony/?p=169|title=The Melancholic Charm of Tony Leung Chiu Wai|publisher=[[yesasia.com]]|date=16 January 2007|accessdate=27 August 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 1982, he passed the training courses of television channel [[TVB]]. Due to his boyish looks, TVB cast him as host of a children's programme, ''[[430 Space Shuttle]]''. Leung enjoyed comedies during his television years; it was for these he became well known. So, in the 1980s, he was named as one of \"TVB's [[Five Tiger Generals (TVB)|Five Tigers]]\" (their five up-and-coming male TV stars) along with [[Andy Lau]], [[Felix Wong]], [[Michael Miu]] and [[Kent Tong]]. Leung starred in the highly successful ''Police Cadet'' TV serial in 1984 (later named ''Police Cadet 84'' to distinguish it from subsequent sequels).\n\nHe played an outgoing young man who decides to become a police officer; [[Maggie Cheung]], who also started her career at the same time, played a shy bookworm, Leung's upstairs neighbour and love interest. Since then they have worked together on ''[[The Yang's Saga]]'' (1985), ''[[Days of Being Wild]]'' (1991), ''[[The Eagle Shooting Heroes]]'' (1993), ''[[Ashes of Time]]'' (1994), ''[[In the Mood for Love]]'' (2000), ''Hero'' (2002), and ''[[2046 (film)|2046]]'' (2005).\n\nInterviewed by Wong Kar Wai, Leung said that he considered Maggie to be his alter ego. \"Maggie is a truly formidable partner \u2013 one to waltz with. We do not spend a lot of time with each other, as we like to keep some mystery between us. Whenever I see her, I discover something new about her\".<ref>{{cite web |author1=Wong Kar Wai |title=Tony Leung: the unforgettable cowboy leading man of Asian cinema shows his true grit to a legendary director and fellow frontiersman |url=http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_m1285/is_8_35/ai_n14931780 |website=BNet |accessdate=1 January 2011 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080625080452/http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_m1285/is_8_35/ai_n14931780 |archivedate=2008-06-25 |url-status=dead|format=Interview |date=May 25, 2005}}</ref>\n\n==Film career==\n[[File:Tony Leung Chiu Wai Hands.jpg|right|thumb|Leung's hand print and autograph at the [[Avenue of Stars, Hong Kong|Avenue of Stars]] in Hong Kong.]]\nMany consider Leung's role in director [[John Woo]]'s 1992 [[Hong Kong action cinema|action film]] ''[[Hard Boiled]]'' in which he co-starred with [[Chow Yun-fat]], as his breakthrough role. However, Leung first received international attention in [[Hou Hsiao-hsien]]'s 1989 film ''[[A City of Sadness]]'', which won the [[Venice Film Festival|Venice]] [[Golden Lion]].\n\nLeung often collaborates with director [[Wong Kar-wai]] and has appeared in many of his films. His most notable roles include the lonely policeman in  ''[[Chungking Express]]'' (1994), a gay Chinese expatriate living in Argentina in ''[[Happy Together (1997 film)|Happy Together]]'' (1997), and a self-controlled victim of adultery in ''[[In the Mood for Love]]'' (2000) for which he won the Best Actor award at [[2000 Cannes Film Festival|Cannes]].<ref name=\"festival-cannes.com\">{{cite web |url=http://www.festival-cannes.com/en/archives/ficheFilm/id/5208/year/2000.html |title=Festival de Cannes: In the Mood for Love |accessdate=10 October 2009|work=festival-cannes.com}}</ref> He trained for five years in [[wing chun]] to prepare for his role as [[Ip Man]] in Wong's ''[[The Grandmaster (film)|The Grandmaster]].''<ref>{{cite web |last1=Marsh |first1=James |title=Paris Cinema IFF Interview: Yuen Wo Ping on the Changing Face of Kung Fu Cinema |url=https://screenanarchy.com/2012/07/paris-cinema-iff-interview-yuen-wo-ping |website=Twitch Film/Screen Anarchy |format=Interview |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160331135215/http://twitchfilm.com/2012/07/paris-cinema-iff-interview-yuen-wo-ping.html |archivedate=March 31, 2016 |date=July 22, 2012|url-status=live}}</ref> He is considered by many to be one of the finest actors of his generation in Hong Kong. [[Robert De Niro]] and [[Brad Pitt]] are admirers of his work,<ref>[http://news.xinhuanet.com/english/2005-04/21/content_2857757.htm Tony Leung in the mood for acting.] China View, 21 April 2005. Retrieved 26 December 2006.</ref> and Leung has been called Asia's answer to [[Clark Gable]].<ref name=\"The Times\"/>\n\nLeung also has an on-and-off [[Cantopop]] and [[Mandarin pop]] singing career and sang the theme song of ''[[Infernal Affairs]]'' with [[Andy Lau]].\n\nDuring the late 1990s, it was difficult for him to break into Hollywood because he would not take on any roles that degrade his character and image in Hong Kong. To date, he has not done a [[Cinema of the United States|Hollywood film]], but is primed to appear in one after signing on with an American film agent.<ref>[http://www.chinadaily.com.cn/english/doc/2005-08/10/content_467794.htm Tony Leung to appear in Hollywood film.] ''China Daily''.com, 10 August 2005. Retrieved 23 December 2006.</ref><ref>[https://archive.today/20120710054307/http://en.chinabroadcast.cn/349/2005/08/18/60@10200.htm Tony Leung Heads for Hollywood.] CRI English.com, 18 August 2005. Retrieved 23 December 2006.</ref>\n\nIn addition to Cantonese, English, and Spanish, Leung speaks [[Standard Mandarin|Mandarin]] (accented) and some Japanese (as heard in ''[[Tokyo Raiders]]''). ''[[Lust, Caution (film)|Lust Caution]]'' is the first film where he has a Mandarin-speaking role in which he used his own voice. (His Mandarin dialogue in ''[[Hero (2002 film)|Hero]]'' was dubbed by someone else.)\n\nDuring the promotion of the film ''[[Hero (2002 film)|Hero]]'', some politicians and commentators in Hong Kong attacked Leung for expressing the view that the [[Tiananmen Square protests of 1989|Tiananmen Square demonstration]] crackdown was necessary to maintain stability. Under constant political pressure and boycott threats, Leung made a single statement that he may have been quoted out of context but refused to retract his statement in the magazine.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20050907000939/http://www.hkentreview.com/2002/december/decother/tltian.html Tony Leung Chiu-Wai claims he was misquoted.] HK Entertainment Review, 19 December 2002. Retrieved 23 December 2006.</ref> However, the movie magazine editor maintained that the original statement was not out of context and challenged people to read the complete interview.\n\nIn 2014 he was selected as a member of the jury for the [[64th Berlin International Film Festival]].<ref name=\"Berlin\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.berlinale.de/en/presse/pressemitteilungen/alle/Alle-Detail_21332.html |title=Berlinale 2014: International Jury |accessdate=31 December 2013 |work=Berlinale}}</ref>\n\nIn July 20, 2019, it was announced that Leung was cast to play [[Mandarin (comics)|The Mandarin]] in the [[Marvel Studios]] film ''[[Shang-Chi and the Legend of the Ten Rings]]'',<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://screenrant.com/shang-chi-mandarin-cast-tony-leung/|title=Shang-Chi Casts Tony Leung As The MCU's Real Mandarin|last=Hood|first=Cooper|date=20 July 2019|website=ScreenRant}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/marvels-shang-chi-sets-simu-liu-star-at-comic-con-1225856|title=Marvel Finds Its Shang-Chi in Chinese-Canadian Actor Simu Liu|website=The Hollywood Reporter|author=Borys Kit , Mia Galuppo|date=July 20, 2019}}</ref> marking his Hollywood debut.<ref>Tseng, Douglas (July 21, 2019). [https://www.todayonline.com/8days/seeanddo/tony-leung-chiu-wai-make-hollywood-debut-new-marvel-movie \"Tony Leung Chiu-Wai To Make Hollywood Debut In New Marvel Movie\"]. Today. Retrieved August 28, 2019.</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\n===Relationship and marriage with Carina Lau===\nTony Leung and [[Carina Lau]] are one of Hong Kong's biggest celebrity couples. They dated for 19 years before marrying in Bhutan in 2008. They had known each other since ''The Replica'' in 1984, and worked on-screen together in ''Replica'' (1984), ''Duke of Mount Deer'' (1984), ''Police Cadet'' (1984, 1985, 1988),  ''The Yangs' Saga'' (1985), ''Days of Being Wild'' (1991), ''He ain't heavy, he's my father'' (1993), ''Ashes of Time'' (1994), and ''2046'' (2005).\n\nIn 1990, during the filming of ''Days of Being Wild'', Lau was abducted for several hours. Wong Kar-wai said, \"Originally, there were plans for ''Days of Being Wild'' I and II, and the sequence featuring Leung was meant to be the opening scene of the second movie. But two things happened, one of which was that ''Days of Being Wild'' didn't do well in Hong Kong, so the producers said, \"No Part 2.\" The other reason was Carina Lau's kidnapping.<ref name=\"nopart2\"/>\n\nOn 21 July 2008, the couple got married in [[Bhutan]] in royal fashion. The wedding created a media frenzy in Hong Kong, with companies spending hundreds of thousands of dollars to pursue the wedding party.<ref>International Herald Tribune. \"[http://www.iht.com/articles/2008/07/20/technology/hkmedia.php IHT].\" '' Actors' wedding leads to Hong Kong media frenzy.'' Retrieved on 22 July 2008.</ref>\n\nAccording to ''[[Ming Pao Daily News]]'', [[Faye Wong]] and her husband actor [[Li Yapeng]] had taken them to India in 2007 to visit the [[Ogyen Trinley Dorje|17th Karmapa]]. The Karmapa's counsel helped them to resolve a crisis in their relationship, and he also suggested Bhutan as a wedding venue.<ref name=\"asiaone\">{{cite web|url=http://www.asiaone.com/Just%2BWoman/News/Celebrities/Story/A1Story20080716-77086.html|website=asiaone.com|title=Why Tony, Carina nuptials in Bhutan|accessdate=17 September 2017|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120925041921/http://www.asiaone.com/Just%2BWoman/News/Celebrities/Story/A1Story20080716-77086.html|archivedate=25 September 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Religion===\nTony Leung is a [[Buddhism|Buddhist]]. He has donated to constructions of Buddhist institutions, performing a marriage in a Buddhist ceremony, attending Buddhist gatherings and doing the Buddhist palm greetings.<ref name=\"chinapress\">{{cite web|url=http://www.chinapress.com.my/20160217/%E6%A2%81%E6%9C%9D%E5%81%89%E8%88%87%E7%8E%8B%E8%8F%B2-%E6%98%A5%E7%AF%80%E9%A3%9B%E5%8D%B0%E5%BA%A6%E6%8B%9C%E6%B3%95%E7%8E%8B/|title=\u6881\u671d\u5049\u8207\u738b\u83f2 \u6625\u7bc0\u98db\u5370\u5ea6\u62dc\u6cd5\u738b &#124; \u4e2d\u570b\u5831 China Press|website=chinapress.com.my|accessdate=17 September 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n\n===Film===\n\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|- align=\"center\"\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! Notes\n|-\n| 1983\n| ''[[Mad, Mad 83]]''\n|\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"| 1985\n| ''[[Young Cops]]''\n| Leung Siu-bo\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Fascinating Affairs]]''\n|\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\"| 1986\n| ''[[The Lunatics]]''\n| Doggie\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Love Unto Waste]]''\n| Tony Cheung\n| Nominated\u2014[[Hong Kong Film Awards|Hong Kong Film Award for Best Actor]]\n|-\n| ''[[You Will I Will]]''\n|\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"| 1987\n| ''[[People's Hero (film)|People's Hero]]''\n| Sai\n| [[Hong Kong Film Awards|Hong Kong Film Award for Best Supporting Actor]]\n|-\n| ''[[Happy Go Lucky (1987 film)|Happy Go Lucky]]''\n|\n|\n|-\n| 1988\n| ''[[I Love Maria]]''\n| Chong Chi-keung\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=\