. uva uva f. diablensis'' <small>Baker 1924: Type locality- Top of Ronde Klip [1288.98\u2032 N, 68852.02\u2032 W]</small>\n\n''Cerion uva knipensis'' <small>Baker 1924: Type locality- Valley area between Seroes Palomba and Baha</small>\n\n''C. uva knipensis f. djerimensis''<sup>\u2020</sup><small>: Type locality- Edge of coastal cliffs near Plaja Djermimi [12821.24\u2032 N, 6989.83\u2032 W]</small>\n\n''Cerion uva arubanum'' <small>Baker 1924: Type locality- Baranca Alto [12828.50\u2032 N, 69857.77\u2032 W]</small>\n\n''Cerion uva bonairensis'' <small>Baker 1924: Type locality- Porta Span\u02dco [12814.06\u2032 N, 68816.68\u2032 W]</small>\n\n''C. uva bonairensis f. kralendijki''<sup>\u2020</sup> <small>Baker 1924: Type locality- South of Kralendijk [1288.08\u2032 N, 68816.68\u2032 W], beside a highway on the western shore of Bonaire.</small>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q28432257}}\n\n[[Category:Cerionidae]]\n[[Category:Gastropods described in 1758]]\n\n\n{{Cerionidae-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Avava25", "label": "safe", "comment": "Grammar and word replacement", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cerion_uva"}
{"title_page": "Portrait of a Musician", "text_new": "{{short description|Italian Renaissance portrait of an unknown musician by Leonardo Da Vinci}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox Painting\n<!-- Before making changes to this infobox please consider the discussion on the talk page, Talk:Portrait_of_a_Musician. It is intentionally concise. -->\n| image_file=Leonardo da Vinci - Portrait of a Musician.jpg\n| title=Portrait of a Musician\n| artist=[[Leonardo da Vinci]]\n| year=c. 1485\u20131490\n| medium=[[oil painting|Oil]] on [[Juglans#Wood|walnut]] wood\n| height_metric=44.7\n| width_metric=32\n| city=[[Milan]] \n| museum=[[Pinacoteca Ambrosiana]]}}\n\n'''''Portrait of a Musician'''''{{#tag:ref|Occasionally referred to as '''''Portrait of Young Man'''''<ref name=\"Z\u00f6llner47-48\">Z\u00f6llner 2015, pp. 47\u201348</ref> or simply '''''The Musician'''''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.apollo-magazine.com/louvre-leonardo-review/ |author=Nicholl, Charles |title=Leonardo at the Louvre is full of wonders \u2013 and a few surprises |work=Apollo |accessdate=15 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Brown\"/>|group=n}} ({{lang-it|'''Ritratto di musico'''}}) is an unfinished painting, from 1485\u20131490,{{#tag:ref|Scholars date the painting to the mid to late 1480s, some suggest specifically 1485,<ref name=\"Ambrosiana\">{{cite web|url=https://www.ambrosiana.it/en/opere/portrait-of-a-musician |title=Portrait of a Musician Leonardo da Vinci (1452\u20131519) |publisher=Veneranda Biblioteca Ambrosiana |accessdate=8 March 2020}}</ref> some 1486\u20131487,<ref>Syson 2011</ref> and some up to 1488\u20131490.<ref name=\"Silvestri\">Silvestri 2009, pp. 26</ref><ref name=\"Z\u00f6llner47-48\"/>|group=n}} in [[oil painting|oils]] on a [[Juglans#Wood|walnut]] wood panel by the [[Italian Renaissance]] [[polymath]] [[Leonardo da Vinci]].<ref name=\"Z\u00f6llner47-48\"/> This is Leonardo's only known portrait of a male and up until the 20th century was thought to depict [[Ludovico Sforza]], the [[List of rulers of Milan|Duke of Milan]] and employer of Leonardo at the time. However, restoration work in 1904\u20131905 caused the removal of overpainting that revealed a hand holding [[sheet music]]. This indicated that the sitter may be a musician, a theory that is widely accepted today.\n\nThe painting has attracted much intrigue and mystery as no contemporary accounts or even records of a [[commission (art)|commission]] of any kind exist. Strong stylistic similarities to other works by Leonardo have secured him at least a partial attribution. The hesitation for a universal consensus in attribution is due to the stiff, rigid and lifeless qualities of the figure's body. While the unfinished nature of the painting may explain this, scholars have explainsd this to be because most of the body was likely done by a [[Leonardeschi| student of Leonardo's]].\n\nThe portrait represents the distinct dark background portrait style of Leonardo's time in Milan. [[Lady with an Ermine]] and [[La Belle Ferronni\u00e8re]] are other examples of this, but the ''Portrait of a Musician'' is the only one to still reside in Milan, where it has sat in the [[Pinacoteca Ambrosiana]] since at least 1672.\n\nThe uncertainty over who the subject is has caused many Italian musicians and politicians to be proposed as the young man. [[Franchinus Gaffurius]] was the most convincing suggestion throughout the 20th century, but scholarly opinion has shifted to [[Atalante Migliorotti]], who has been the leading candidate throughout the 21st century. Other notable suggestions include [[Josquin des Prez]] and [[Gaspar Van Weerbeke]] but there is no decisive evidence to confirm any claims.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wga.hu/html_m/l/leonardo/03/1musicia.html |author1=Kr\u00e9n, Emil |author2=Marx, Daniel |title=Portrait of a Musician by Leonardo da Vinci |publisher=Web Gallery of Art |accessdate=13 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Fagnart76\">Fagnart 2019, pp. 76</ref>\n\n==Description==\n===Composition===\nThis painting was made with [[oil painting|oils]] on a [[Juglans#Wood|walnut]] wood panel, a medium which Leonardo had begun to favor at the time of the painting's creation.<ref name=\"Isaacson237\"/> The portrait depicts a young man in a bust length, three-quarter position while his right hand holds a folded [[sheet music|musical score]] of some kind.<ref name=\"Bambach\"/> It is reminiscent of his other portraits from his time in [[Milan]], such as the [[Lady with an Ermine]] and [[La Belle Ferronni\u00e8re]], from their shared black background, while also differing in the angled, rather than profile view.<ref name=\"Palmer\"/> \n\n===The Musician===\n[[File:Ritratto di musico 02.jpg|thumb|350px|Detail of the musical score.]]\nThe man has curly shoulder length hair, sporting a red hat on his mostly finished face that intently stares at something outside the spectator's field of vision.<ref name=\"Brown\"/><ref name=\"Isaacson237\">Isaacson 2017, pp. 237</ref> He wears a tight white undershirt with an unfinished black [[doublet (clothing)|doublet]] and only an [[underpaint|underpainted]] brownish-orange [[Academic stole|stole]].<ref name=\"Kemp\">Kemp 2019, pp. 92</ref><ref name=\"Fagnart73\">Fagnart 2019, pp. 73</ref><ref name=\"Palmer\"/> The mouth hints at the start of a smile or suggests that perhaps the man is about to sing or has just sung.<ref name=\"Pedretti\">Pedretti 1989, pp. 68</ref> A notable feature of the musician's face is the effect on his eyes from the light outside the frame. The light causes both eyes to be dilated but the left eye to a far greater extent than the right, something that is not humanly possible. Some defned Leonardo claiming that this is simply for dramatic effect, so the viewer feels a sense of motion from the musician's left to right side of his face.<ref name=\"Isaacson239\">Isaacson 2017, pp. 239</ref>\n\n===The Musical Score===\nThe stiffly folded piece of paper is held in an odd and delicate manner and is at least one part of a [[sheet music|musical score]], with [[musical notes]] and letters written on it.<ref name=\"Kemp\"/> Due to the poor [[art conservation|conservation]] of the lower part of the painting, the notes and letters are largely illegible.<ref name=\"Brown\"/><ref name=\"Kemp\"/> This has not stopped various scholars from hypothesizing as to what the letters say, often using their interpretations to support their theory of the musician's identity.<ref name=\"Fagnart75\u201376\"/> The notes on the other hand have offered little clarity into the painting, other than strongly suggesting the subject to be a musician.<ref name=\"Ambrosiana\"/> The notes are also undoubtedly in measural notation and therefore likely representative of [[polyphonic music]].<ref name=\"Fagnart73\"/> But since comparisons of Leonardo's notation of music from drawings{{#tag:ref|Drawings that are kept in the [[Royal Library, Windsor|Royal Library of Windsor]], to be exact.|group=n}} does not resemble that of the painting, he is probably not the author, leaving the author and the significance of the music, unknown.<ref name=\"Bambach\"/>\n\n==History==\n===Attribution and Date===\nWhile once controversial, modern scholars generally agree that the ''Portrait of a Musician'' is by Leonardo da Vinci.<ref name=\"Oxford Art\">{{cite web|url-access=subscription |url=https://www.oxfordartonline.com/groveart/view/10.1093/gao/9781884446054.001.0001/oao-9781884446054-e-7000050401 |author=Kemp, Martin |title=Leonardo da Vinci |publisher=Oxford University Press |accessdate=26 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Pedretti\"/><ref name=\"Brown\">Brown 1983, pp. 105</ref> This controversy stemmed from the rigid and stoicness of the painting,<ref name=\"Kemp\"/> something which scholars address by proposing that the clothing and torso were done by a [[Leonardeschi| student of his]], perhaps [[Giovanni Antonio Boltraffio]] or [[Giovanni Ambrogio de Predis]].<ref name=\"Clark\">Clark 1989</ref><ref name=\"Palmer\"/><ref name=\"Universal\"/> But it is universally agreed that if Leonardo did not create the whole painting, then he at least painted the face.<ref name=\"Isaacson237\"/>\n\n[[File:Portrait of a Lady - Ambrogio de Predis.png|thumb|left|200px|''Portrait of a Lady'' by [[Giovanni Ambrogio de Predis]]. Originally thought to also be by Leonardo and paired with ''Portrait of a Musician'']]\t\nWhile no recording of a [[commission (art)|commission]] exists,<ref name=\"Isaacson237\"/> this attribution comes from various stylistic similarities to Leonardo's other works, notably the angel and St. Jerome's face from [[Virgin of the Rocks]] and [[Saint Jerome in the Wilderness]] respectively, as well as the portrait having hair reminiscent of that in [[Ginevra de' Benci]].<ref name=\"Clark\"/><ref name=\"Pedretti\" /> The dark background of the portrait, a style popularized by Leonardo, furthers this attribution as it appears in other portraits from his time in Milan, such as [[Lady with an Ermine]] and [[La Belle Ferronni\u00e8re]].<ref name=\"Oxford Art\"/> The shared quality of these portraits suggests that the ''Portrait of a Musician'' was likely done in Milan as well, meaning after 1482, the year he arrived there. Leonardo's lack of anatomical detail suggests that the Portrait of a Musician is from before 1490, the year where he would engage in a study of the [[anatomy|human body structure]], especially the [[skull]]. In fact, the later Lady with an Ermine, from 1489-1490, is representative of this refined and articulate dedication to accuracy in painting the human form, further suggesting the painting to be from before 1490. It can be further narrowed down due to the similarity in treatment of [[chiaroscuro]] from works in the mid 1840s, such [[Virgin of the Rocks]] and sketches for a [[Leonardo's horse|bronze horse sculpture]] making the painting safe to date to 1895-1890.<ref name=\"Clark\"/><ref name=\"Fagnart74\">Fagnart 2019, pp. 74</ref>\n\n===Ambrosiana===\nThis is Leonardo's only portrait to stay in Milan and was catalogued into the [[Pinacoteca Ambrosiana]] in 1672. Its whereabouts before then are unknown but the portrait beared the description of being \"the face of the [[List of rulers of Milan|Duke of Milan]], with such elegance, that perhaps the living Duke would have wanted it for himself,\" which implied the subject to be [[Ludovico Sforza]], the duke at the time.<ref name=\"Fagnart74\"/> The theory was that it was a counterpart to the ''Portrait of a Lady'', now attributed to [[Giovanni Ambrogio de Predis]] but was thought to be a portrait by Leonardo, of [[Beatrix d'Este|Beatrice d'Este]], Ludovico's wife.<ref name=\"Silvestri\"/> These assumptions were taken to be true without question until [[Luigi Cavenaghi]]'s 1904\u20131905 [[Conservation and restoration of paintings|restoration]] removed a layer of black paint and revealed a hand holding some kind of [[sheet music|musical score]],<ref name=\"Fagnart74\"/> which led to the identification of the subject as a musician.<ref name=\"Z\u00f6llner45\">Z\u00f6llner 2015, pp. 45</ref> Since this discovery, numerous candidates have been proposed as the sitter.<ref name=\"Pooler32\">Pooler 2014, pp. 32</ref>\n\n==Possible Subjects==\n{{multiple image|total_width=300\n|image1=Portrait of a Youth in Profile - Francesco Napoletano.jpg\n|image2=Bust of a Youth in Profile - Leonardo da Vinci.jpg\n|footer=Two drawings, thought to depict the same person as the ''Portrait of a Musician''. Left by [[Francesco Napoletano|Napoletano]] and right by [[Leonardo da Vinci|Leonardo]]}}\nAfter [[Luigi Cavenaghi]]'s 1904\u20131905 [[Conservation and restoration of paintings|restoration]] removed a layer of black paint and revealed a hand holding some kind of [[sheet music|musical score]],<ref name=\"Silvestri\"/> the man was widely declared to be a musician of some sort.<ref name=\"Ambrosiana\"/><ref name=\"Z\u00f6llner45\"/><ref name=\"Fagnart75\">Fagnart 2019, pp. 75</ref> While the subject's identity is uncertain, the subject himself may appear in other works. Scholars at the [[National Gallery]] have suggested that [[Francesco Napoletano|Francesco Napoletano's]] drawing of ''Portrait of a Youth in Profile'' and Leonardo's drawing of a ''Bust of a Youth in Profile'' depict the same figure as the ''Portrait of a Musician''.<ref name=\"National Gallery\">{{cite book |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Leonardo Da Vinci Painter at the Court of Milan |url=https://www.nationalgallery.org.uk/media/15705/exhibition-guide_leonardo-da-vinci.pdf |location=London |publisher=The National Gallery |page=4 |date=n.d.}}</ref> However the identity of the sitter himself remains unknown and not only have various candidates been proposed but even the idea that the subject is simply anonymous has also been explored.<ref name=\"Pooler32\"/>\n\n===Franchinus Gaffurius===\n\nThroughout the 20th century, the leading candidate, suggested by [[Luca Beltrami]] in 1906, was [[Franchinus Gaffurius]], priest, music theorist, court musician for [[Ludovico Sforza]] and after January 1848, ''[[maestro di cappella]]'' of [[Milan Cathedral]].<ref name=\"Isaacson238\">Isaacson 2017, pp. 238</ref> Gaffurius and Leonardo were known to have been friends, both entering the Duke's service only a year or two apart from each other. In fact, Gaffurius' celebrated 1496 music treatise, ''Practica Musica'', contains various [[woodcuts]] by Leonardo.<ref name=\"Pooler31\">Pooler 2014, pp. 31</ref> Additionally, the letters \"Cant\" and \"Ang\" have been deciphered on the sheet music which could by an abbreviation for Cantum Angelicum. This has been suggested to be in reference to ''Angelicum ac divinum opus'', a music treatise published in 1508.<ref name=\"Silvestri\"/> The issues that have since discredited this theory are the treatise being published at least 18 years after the painting's creation and no physical descriptions from Gaffurius' lifetime matching the ''Portrait of a Musician.''<ref name=\"Fagnart75\"/> Also, the issues of Gaffurius, a priest, not being depicted in [[Clerical clothing|clerical robe]] and that Gaffurius would have been in his mid thirties at the time, make him likely too old to be the young man of the painting.<ref name=\"Gaffurius Grove\"/><ref>Pooler 2014, pp. 31\u201332</ref>\n\n<imagemap>\nImage:Portrait of a Musician Candidates.jpg|thumb|left|alt=''Portrait of a Musician'' and four proposed candidates of the subject.|Sforza, Gaffurius, Josquin and Galeazzo.{{#tag:ref|This portrait, by [[Andrea Solari]], has often been suggested to be [[Gal\u00e9as de Saint-S\u00e9verin|Galeazzo di Sanseverino]], another candidate for the sitter in Leonardo's painting.|group=n}} (Left to right, ''Portrait of a Musician'' center) have each been proposed as the subject. <small>''(Clickable image\u2014use cursor to identify.)''</small>\npoly 10 10 218 10 218 192 150 192 149 278 10 278 [[Ludovico Sforza]]\npoly 220 10 424 10 424 278 284 278 284 192 220 192 [[Franchinus Gaffurius]]\nrect 150 192 284 372[[Portrait of a Musician]]\npoly 10 282 149 282 149 380 218 380 218 554 10 554 [[Josquin des Prez]]\npoly 284 282 424 282 424 554 220 554 220 380 284 372 [[Gal\u00e9as de Saint-S\u00e9verin]]\n</imagemap>\n\n===Atalante Migliorotti===\nSince Pietro C. Marani's suggestion in 2000,<ref>Marani 2000, pp. 165</ref> [[Atalante Migliorotti]], a [[Tuscany|Tuscan]] [[lute|lutist]], actor, lyricist and singer, has been the most widely accepted identity of the musician.<ref name=\"Bambach\">Bambach 2012, pp. 83</ref><ref name=\"Isaacson238\"/> In 1482, Migliarotti and Leonardo left [[Florence]] together for [[Milan]] to serve in the court of [[Ludovico Sforza]], the [[List of rulers of Milan|Duke of Milan]].<ref name=\"Silvestri\"/> Furthermore, Leonardo is thought to have taught Migliarotti the [[lute]] and [[lyre]] and known to be friends.<ref>{{cite web|url-access=subscription |url=https://www.oxfordmusiconline.com/grovemusic/view/10.1093/gmo/9781561592630.001.0001/omo-9781561592630-e-0000010313 |author1=Harr\u00e1n, Don |author2=Chater, James |title=Frottola |publisher=Oxford University Press |accessdate=22 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Pooler32\"/><ref name=\"Palmer\">Palmer 2018, pp. 122</ref>{{#tag:ref|This was claimed by [[Anonimo Gaddiano]], one of the earliest biographers of Leonardo Da Vinci.|group=n}} During the painting's conception, Migliarotti would have been in his late teens or early twenties{{#tag:ref|His age being 19\u201324 depending on the accepted year as 1485\u20131490.|group=n}} making him a fitting candidate to be the young man in the painting.<ref name=\"Fagnart75\"/> Additionally, in a 1482 inventory from the [[Codex Atlanticus]]{{#tag:ref|Folio 888 recto (ex 324 recto) to be exact.<ref name=\"Fagnart75\"/>|group=n}} Leonardo listed \"a portrait of Atalante with his face raised.\"<ref name=\"Isaacson238\"/>{{#tag:ref|Alternatively translated as: \"a portrait of Atalante with his upturned face.\"<ref name=\"Fagnart75\u201376\">Fagnart 2019, pp. 75\u201376</ref> or \"a head portrayed from Atalante who raises his face.\"<ref name=\"Kemp\"/>|group=n}} This has been considered by many to have been some kind of study or start of the later ''Portrait of a Musician''.<ref name=\"Fagnart76\"/><ref name=\"Isaacson238\"/><ref name=\"Kemp\"/> The only issues with this theory are that the subject's face is not raised, as Leonardo wrote in his notes, and this note was written 3 years prior to the earliest estimated date of completion{{#tag:ref|The earliest being 1485 with the latest at 1490.|group=n}} for the ''Portrait of a Musician''.<ref name=\"Isaacson238\"/> However, these are by no means outstanding issues, as Leonardo was known to often make numerous revisions and take many years to complete a painting{{#tag:ref|Often, like ''The Portrait of a Musician'', not even finishing his paintings.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/07/11/arts/design/davinci-saint-jerome-metropolitan-museum.html |author=Cotter, Holland |title=What Leonardo da Vinci Couldn't Finish  |accessdate=22 March 2020}}</ref>|group=n}} therefore, since the widespread rejection of Franchinus Gaffurius as the leading candidate, Migliarotti is now considered the most likely.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nationalgeographic.com/magazine/2019/05/leonardo-da-vinci-artistic-brilliance-endures-500-years-after-death/ |author=Kalb, Claudia |title=Why Leonardo da Vinci's brilliance endures, 500 years after his death |work=National Geographic |accessdate=22 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.lagazzettaitaliana.com/people/8764-leonardo-da-vinci-s-impact-500-years-later |author=Selvaggio, Danielle |title=Leonardo da Vinci's Impact 500 Years Later |publisher=La Gazzetta Italiana |accessdate=22 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Gaffurius Grove\">{{cite web|url-access=subscription |url=https://www.oxfordmusiconline.com/grovemusic/view/10.1093/gmo/9781561592630.001.0001/omo-9781561592630-e-0000010477?rskey=JtGv9F&result=1 |author=Blackburn, Bonnie J. |title=Gaffurius [Gafurius], Franchinus |publisher=Oxford University Press |accessdate=22 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Bambach\"/><ref name=\"Isaacson238\"/>\n\n===Josquin des Prez===\nIn 1972, [[Josquin des Prez]], French singer and composer, was suggested as the subject by [[Belgian]] musicologist, Suzanne Clercx-Lejeune.<ref name=\"Fagnart75\"/> Josquin worked in the service of the [[House of Sforza|Sforza family]] during various periods of the 1480s,{{#tag:ref|Either 1483 or 1484 as well as 1489.<ref name=\"Josquin\">{{cite web|url-access=subscription |url=https://www.oxfordmusiconline.com/grovemusic/view/10.1093/gmo/9781561592630.001.0001/omo-9781561592630-e-0000014497 |author1=Macey, Patrick |author2=Noble, Jeremy |author3=Dean, Jeffrey |author4=Reese, Gustave |title=Josquin (Lebloitte dit) des Prez |publisher=Oxford University Press |accessdate=23 March 2020}}</ref>|group=n}} consequently working at the same time as Leonardo.<ref name=\"Ambrosiana\"/> Suzanne Clercx-Lejeune proposed that the words on the [[sheet music|musical score]] where the abbreviations of \"Cont,\" \"Cantuz,\" and \"A Z\" appear in reference to the words \"[[Contratenor]],\" \"Cantuz\" and [[Alto|Altuz]]. She claimed that this meant they were associated with a song with a descending melodic line, such as [[Mass (music)|masses]], [[motets]] and songs by Josquin.<ref name=\"Fagnart75\"/>{{#tag:ref|With Josquin's motet ''Illibata Dei Virgo nutrix'' suggested as a piece that exemplifies this.|group=n}} This theory has since been strongly discredited due to the notation in the painting being largely illegible and the fact that many composers of the time were writing the same forms in the same manner that was suggested to indicate specifically Josquin.<ref name=\"Fagnart75\"/> Additionally, this theory runs into the same issues\nas that of Gaffurius', in that Josquin was also a priest in his mid 30s at the time, making it unlikely to be him, a young man depicted without [[Clerical clothing|clerical robes]], in the ''Portrait of a Musician''.<ref name=\"Josquin\"/>\n\n===Gaspar Van Weerbeke===\nLaure Fagnart suggested most recently in 2019 that the sitter's identity is, [[Gaspar Van Weerbeke]], a [[Netherlandish]] composer and singer. Gaspar worked for the [[House of Sforza|Sforza family]] at the same time as Leonardo, where they likely knew each other due to their shared employer.<ref name=\"Fagnart76\"/> This theory cites letters from [[Galeazzo Maria Sforza]] to Gotardo Panigarola concerning the attire of musicians for the court, with one stating, \"Gotardo. To Gaspar, our singer, we would like to give a dark velvet robe, such as you have given to the Abbot [Antonio Guinati] and to Cordier, both of them also our sing-ers.\" As Fagnart points out, this letter is too vague to defiantly link Gaspar to the portrait, additionally, Gaspar runs into the same issue as Gaffurius and Josquin, as he would have also been in his 30s and probably too old to be the young man in the painting.<ref name= Fagnart76/>\n\n===Other Candidates===\n[[Gal\u00e9as de Saint-S\u00e9verin]] has been suggested as the sitter, since Leonardo lived with him while in Milan. Not only is there no direct evidence to support this, but the uncovering of the musical score makes this very unlikely as Gal\u00e9as de Saint-S\u00e9verin was not known to be a musician.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.freeart.com/artwork/art-print/leonardo-da-vinci-portrait-of-unknown_fan22837019.html |title=Leonardo da Vinci, portrait of unknown musician, perhaps Franchino Gaffurio or Galeazzo di Sanseverino. Milan, Pinacoteca Ambrosiana. |publisher=UFreeArt, Inc |accessdate=26 March 2020}}</ref> [[Francesco Canova da Milano]], an Italian [[lute]]nist and composer, has also been suggested as the subject since he was an important musician also working in [[Milan]] when Leonardo was there. However, there is no circumstantial evidence to support this claim.<ref name=\"Universal\">{{cite web|url=http://universalleonardo.org/work.php?id=308 |title=Portrait of a Musician c1485 |publisher=University of the Arts, London |accessdate=22 March 2020}}</ref> [[Siegfried Woldhek]], a Dutch illustrator, has claimed that ''Portrait of a Musician'' is one of three self portraits by Leonardo.<ref>{{cite web|author=TED2008 |url=http://www.ted.com/talks/siegfried_woldhek_shows_how_he_found_the_true_face_of_leonardo.html |title=Siegfried Woldhek shows how he found the true face of Leonardo |publisher=Ted.com |date= n.d.|accessdate=17 July 2013}}</ref>\nIt is worth noting that this claim is considered highly improbable.<ref name=\"Pooler32\"/>\n\n==Interpretation==\nWhile the lack of contemporary records of the portrait have prevented the understanding of the origin and purpose of the painting, scholars have proposed various theories. \n\nVarious scholars propose that the tension in the subject's face is due to intense thought on music that was either just performed, about to be performed or being performed.<ref name=\"Pedretti\" /><ref name=\"Fagnart75\"/> The painting has also been proposed as representative of Leonardo's self proclaimed ideology in the superiority of painting over other art forms like [[poetry]], [[sculpture]] and [[music]].<ref name=\"Fagnart77\">Fagnart 2019, pp. 77</ref> Leonardo famously declared in the beginning of his uncompleted ''[[A Treatise on Painting|Libro de pittura]]'', \n\n{{Quote\n|text=How Music Ought to be Called the Sister and Junior to Painting. Music is to be re-garded none other than the sitter of painting since it is subject to hearing, a sense second to the eye, and since it composes harmony from the conjunction of its proportional parts operating at the same time. [These parts] are constrained to arise and to die in one or more harmonic tempos which surround a proportionality by its members; such a har-mony is composed not differently from the circumferential lines which generate human beauty by its [respective] members. Yet painting excels and rules over music, because it does not immediately die after its creation the way unfortunately music does. To the contrary, painting stays in existence, and will show you as being alive what is, in fact, on a single surface. \n|author=Leonardo da Vinci\n|source=''[[A Treatise on Painting]]'' (1490-92)\n}}\n\nThe preceding excerpt disapproves of music for its inability to stay in existence after a performance, unlike painting where once a painting is crafted it is seemingly there forever. This theory would suggest that the sadness in the young man's eyes is due to this proposed idea that music simply disappears after a finished performance.<ref name=\"Fagnart77\"/>\n\nAnother interpretation is that Leonardo was moved to depict the a young man's beauty and curly hair. But more likely, due to the odd and seemingly intimate aesthetic of the painting, is that it was a personal gift for a close friend.<ref name=\"Isaacson238\"/><ref name=\"Kemp\"/> This would fit with a lot of the proposed subjects, especially [[Atalante Migliorotti]], a close friend of Leonardo's and one likely not financially able to commision a portrait himself.<ref name=\"Fagnart75\"/>\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|group=n|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==References==\n=== Citations ===\n{{Reflist}}\n\n=== Sources ===\n\n*{{cite magazine |last=Bambach |first=Carmen C. |authorlink=Carmen C. Bambach |date=2012 |title=\"Seeking the Universal Painter\" (review of exhibition, Leonardo, Painter at the Court of Milan, National Gallery, London) |url=https://www.academia.edu/4057518/Bambach_Seeking_the_Universal_Painter_review_of_exhibition_Leonardo_Painter_at_the_Court_of_Milan_National_Gallery_London_._Apollo_vol._175_no._595_Feb._2012_pp._82-85 |magazine= Apollo |location=London |publisher=Apollo |volume=175 |issue=595 |pages=82-83}}\n\n*{{cite journal |last=Brown |first=David Alan |date=1983 |title=Leonardo and the Idealized Portrait in Milan |url=https://www.jstor.org/stable/43105426?seq=1 |journal=Arte Lombarda |volume=64 |pages= 105}}\n\n*{{cite book |last1=Clark |first1=Kenneth |authorlink1=Kenneth Clark |last2=Kemp |first2=Martin |authorlink2=Martin Kemp (art historian) |title=Leonardo da Vinci: Revised Edition |edition=2nd |publisher=Penguin |year=1989 |ref=Clark |isbn=978-0140169829}}\n\n*{{cite book |last=Fagnart |first=Laure |editor-first1=Andrea |editor-last1=Lindmayr-Brandl |editor2=Paul Kolb |title=Gaspar van Weerbeke. New Perspectives on his Life and Music |location=Belgium |publisher=Brepols |year=2019 |ref=Fagnart |pages=73\u201377 |chapter=Gaspar Depicted? Leonardo\u2019s Portrait of a Musician |doi-access=free |doi=10.1484/M.EM-EB.4.2019026 |url=https://www.brepolsonline.net/doi/10.1484/M.EM-EB.4.2019026 |isbn=978-2503584546}}\n\n*{{cite book |last=Isaacson |first=Walter |authorlink=Walter Isaacson |title=Leonardo da Vinci |edition=1st |publisher=Simon & Schuster |year=2017 |ref=Isaacson |isbn=978-1501139154}}\n\n*{{cite book |last=Kemp |first=Martin |authorlink=Martin Kemp (art historian) |title=Leonardo da Vinci: The 100 Milestones |publisher=Sterling |year=2019 |ref=Kemp |isbn=978-1454930426}}\n\n*{{cite book |last=Marani |first=Pietro C. |title=Leonardo da Vinci: The Complete Paintings |edition=1st |publisher=Harry N. Abrams |year=2000 |ref=Marani |isbn=978-0810935815}}\n\n*{{cite book |last=Palmer |first=Allison Lee |title=Leonardo da Vinci: A Reference Guide to His Life and Works (Significant Figures in World History) |publisher=Rowman & Littlefield Publishers |year=2018 |ref=Palmer |isbn=978-1538119778}}\n\n*{{cite book |last=Pedretti |first=Carlo |authorlink=Carlo Pedretti |title=Leonardo, a study in chronology and style |edition=1st |publisher=Johnson Reprint Corp |year=1982 |ref=Pedretti |isbn=978-0384452817}}\n\n*{{cite book |last=Pooler |first=Richard Shaw |title=Leonardo Da Vinci's Treatise of Painting. The Story of The World's Greatest Treatise on Painting - Its Origins, History, Content, And Influence. |edition=1st |publisher=Vernon Press |year=2014 |ref=Pooler |isbn=978-1622730179}}\n\n*{{cite book |last=Russell |first=Peter |title=Delphi Complete Works of Leonardo da Vinci (Illustrated) |edition=2nd |publisher=Delphi Classics |year=2014 |ref=Russell |url-access=limited |url=https://www.scribd.com/book/276845423/Delphi-Complete-Works-of-Leonardo-da-Vinci-Illustrated |isbn=978-1908909916}}\n\n*{{cite book |last=Silvestri |first=Paolo De |title=Leonardo. Ediz. inglese |publisher=ATS Italia  |year=2009 |ref=Silvestri |isbn=978-8875718732}}\n\n*{{cite book |last1=Syson |first1=Luke |author2=Larry Keith |author3=Arturo Galansino |author4=Antoni Mazzotta |author5=Scott Nethersole |author6=Per Rumberg |title=Leonardo da Vinci: Painter at the Court of Milan |edition=1st |location=London |publisher=National Gallery |year=2011 |ref=Syson |isbn=978-1857094916}}\n\n*{{cite book |last=Z\u00f6llner |first=Frank |authorlink=Frank Z\u00f6llner |title=Leonardo |edition=2nd |publisher=Taschen |year=2015 |ref=Z\u00f6llner |isbn=978-3-8365-0215-3}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.ambrosiana.it/en/opere/portrait-of-a-musician ''Portrait of a Musician'' on the Pinacoteca Ambrosiana's Website]\n* [http://www.universalleonardo.org/work.php?id=308 ''Portrait of a Musician'' on the Universal Leonardo website]\n* [https://www.ambrosiana.it/en/opere/portrait-of-a-lady/ ''Portrait of a Lady'' on the Pinacoteca Ambrosiana's Website]\n\n{{Leonardo da Vinci}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Paintings by Leonardo da Vinci]]\n[[Category:Paintings of the Ambrosiana]]\n[[Category:1490 paintings]]\n[[Category:1480 paintings]]\n[[Category:15th-century portraits]]\n[[Category:Portraits of men]]\n[[Category:Cultural depictions of musicians]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Italian Renaissance portrait of an unknown musician by Leonardo Da Vinci}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox Painting\n<!-- Before making changes to this infobox please consider the discussion on the talk page, Talk:Portrait_of_a_Musician. It is intentionally concise. -->\n| image_file=Leonardo da Vinci - Portrait of a Musician.jpg\n| title=Portrait of a Musician\n| artist=[[Leonardo da Vinci]]\n| year=c. 1485\u20131490\n| medium=[[oil painting|Oil]] on [[Juglans#Wood|walnut]] wood\n| height_metric=44.7\n| width_metric=32\n| city=[[Milan]] \n| museum=[[Pinacoteca Ambrosiana]]}}\n\n'''''Portrait of a Musician'''''{{#tag:ref|Occasionally referred to as '''''Portrait of Young Man'''''<ref name=\"Z\u00f6llner47-48\">Z\u00f6llner 2015, pp. 47\u201348</ref> or simply '''''The Musician'''''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.apollo-magazine.com/louvre-leonardo-review/ |author=Nicholl, Charles |title=Leonardo at the Louvre is full of wonders \u2013 and a few surprises |work=Apollo |accessdate=15 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Brown\"/>|group=n}} ({{lang-it|'''Ritratto di musico'''}}) is an unfinished painting, from 1485\u20131490,{{#tag:ref|Scholars date the painting to the mid to late 1480s, some suggest specifically 1485,<ref name=\"Ambrosiana\">{{cite web|url=https://www.ambrosiana.it/en/opere/portrait-of-a-musician |title=Portrait of a Musician Leonardo da Vinci (1452\u20131519) |publisher=Veneranda Biblioteca Ambrosiana |accessdate=8 March 2020}}</ref> some 1486\u20131487,<ref>Syson 2011</ref> and some up to 1488\u20131490.<ref name=\"Silvestri\">Silvestri 2009, pp. 26</ref><ref name=\"Z\u00f6llner47-48\"/>|group=n}} in [[oil painting|oils]] on a [[Juglans#Wood|walnut]] wood panel by the [[Italian Renaissance]] [[polymath]] [[Leonardo da Vinci]].<ref name=\"Z\u00f6llner47-48\"/> This is Leonardo's only known portrait of a male and up until the 20th century was thought to depict [[Ludovico Sforza]], the [[List of rulers of Milan|Duke of Milan]] and employer of Leonardo at the time. However, restoration work in 1904\u20131905 caused the removal of overpainting that revealed a hand holding [[sheet music]]. This indicated that the sitter may be a musician, a theory that is widely accepted today.\n\nThe painting has attracted much intrigue and mystery as no contemporary accounts or even records of a [[commission (art)|commission]] of any kind exist. Strong stylistic similarities to other works by Leonardo have secured him at least a partial attribution. The hesitation for a universal consensus in attribution is due to the stiff, rigid and lifeless qualities of the figure's body. While the unfinished nature of the painting may explain this, scholars have explainsd this to be because most of the body was likely done by a [[Leonardeschi| student of Leonardo's]].\n\nThe portrait represents the distinct dark background portrait style of Leonardo's time in Milan. [[Lady with an Ermine]] and [[La Belle Ferronni\u00e8re]] are other examples of this, but the ''Portrait of a Musician'' is the only one to still reside in Milan, where it has sat in the [[Pinacoteca Ambrosiana]] since at least 1672.\n\nThe uncertainty over who the subject is has caused many Italian musicians and politicians to be proposed as the young man. [[Franchinus Gaffurius]] was the most convincing suggestion throughout the 20th century, but scholarly opinion has shifted to [[Atalante Migliorotti]], who has been the leading candidate throughout the 21st century. Other notable suggestions include [[Josquin des Prez]] and [[Gaspar Van Weerbeke]] but there is no decisive evidence to confirm any claims.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wga.hu/html_m/l/leonardo/03/1musicia.html |author1=Kr\u00e9n, Emil |author2=Marx, Daniel |title=Portrait of a Musician by Leonardo da Vinci |publisher=Web Gallery of Art |accessdate=13 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Fagnart76\">Fagnart 2019, pp. 76</ref>\n\n==Description==\n===Composition===\nThis painting was made with [[oil painting|oils]] on a [[Juglans#Wood|walnut]] wood panel, a medium which Leonardo had begun to favor at the time of the painting's creation.<ref name=\"Isaacson237\"/> The portrait depicts a young man in a bust length, three-quarter position while his right hand holds a folded [[sheet music|musical score]] of some kind.<ref name=\"Bambach\"/> It is reminiscent of his other portraits from his time in [[Milan]], such as the [[Lady with an Ermine]] and [[La Belle Ferronni\u00e8re]], from their shared black background, while also differing in the angled, rather than profile view.<ref name=\"Palmer\"/> \n\n===The Musician===\n[[File:Ritratto di musico 02.jpg|thumb|350px|Detail of the musical score.]]\nThe man has curly shoulder length hair, sporting a red hat on his mostly finished face that intently stares at something outside the spectator's field of vision.<ref name=\"Brown\"/><ref name=\"Isaacson237\">Isaacson 2017, pp. 237</ref> He wears a tight white undershirt with an unfinished black [[doublet (clothing)|doublet]] and only an [[underpaint|underpainted]] brownish-orange [[Academic stole|stole]].<ref name=\"Kemp\">Kemp 2019, pp. 92</ref><ref name=\"Fagnart73\">Fagnart 2019, pp. 73</ref><ref name=\"Palmer\"/> The mouth hints at the start of a smile or suggests that perhaps the man is about to sing or has just sung.<ref name=\"Pedretti\">Pedretti 1989, pp. 68</ref> A notable feature of the musician's face is the effect on his eyes from the light outside the frame. The light causes both eyes to be dilated but the left eye to a a far greater extent than the right, something that is not humanly possible. Some defned Leonardo claiming that this is simply for dramatic effect, so the viewer feels a sense of motion from the musician's left to right side of his face.<ref name=\"Isaacson239\">Isaacson 2017, pp. 239</ref>\n\n===The Musical Score===\nThe stiffly folded piece of paper is held in an odd and delicate manner and is at least one part of a [[sheet music|musical score]], with [[musical notes]] and letters written on it.<ref name=\"Kemp\"/> Due to the poor [[art conservation|conservation]] of the lower part of the painting, the notes and letters are largely illegible.<ref name=\"Brown\"/><ref name=\"Kemp\"/> This has not stopped various scholars from hypothesizing as to what the letters say, often using their interpretations to support their theory of the musician's identity.<ref name=\"Fagnart75\u201376\"/> The notes on the other hand have offered little clarity into the painting, other than strongly suggesting the subject to be a musician.<ref name=\"Ambrosiana\"/> The notes are also undoubtedly in measural notation and therefore likely representative of [[polyphonic music]].<ref name=\"Fagnart73\"/> But since comparisons of Leonardo's notation of music from drawings{{#tag:ref|Drawings that are kept in the [[Royal Library, Windsor|Royal Library of Windsor]], to be exact.|group=n}} does not resemble that of the painting, he is probably not the author, leaving the author and the significance of the music, unknown.<ref name=\"Bambach\"/>\n\n==History==\n===Attribution and Date===\nWhile once controversial, modern scholars generally agree that the ''Portrait of a Musician'' is by Leonardo da Vinci.<ref name=\"Oxford Art\">{{cite web|url-access=subscription |url=https://www.oxfordartonline.com/groveart/view/10.1093/gao/9781884446054.001.0001/oao-9781884446054-e-7000050401 |author=Kemp, Martin |title=Leonardo da Vinci |publisher=Oxford University Press |accessdate=26 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Pedretti\"/><ref name=\"Brown\">Brown 1983, pp. 105</ref> This controversy stemmed from the rigid and stoicness of the painting,<ref name=\"Kemp\"/> something which scholars address by proposing that the clothing and torso were done by a [[Leonardeschi| student of his]], perhaps [[Giovanni Antonio Boltraffio]] or [[Giovanni Ambrogio de Predis]].<ref name=\"Clark\">Clark 1989</ref><ref name=\"Palmer\"/><ref name=\"Universal\"/> But it is universally agreed that if Leonardo did not create the whole painting, then he at least painted the face.<ref name=\"Isaacson237\"/>\n\n[[File:Portrait of a Lady - Ambrogio de Predis.png|thumb|left|200px|''Portrait of a Lady'' by [[Giovanni Ambrogio de Predis]]. Originally thought to also be by Leonardo and paired with ''Portrait of a Musician'']]\t\nWhile no recording of a [[commission (art)|commission]] exists,<ref name=\"Isaacson237\"/> this attribution comes from various stylistic similarities to Leonardo's other works, notably the angel and St. Jerome's face from [[Virgin of the Rocks]] and [[Saint Jerome in the Wilderness]] respectively, as well as the portrait having hair reminiscent of that in [[Ginevra de' Benci]].<ref name=\"Clark\"/><ref name=\"Pedretti\" /> The dark background of the portrait, a style popularized by Leonardo, furthers this attribution as it appears in other portraits from his time in Milan, such as [[Lady with an Ermine]] and [[La Belle Ferronni\u00e8re]].<ref name=\"Oxford Art\"/> The shared quality of these portraits suggests that the ''Portrait of a Musician'' was likely done in Milan as well, meaning after 1482, the year he arrived there. Leonardo's lack of anatomical detail suggests that the Portrait of a Musician is from before 1490, the year where he would engage in a study of the [[anatomy|human body structure]], especially the [[skull]]. In fact, the later Lady with an Ermine, from 1489-1490, is representative of this refined and articulate dedication to accuracy in painting the human form, further suggesting the painting to be from before 1490. It can be further narrowed down due to the similarity in treatment of [[chiaroscuro]] from works in the mid 1840s, such [[Virgin of the Rocks]] and sketches for a [[Leonardo's horse|bronze horse sculpture]] making the painting safe to date to 1895-1890.<ref name=\"Clark\"/><ref name=\"Fagnart74\">Fagnart 2019, pp. 74</ref>\n\n===Ambrosiana===\nThis is Leonardo's only portrait to stay in Milan and was catalogued into the [[Pinacoteca Ambrosiana]] in 1672. Its whereabouts before then are unknown but the portrait beared the description of being \"the face of the [[List of rulers of Milan|Duke of Milan]], with such elegance, that perhaps the living Duke would have wanted it for himself,\" which implied the subject to be [[Ludovico Sforza]], the duke at the time.<ref name=\"Fagnart74\"/> The theory was that it was a counterpart to the ''Portrait of a Lady'', now attributed to [[Giovanni Ambrogio de Predis]] but was thought to be a portrait by Leonardo, of [[Beatrix d'Este|Beatrice d'Este]], Ludovico's wife.<ref name=\"Silvestri\"/> These assumptions were taken to be true without question until [[Luigi Cavenaghi]]'s 1904\u20131905 [[Conservation and restoration of paintings|restoration]] removed a layer of black paint and revealed a hand holding some kind of [[sheet music|musical score]],<ref name=\"Fagnart74\"/> which led to the identification of the subject as a musician.<ref name=\"Z\u00f6llner45\">Z\u00f6llner 2015, pp. 45</ref> Since this discovery, numerous candidates have been proposed as the sitter.<ref name=\"Pooler32\">Pooler 2014, pp. 32</ref>\n\n==Possible Subjects==\n{{multiple image|total_width=300\n|image1=Portrait of a Youth in Profile - Francesco Napoletano.jpg\n|image2=Bust of a Youth in Profile - Leonardo da Vinci.jpg\n|footer=Two drawings, thought to depict the same person as the ''Portrait of a Musician''. Left by [[Francesco Napoletano|Napoletano]] and right by [[Leonardo da Vinci|Leonardo]]}}\nAfter [[Luigi Cavenaghi]]'s 1904\u20131905 [[Conservation and restoration of paintings|restoration]] removed a layer of black paint and revealed a hand holding some kind of [[sheet music|musical score]],<ref name=\"Silvestri\"/> the man was widely declared to be a musician of some sort.<ref name=\"Ambrosiana\"/><ref name=\"Z\u00f6llner45\"/><ref name=\"Fagnart75\">Fagnart 2019, pp. 75</ref> While the subject's identity is uncertain, the subject himself may appear in other works. Scholars at the [[National Gallery]] have suggested that [[Francesco Napoletano|Francesco Napoletano's]] drawing of ''Portrait of a Youth in Profile'' and Leonardo's drawing of a ''Bust of a Youth in Profile'' depict the same figure as the ''Portrait of a Musician''.<ref name=\"National Gallery\">{{cite book |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Leonardo Da Vinci Painter at the Court of Milan |url=https://www.nationalgallery.org.uk/media/15705/exhibition-guide_leonardo-da-vinci.pdf |location=London |publisher=The National Gallery |page=4 |date=n.d.}}</ref> However the identity of the sitter himself remains unknown and not only have various candidates been proposed but even the idea that the subject is simply anonymous has also been explored.<ref name=\"Pooler32\"/>\n\n===Franchinus Gaffurius===\n\nThroughout the 20th century, the leading candidate, suggested by [[Luca Beltrami]] in 1906, was [[Franchinus Gaffurius]], priest, music theorist, court musician for [[Ludovico Sforza]] and after January 1848, ''[[maestro di cappella]]'' of [[Milan Cathedral]].<ref name=\"Isaacson238\">Isaacson 2017, pp. 238</ref> Gaffurius and Leonardo were known to have been friends, both entering the Duke's service only a year or two apart from each other. In fact, Gaffurius' celebrated 1496 music treatise, ''Practica Musica'', contains various [[woodcuts]] by Leonardo.<ref name=\"Pooler31\">Pooler 2014, pp. 31</ref> Additionally, the letters \"Cant\" and \"Ang\" have been deciphered on the sheet music which could by an abbreviation for Cantum Angelicum. This has been suggested to be in reference to ''Angelicum ac divinum opus'', a music treatise published in 1508.<ref name=\"Silvestri\"/> The issues that have since discredited this theory are the treatise being published at least 18 years after the painting's creation and no physical descriptions from Gaffurius' lifetime matching the ''Portrait of a Musician.''<ref name=\"Fagnart75\"/> Also, the issues of Gaffurius, a priest, not being depicted in [[Clerical clothing|clerical robe]] and that Gaffurius would have been in his mid thirties at the time, make him likely too old to be the young man of the painting.<ref name=\"Gaffurius Grove\"/><ref>Pooler 2014, pp. 31\u201332</ref>\n\n<imagemap>\nImage:Portrait of a Musician Candidates.jpg|thumb|left|alt=''Portrait of a Musician'' and four proposed candidates of the subject.|Sforza, Gaffurius, Josquin and Galeazzo.{{#tag:ref|This portrait, by [[Andrea Solari]], has often been suggested to be [[Gal\u00e9as de Saint-S\u00e9verin|Galeazzo di Sanseverino]], another candidate for the sitter in Leonardo's painting.|group=n}} (Left to right, ''Portrait of a Musician'' center) have each been proposed as the subject. <small>''(Clickable image\u2014use cursor to identify.)''</small>\npoly 10 10 218 10 218 192 150 192 149 278 10 278 [[Ludovico Sforza]]\npoly 220 10 424 10 424 278 284 278 284 192 220 192 [[Franchinus Gaffurius]]\nrect 150 192 284 372[[Portrait of a Musician]]\npoly 10 282 149 282 149 380 218 380 218 554 10 554 [[Josquin des Prez]]\npoly 284 282 424 282 424 554 220 554 220 380 284 372 [[Gal\u00e9as de Saint-S\u00e9verin]]\n</imagemap>\n\n===Atalante Migliorotti===\nSince Pietro C. Marani's suggestion in 2000,<ref>Marani 2000, pp. 165</ref> [[Atalante Migliorotti]], a [[Tuscany|Tuscan]] [[lute|lutist]], actor, lyricist and singer, has been the most widely accepted identity of the musician.<ref name=\"Bambach\">Bambach 2012, pp. 83</ref><ref name=\"Isaacson238\"/> In 1482, Migliarotti and Leonardo left [[Florence]] together for [[Milan]] to serve in the court of [[Ludovico Sforza]], the [[List of rulers of Milan|Duke of Milan]].<ref name=\"Silvestri\"/> Furthermore, Leonardo is thought to have taught Migliarotti the [[lute]] and [[lyre]] and known to be friends.<ref>{{cite web|url-access=subscription |url=https://www.oxfordmusiconline.com/grovemusic/view/10.1093/gmo/9781561592630.001.0001/omo-9781561592630-e-0000010313 |author1=Harr\u00e1n, Don |author2=Chater, James |title=Frottola |publisher=Oxford University Press |accessdate=22 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Pooler32\"/><ref name=\"Palmer\">Palmer 2018, pp. 122</ref>{{#tag:ref|This was claimed by [[Anonimo Gaddiano]], one of the earliest biographers of Leonardo Da Vinci.|group=n}} During the painting's conception, Migliarotti would have been in his late teens or early twenties{{#tag:ref|His age being 19\u201324 depending on the accepted year as 1485\u20131490.|group=n}} making him a fitting candidate to be the young man in the painting.<ref name=\"Fagnart75\"/> Additionally, in a 1482 inventory from the [[Codex Atlanticus]]{{#tag:ref|Folio 888 recto (ex 324 recto) to be exact.<ref name=\"Fagnart75\"/>|group=n}} Leonardo listed \"a portrait of Atalante with his face raised.\"<ref name=\"Isaacson238\"/>{{#tag:ref|Alternatively translated as: \"a portrait of Atalante with his upturned face.\"<ref name=\"Fagnart75\u201376\">Fagnart 2019, pp. 75\u201376</ref> or \"a head portrayed from Atalante who raises his face.\"<ref name=\"Kemp\"/>|group=n}} This has been considered by many to have been some kind of study or start of the later ''Portrait of a Musician''.<ref name=\"Fagnart76\"/><ref name=\"Isaacson238\"/><ref name=\"Kemp\"/> The only issues with this theory are that the subject's face is not raised, as Leonardo wrote in his notes, and this note was written 3 years prior to the earliest estimated date of completion{{#tag:ref|The earliest being 1485 with the latest at 1490.|group=n}} for the ''Portrait of a Musician''.<ref name=\"Isaacson238\"/> However, these are by no means outstanding issues, as Leonardo was known to often make numerous revisions and take many years to complete a painting{{#tag:ref|Often, like ''The Portrait of a Musician'', not even finishing his paintings.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/07/11/arts/design/davinci-saint-jerome-metropolitan-museum.html |author=Cotter, Holland |title=What Leonardo da Vinci Couldn't Finish  |accessdate=22 March 2020}}</ref>|group=n}} therefore, since the widespread rejection of Franchinus Gaffurius as the leading candidate, Migliarotti is now considered the most likely.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nationalgeographic.com/magazine/2019/05/leonardo-da-vinci-artistic-brilliance-endures-500-years-after-death/ |author=Kalb, Claudia |title=Why Leonardo da Vinci's brilliance endures, 500 years after his death |work=National Geographic |accessdate=22 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.lagazzettaitaliana.com/people/8764-leonardo-da-vinci-s-impact-500-years-later |author=Selvaggio, Danielle |title=Leonardo da Vinci's Impact 500 Years Later |publisher=La Gazzetta Italiana |accessdate=22 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Gaffurius Grove\">{{cite web|url-access=subscription |url=https://www.oxfordmusiconline.com/grovemusic/view/10.1093/gmo/9781561592630.001.0001/omo-9781561592630-e-0000010477?rskey=JtGv9F&result=1 |author=Blackburn, Bonnie J. |title=Gaffurius [Gafurius], Franchinus |publisher=Oxford University Press |accessdate=22 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Bambach\"/><ref name=\"Isaacson238\"/>\n\n===Josquin des Prez===\nIn 1972, [[Josquin des Prez]], French singer and composer, was suggested as the subject by [[Belgian]] musicologist, Suzanne Clercx-Lejeune.<ref name=\"Fagnart75\"/> Josquin worked in the service of the [[House of Sforza|Sforza family]] during various periods of the 1480s,{{#tag:ref|Either 1483 or 1484 as well as 1489.<ref name=\"Josquin\">{{cite web|url-access=subscription |url=https://www.oxfordmusiconline.com/grovemusic/view/10.1093/gmo/9781561592630.001.0001/omo-9781561592630-e-0000014497 |author1=Macey, Patrick |author2=Noble, Jeremy |author3=Dean, Jeffrey |author4=Reese, Gustave |title=Josquin (Lebloitte dit) des Prez |publisher=Oxford University Press |accessdate=23 March 2020}}</ref>|group=n}} consequently working at the same time as Leonardo.<ref name=\"Ambrosiana\"/> Suzanne Clercx-Lejeune proposed that the words on the [[sheet music|musical score]] where the abbreviations of \"Cont,\" \"Cantuz,\" and \"A Z\" appear in reference to the words \"[[Contratenor]],\" \"Cantuz\" and [[Alto|Altuz]]. She claimed that this meant they were associated with a song with a descending melodic line, such as [[Mass (music)|masses]], [[motets]] and songs by Josquin.<ref name=\"Fagnart75\"/>{{#tag:ref|With Josquin's motet ''Illibata Dei Virgo nutrix'' suggested as a piece that exemplifies this.|group=n}} This theory has since been strongly discredited due to the notation in the painting being largely illegible and the fact that many composers of the time were writing the same forms in the same manner that was suggested to indicate specifically Josquin.<ref name=\"Fagnart75\"/> Additionally, this theory runs into the same issues\nas that of Gaffurius', in that Josquin was also a priest in his mid 30s at the time, making it unlikely to be him, a young man depicted without [[Clerical clothing|clerical robes]], in the ''Portrait of a Musician''.<ref name=\"Josquin\"/>\n\n===Gaspar Van Weerbeke===\nLaure Fagnart suggested most recently in 2019 that the sitter's identity is, [[Gaspar Van Weerbeke]], a [[Netherlandish]] composer and singer. Gaspar worked for the [[House of Sforza|Sforza family]] at the same time as Leonardo, where they likely knew each other due to their shared employer.<ref name=\"Fagnart76\"/> This theory cites letters from [[Galeazzo Maria Sforza]] to Gotardo Panigarola concerning the attire of musicians for the court, with one stating, \"Gotardo. To Gaspar, our singer, we would like to give a dark velvet robe, such as you have given to the Abbot [Antonio Guinati] and to Cordier, both of them also our sing-ers.\" As Fagnart points out, this letter is too vague to defiantly link Gaspar to the portrait, additionally, Gaspar runs into the same issue as Gaffurius and Josquin, as he would have also been in his 30s and probably too old to be the young man in the painting.<ref name= Fagnart76/>\n\n===Other Candidates===\n[[Gal\u00e9as de Saint-S\u00e9verin]] has been suggested as the sitter, since Leonardo lived with him while in Milan. Not only is there no direct evidence to support this, but the uncovering of the musical score makes this very unlikely as Gal\u00e9as de Saint-S\u00e9verin was not known to be a musician.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.freeart.com/artwork/art-print/leonardo-da-vinci-portrait-of-unknown_fan22837019.html |title=Leonardo da Vinci, portrait of unknown musician, perhaps Franchino Gaffurio or Galeazzo di Sanseverino. Milan, Pinacoteca Ambrosiana. |publisher=UFreeArt, Inc |accessdate=26 March 2020}}</ref> [[Francesco Canova da Milano]], an Italian [[lute]]nist and composer, has also been suggested as the subject since he was an important musician also working in [[Milan]] when Leonardo was there. However, there is no circumstantial evidence to support this claim.<ref name=\"Universal\">{{cite web|url=http://universalleonardo.org/work.php?id=308 |title=Portrait of a Musician c1485 |publisher=University of the Arts, London |accessdate=22 March 2020}}</ref> [[Siegfried Woldhek]], a Dutch illustrator, has claimed that ''Portrait of a Musician'' is one of three self portraits by Leonardo.<ref>{{cite web|author=TED2008 |url=http://www.ted.com/talks/siegfried_woldhek_shows_how_he_found_the_true_face_of_leonardo.html |title=Siegfried Woldhek shows how he found the true face of Leonardo |publisher=Ted.com |date= n.d.|accessdate=17 July 2013}}</ref>\nIt is worth noting that this claim is considered highly improbable.<ref name=\"Pooler32\"/>\n\n==Interpretation==\nWhile the lack of contemporary records of the portrait have prevented the understanding of the origin and purpose of the painting, scholars have proposed various theories. \n\nVarious scholars propose that the tension in the subject's face is due to intense thought on music that was either just performed, about to be performed or being performed.<ref name=\"Pedretti\" /><ref name=\"Fagnart75\"/> The painting has also been proposed as representative of Leonardo's self proclaimed ideology in the superiority of painting over other art forms like [[poetry]], [[sculpture]] and [[music]].<ref name=\"Fagnart77\">Fagnart 2019, pp. 77</ref> Leonardo famously declared in the beginning of his uncompleted ''[[A Treatise on Painting|Libro de pittura]]'', \n\n{{Quote\n|text=How Music Ought to be Called the Sister and Junior to Painting. Music is to be re-garded none other than the sitter of painting since it is subject to hearing, a sense second to the eye, and since it composes harmony from the conjunction of its proportional parts operating at the same time. [These parts] are constrained to arise and to die in one or more harmonic tempos which surround a proportionality by its members; such a har-mony is composed not differently from the circumferential lines which generate human beauty by its [respective] members. Yet painting excels and rules over music, because it does not immediately die after its creation the way unfortunately music does. To the contrary, painting stays in existence, and will show you as being alive what is, in fact, on a single surface. \n|author=Leonardo da Vinci\n|source=''[[A Treatise on Painting]]'' (1490-92)\n}}\n\nThe preceding excerpt disapproves of music for its inability to stay in existence after a performance, unlike painting where once a painting is crafted it is seemingly there forever. This theory would suggest that the sadness in the young man's eyes is due to this proposed idea that music simply disappears after a finished performance.<ref name=\"Fagnart77\"/>\n\nAnother interpretation is that Leonardo was moved to depict the a young man's beauty and curly hair. But more likely, due to the odd and seemingly intimate aesthetic of the painting, is that it was a personal gift for a close friend.<ref name=\"Isaacson238\"/><ref name=\"Kemp\"/> This would fit with a lot of the proposed subjects, especially [[Atalante Migliorotti]], a close friend of Leonardo's and one likely not financially able to commision a portrait himself.<ref name=\"Fagnart75\"/>\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|group=n|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==References==\n=== Citations ===\n{{Reflist}}\n\n=== Sources ===\n\n*{{cite magazine |last=Bambach |first=Carmen C. |authorlink=Carmen C. Bambach |date=2012 |title=\"Seeking the Universal Painter\" (review of exhibition, Leonardo, Painter at the Court of Milan, National Gallery, London) |url=https://www.academia.edu/4057518/Bambach_Seeking_the_Universal_Painter_review_of_exhibition_Leonardo_Painter_at_the_Court_of_Milan_National_Gallery_London_._Apollo_vol._175_no._595_Feb._2012_pp._82-85 |magazine= Apollo |location=London |publisher=Apollo |volume=175 |issue=595 |pages=82-83}}\n\n*{{cite journal |last=Brown |first=David Alan |date=1983 |title=Leonardo and the Idealized Portrait in Milan |url=https://www.jstor.org/stable/43105426?seq=1 |journal=Arte Lombarda |volume=64 |pages= 105}}\n\n*{{cite book |last1=Clark |first1=Kenneth |authorlink1=Kenneth Clark |last2=Kemp |first2=Martin |authorlink2=Martin Kemp (art historian) |title=Leonardo da Vinci: Revised Edition |edition=2nd |publisher=Penguin |year=1989 |ref=Clark |isbn=978-0140169829}}\n\n*{{cite book |last=Fagnart |first=Laure |editor-first1=Andrea |editor-last1=Lindmayr-Brandl |editor2=Paul Kolb |title=Gaspar van Weerbeke. New Perspectives on his Life and Music |location=Belgium |publisher=Brepols |year=2019 |ref=Fagnart |pages=73\u201377 |chapter=Gaspar Depicted? Leonardo\u2019s Portrait of a Musician |doi-access=free |doi=10.1484/M.EM-EB.4.2019026 |url=https://www.brepolsonline.net/doi/10.1484/M.EM-EB.4.2019026 |isbn=978-2503584546}}\n\n*{{cite book |last=Isaacson |first=Walter |authorlink=Walter Isaacson |title=Leonardo da Vinci |edition=1st |publisher=Simon & Schuster |year=2017 |ref=Isaacson |isbn=978-1501139154}}\n\n*{{cite book |last=Kemp |first=Martin |authorlink=Martin Kemp (art historian) |title=Leonardo da Vinci: The 100 Milestones |publisher=Sterling |year=2019 |ref=Kemp |isbn=978-1454930426}}\n\n*{{cite book |last=Marani |first=Pietro C. |title=Leonardo da Vinci: The Complete Paintings |edition=1st |publisher=Harry N. Abrams |year=2000 |ref=Marani |isbn=978-0810935815}}\n\n*{{cite book |last=Palmer |first=Allison Lee |title=Leonardo da Vinci: A Reference Guide to His Life and Works (Significant Figures in World History) |publisher=Rowman & Littlefield Publishers |year=2018 |ref=Palmer |isbn=978-1538119778}}\n\n*{{cite book |last=Pedretti |first=Carlo |authorlink=Carlo Pedretti |title=Leonardo, a study in chronology and style |edition=1st |publisher=Johnson Reprint Corp |year=1982 |ref=Pedretti |isbn=978-0384452817}}\n\n*{{cite book |last=Pooler |first=Richard Shaw |title=Leonardo Da Vinci's Treatise of Painting. The Story of The World's Greatest Treatise on Painting - Its Origins, History, Content, And Influence. |edition=1st |publisher=Vernon Press |year=2014 |ref=Pooler |isbn=978-1622730179}}\n\n*{{cite book |last=Russell |first=Peter |title=Delphi Complete Works of Leonardo da Vinci (Illustrated) |edition=2nd |publisher=Delphi Classics |year=2014 |ref=Russell |url-access=limited |url=https://www.scribd.com/book/276845423/Delphi-Complete-Works-of-Leonardo-da-Vinci-Illustrated |isbn=978-1908909916}}\n\n*{{cite book |last=Silvestri |first=Paolo De |title=Leonardo. Ediz. inglese |publisher=ATS Italia  |year=2009 |ref=Silvestri |isbn=978-8875718732}}\n\n*{{cite book |last1=Syson |first1=Luke |author2=Larry Keith |author3=Arturo Galansino |author4=Antoni Mazzotta |author5=Scott Nethersole |author6=Per Rumberg |title=Leonardo da Vinci: Painter at the Court of Milan |edition=1st |location=London |publisher=National Gallery |year=2011 |ref=Syson |isbn=978-1857094916}}\n\n*{{cite book |last=Z\u00f6llner |first=Frank |authorlink=Frank Z\u00f6llner |title=Leonardo |edition=2nd |publisher=Taschen |year=2015 |ref=Z\u00f6llner |isbn=978-3-8365-0215-3}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.ambrosiana.it/en/opere/portrait-of-a-musician ''Portrait of a Musician'' on the Pinacoteca Ambrosiana's Website]\n* [http://www.universalleonardo.org/work.php?id=308 ''Portrait of a Musician'' on the Universal Leonardo website]\n* [https://www.ambrosiana.it/en/opere/portrait-of-a-lady/ ''Portrait of a Lady'' on the Pinacoteca Ambrosiana's Website]\n\n{{Leonardo da Vinci}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Paintings by Leonardo da Vinci]]\n[[Category:Paintings of the Ambrosiana]]\n[[Category:1490 paintings]]\n[[Category:1480 paintings]]\n[[Category:15th-century portraits]]\n[[Category:Portraits of men]]\n[[Category:Cultural depictions of musicians]]\n", "name_user": "Arjayay", "label": "safe", "comment": "Duplicate word removed", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Portrait_of_a_Musician"}
{"title_page": "Effie Gray", "text_new": "{{For|the biographical film|Effie Gray (film)}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{Use British English|date=June 2012}}\n{{Infobox writer <!-- for more information see [[:Template:Infobox writer/doc]] -->\n| name          = Effie Gray\n| birth_name    = Euphemia Chalmers Gray\n| image         = Euphemia ('Effie') Chalmers (n\u00e9e Gray), Lady Millais by Thomas Richmond.jpg\n| caption       = Gray portrait {{circa|1865}} (she thought the portrait made her look like \"a graceful doll\")<ref>[http://www.npg.org.uk/collections/search/portrait.php?LinkID=mp07473&rNo=0&role=art Euphemia ('Effie') Chalmers (n\u00e9e Gray), Lady Millais, National Portrait Gallery]</ref>\n| birth_date    = {{Birth date|1828|5|7|df=yes}}\n| birth_place   = [[Perth, Scotland|Perth]], [[Perthshire]], Scotland\n| death_date    = {{death date and age|1897|12|23|1828|5|7|df=yes}}\n| death_place   = Perth, Perthshire, Scotland\n| nationality   = British\n| occupation    = Author, artist\n| education     = \n| alma_mater    = \n| period        = [[Victorian era]]\n| years_active  = \n| spouse        = {{Plainlist|\n* {{marriage|[[John Ruskin]]|1848|1854|end={{abbr|ann.|annulled}}}}\n* {{marriage |[[John Everett Millais]]|1855|1896|end={{abbr|d.|died}}}}}}\n| children      = 8, including [[John Guille Millais]]\n| signature     = \n| signature_alt = \n| module        = \n}}\n\n'''Euphemia Chalmers Millais, Lady Millais''' (''n\u00e9e'' '''Gray'''; 7 May 1828 \u2013 23 December 1897) was an English painter and the wife of [[Pre-Raphaelite Brotherhood|Pre-Raphaelite]] painter [[John Everett Millais]]. She had previously been married to the critic [[John Ruskin]], but the marriage was annulled, and she left him without it having been consummated. This famous Victorian \"[[love triangle]]\" has been dramatised in plays, films and an opera.\n\n==Early life==\nEuphemia Chalmers Gray, initially known by the pet name of \"Phemy\", later as \"Effie,\" was born on 7 May 1828 to Sophia Margaret Gray and George Gray in [[Perth, Scotland|Perth]], [[Perthshire]], [[Scotland]].  Her sisters [[Sophie Gray]] and Alice often modeled for [[John Everett Millais]].\n\n==Relationship with John Ruskin and John Everett Millais==\n[[File:Gray millais 1865.jpg|thumbnail|Albumen print photograph by [[Lewis Carroll]] from 21 July 1865 depicting Effie Gray, [[John Everett Millais]], and their daughters Effie and Mary at 7 Cromwell Place, signed \"Effie C. Millais\".]]\nGray's family knew Ruskin's father, and they encouraged a match between Ruskin and Gray. Ruskin wrote the fantasy novel ''[[The King of the Golden River]]'' for her in 1841, when she was twelve years old. She married Ruskin when she was only 20 years old.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|title=Pre-Raphaelite Girl Gang|last=Walker|first=Kirsty Stonell|publisher=Unicorn|year=2018|isbn=|location=|pages=20}}</ref> After their marriage in 1848,<ref>{{cite book|title=The Order of Release: The Story of John Ruskin, Effie Gray and John Everett Millais Told for the First Time in their Unpublished Letters|year=1948|publisher=J. Murray|location=University of Michigan|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=jU4RAAAAMAAJ&q=ruskin+gray+marriage&dq=ruskin+gray+marriage&hl=en&ei=TBO8TqmVJert0gG124jfCQ&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=1&ved=0CDEQ6AEwAA|editor=James, William Milbourne|page=1}}</ref> they travelled to Venice, where Ruskin was researching his book ''[[The Stones of Venice (book)|The Stones of Venice]]''. In Perth, Scotland, they lived in Bowerswell, the house where Ruskin's grandfather had killed himself by cutting his throat in 1817.<ref name=\"Garnett2012\">{{cite book|author=Henrietta Garnett|title=Wives and Stunners: The Pre-Raphaelites and Their Muses|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xshaKqrZClAC&pg=PP227|date=30 August 2012|publisher=Pan Macmillan|isbn=978-0-230-76754-6|pages=227\u2013etc}}</ref>\n\nTheir different personalities were thrown into sharp relief by their contrasting priorities. For Effie, Venice provided an opportunity to socialise while Ruskin was engaged in solitary studies. In particular, he made a point of drawing the [[Ca' d'Oro]] and the [[Doge's Palace, Venice|Palazzo Ducale]] (Doge's Palace), because he feared they would soon be destroyed by the occupying Austrian troops. One of the troops, Lieutenant Charles Paulizza, made friends with Effie, apparently with no objection from Ruskin. Her brother, among others, later claimed that Ruskin was deliberately encouraging the friendship to compromise her, as an excuse to separate.\n\nWhen she met Millais five years later, she was still a virgin, as Ruskin had persistently put off [[consummate|consummating]] the marriage. Gray and Ruskin had agreed upon abstaining from sex for five years to allow Ruskin to focus on his studies.<ref name=\":0\" /> Another reason may have involved his disgust with some aspect of her body. As she later wrote to her father,\n\n<blockquote>He alleged various reasons, hatred to children, religious motives, a desire to preserve my beauty, and, finally this last year he told me his true reason...  that he had imagined women were quite different to what he saw I was, and that the reason he did not make me his Wife was because he was disgusted with my person the first evening.<ref name=\"Hewison1979\">{{cite book|author=Robert Hewison|title=John Ruskin|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=1XjntfarTykC&pg=PA201|year=1979|publisher=Ardent Media|pages=201\u2013202|id=GGKEY:8PSQ7NGSATA}}</ref></blockquote>\n\nRuskin confirmed this in his statement to his lawyer during the annulment proceedings: \"It may be thought strange that I could abstain from a woman who to most people was so attractive. But though her face was beautiful, her person was not formed to excite passion. On the contrary, there were certain circumstances in her person which completely checked it.\"<ref>Lutyens, M., ''Millais and the Ruskins'', p.191</ref> The reason for Ruskin's disgust with \"circumstances in her person\" is unknown. Various suggestions have been made, including revulsion at either her pubic hair,<ref>Phyllis Rose (1983) ''Parallel Lives''; Franny Moyle (2009) ''Desperate Romantics''</ref> or menstrual blood.<ref>Peter Fuller, ''Theoria: Art and the Absence of Grace'', Chatto & Windus, 1988, pp.11\u201312; [[Suzanne Fagence Cooper]] (2010) ''The Model Wife: The Passionate Lives of Effie Gray, Ruskin and Millais''</ref> Robert Brownell, on the contrary, in his analysis ''Marriage of Inconvenience'', argues that Ruskin's difficulty with the marriage was financial and related to concerns that Effie and her less affluent family were trying to tap into Ruskin's considerable wealth.<ref>{{cite journal |url = https://www.theguardian.com/books/2013/mar/29/ruskin-effie-marriage-inconvenience-brownell|first = Michael|last = Prodger|date = 29 March 2013|accessdate = 24 March 2015|title = John Ruskin's marriage: What really happened|magazine = Guardian}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Millais Waterfall 1935-53.jpg|thumb|''Waterfall'', or ''Effie at Glenfinlas'', 1853, by Millais]]\nWhile married to Ruskin, she modelled for Millais' painting ''[[The Order of Release]]'', in which she was depicted as the loyal wife of a Scottish rebel who has secured his release from prison. She then became close to Millais when he accompanied the couple on a trip to Scotland in order to paint Ruskin's portrait according to the critic's artistic principles. During this time, spent in [[Brig o' Turk]] in the [[Trossachs]], they fell in love. While working on the portrait of her husband, Millais made many drawings and sketches of her. He also sent humorous cartoons of himself, Effie and Ruskin to friends. She copied some of his works.\n\nAfter their return to London, she left Ruskin, nominally to visit her family. She sent back her wedding ring with a note announcing her intention to file for an [[annulment]]. With the support of her family and a number of influential friends, she successfully pursued the case, causing a major public scandal, and their marriage was annulled on the grounds of 'incurable impotency' in 1854.<ref>National Records of Scotland, Annulment recorded in Kinnoull Kirk Session Minutes (NRS ref. CH2/948/7), 1854, pp.223\u2013227.</ref>\n\nIn 1855, she married John Millais and they had eight children together: Everett, born in 1856; George, born in 1857; Effie, born in 1858; Mary, born in 1860; Alice, born in 1862; Geoffroy, born in 1863; John in 1865; and Sophie in 1868. Their youngest son, [[John Guille Millais]], was a notable bird artist and gardener. She also modelled for a number of her husband's works, notably ''[[Peace Concluded]]'' (1856), which idealises her as an icon of beauty and fertility.\n\nWhen Ruskin later sought to become engaged to a teenage girl, [[Rose La Touche]], Rose's parents were concerned. They wrote to Gray to ask about the marriage; she replied by describing Ruskin as an oppressive husband. The engagement was broken off.\n\n==Influence on Millais==\n[[File:EFFIE.jpg|thumb|200px|Gray in middle age, painted by Millais. She is holding a copy of the ''[[Cornhill Magazine]]''.]]\nAfter his marriage, Millais began to paint in a broader style, which Ruskin condemned as a \"catastrophe\".  Marriage had given him a large family to support, and it is speculated that he tried to churn out popular works for financial gain although this is unconfirmed.\n\nEffie was an effective manager of Millais' career and often collaborated with him in choosing his subjects. Her journal indicates her high regard for her husband's art, and his works are still recognisably Pre-Raphaelite in style several years after his marriage.\n\nHowever, Millais eventually abandoned the Pre-Raphaelite obsession with detail and began to paint in a looser style which produced more paintings for the time and effort. Many paintings were inspired by his family life with his wife, often using his children and grandchildren as models. Millais also used his sister-in-law, [[Sophie Gray]], then in her early teens, as the basis of some striking images in the mid to late 1850s, provoking suggestions of a mutual infatuation.<ref name=Cooper>Suzanne Fagence Cooper (2010) ''The Model Wife: The Passionate Lives of Effie Gray, Ruskin and Millais''</ref>\n\n==Later life==\n[[File:Euphemia Millais Gray.jpg|thumb|Euphemia Millais Gray, Perth, Scotland]]\nThe [[annulment]] from Ruskin barred her from events at which [[Queen Victoria]] was present. Both she and her husband were considerably bothered, as she had been socially very active, although many in society were still prepared to receive her and to press her case sympathetically.<ref name=Cooper/> Eventually, when Millais was dying, the queen relented through the intervention of her daughter [[Princess Louise, Duchess of Argyll|Princess Louise]], allowing Gray to attend an official function. Sixteen months after Millais' death, Effie died at Bowerswell on 23 December 1897<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=mFKRlPTPTKkC&pg=PA251|title=The Order of Release \u2013 The Story of John Ruskin, Effie Gray and John Everett Millias|first=W.|last=James|isbn=978-1-4437-0293-5|publisher=Read|year=2008|page=251|accessdate=27 February 2010}}</ref> and was buried in Kinnoull churchyard, Perth, which is depicted in Millais's painting ''The Vale of Rest''.\n[[File:Carteret Millais, Perth, Scotland.jpg|thumb|Carteret Millais, Perth, Scotland]]\n\n== In drama and literature ==\n{{Commons category}}\nHer marriage to Ruskin and subsequent romance with Millais have been dramatised on many occasions:\n\n*''The Love of John Ruskin'' (1912), a silent movie about Ruskin, Gray and Millais.\n*''[[The Love School]]'' (1975), a BBC series about the Pre-Raphaelites, starring [[Anne Kidd]] (Gray), [[David Collings]] (Ruskin), and [[Peter Egan]] (Millais).\n*''John Ruskin's Wife'' (1979), a novel about the relationship by Eva McDonald.\n*''Dear Countess'' (1983), a radio play by [[Elizabeth Morgan (actress)|Elizabeth Morgan]], with [[Derek Jacobi]] (Ruskin), Bridget McCann (Gray), [[Timothy West]] (Old Mr Ruskin) [[Michael Fenner]] (Millais). The author played Ruskin's mother.\n*''[[The Passion of John Ruskin]]'' (1994), a short film directed by [[Alex Chappel]], starring [[Mark McKinney]] (Ruskin), [[Neve Campbell]] (Gray) and [[Colette Stevenson]] (Gray's voice).\n*''Modern Painters'' (1995), an opera about Ruskin, Gray and Millais, music by David Lang, libretto by Manuela Hoelterhoff.\n*''Parrots and Owls'', (1994) a radio play by [[John Purser]] about the [[O'Shea brothers]] in which Gray appears as a friend of James O'Shea and her marital problems are discussed.\n*''[[The Countess (play)|The Countess]]'' (1995), a play written by [[Gregory Murphy]] concentrating on the breakdown of the marriage between Ruskin and Gray.\n* ''The Order of Release'' (1998), a radio play by [[Robin Brooks]] about Ruskin ([[Bob Peck]]), Gray ([[Sharon Small]]) and Millais ([[David Tennant]]).\n*''The Woman Who Gave Birth to Rabbits'' (2002), a collection of short stories by [[Emma Donoghue]], contains a story \"Come, Gentle Night\" about Ruskin and Gray's wedding night.\n* ''Mrs Ruskin'' (2003), a play by [[Kim Morrissey]] about the breakdown of the marriage and Gray's fraught relationship with Ruskin's domineering mother.\n* ''[[Desperate Romantics]]'' (2009), a six-part [[BBC]] television drama serial about the Pre-Raphaelite Brotherhood. She is played by [[Zoe Tapper]].\n* ''[[Effie Gray (film)|Effie Gray]]'' (2014), a film produced by [[Emma Thompson]] with [[Dakota Fanning]] as Effie, [[Tom Sturridge]] as Millais and [[Greg Wise]] as Ruskin.<ref>[http://www.deadline.com/2011/08/dakota-fanning-and-emma-thompson-team-for-1850s-victorian-drama-effie/ Dakota Fanning and Emma Thompson Team for 1850s Victorian Drama \"Effie\"]</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://effiegraymovie.com A movie about Effie Gray]\n*[https://www.npg.org.uk/collections/search/person/mp03082/euphemia-effie-chalmers-ne-gray-lady-millais?search=sas&sText=Euphemia+Millais+Gray Portraits of Effie Gray in the National Portrait Gallery]\n*[http://www.preraphaelites.org Birmingham Museums & Art Gallery's Pre-Raphaelite Online Resource]\n*[http://preraphaelitesisterhood.com/what-is-the-pre-raphaelite-woman/ An overview of the women involved in the Pre-Raphaelite circle]\n\n{{Pre-Raphaelite Brotherhood}}\n{{John Everett Millais}}\n{{John Ruskin}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gray, Effie}}\n[[Category:1828 births]]\n[[Category:1897 deaths]]\n[[Category:British artists' models]]\n[[Category:John Ruskin]]\n[[Category:People from Perth, Scotland]]\n[[Category:Pre-Raphaelite Brotherhood artists' models]]\n[[Category:Scottish female models]]\n[[Category:Women of the Victorian era]]\n[[Category:Wives of baronets]]\n[[Category:Millais family]]\n", "text_old": "{{For|the biographical film|Effie Gray (film)}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{Use British English|date=June 2012}}\n{{Infobox writer <!-- for more information see [[:Template:Infobox writer/doc]] -->\n| name          = Effie Gray\n| birth_name    = Euphemia Chalmers Gray\n| image         = Euphemia ('Effie') Chalmers (n\u00e9e Gray), Lady Millais by Thomas Richmond.jpg\n| caption       = Gray portrait {{circa|1865}} (she thought the portrait made her look like \"a graceful doll\")<ref>[http://www.npg.org.uk/collections/search/portrait.php?LinkID=mp07473&rNo=0&role=art Euphemia ('Effie') Chalmers (n\u00e9e Gray), Lady Millais, National Portrait Gallery]</ref>\n| birth_date    = {{Birth date|1828|5|7|df=yes}}\n| birth_place   = [[Perth, Scotland|Perth]], [[Perthshire]], Scotland\n| death_date    = {{death date and age|1897|12|23|1828|5|7|df=yes}}\n| death_place   = Perth, Perthshire, Scotland\n| nationality   = British\n| occupation    = Author, artist\n| education     = \n| alma_mater    = \n| period        = [[Victorian era]]\n| years_active  = \n| spouse        = {{Plainlist|\n* {{marriage|[[John Ruskin]]|1848|1854|end={{abbr|ann.|annulled}}}}\n* {{marriage |[[John Everett Millais]]|1855|1896|end={{abbr|d.|died}}}}}}\n| children      = 8, including [[John Guille Millais]]\n| signature     = \n| signature_alt = \n| module        = \n}}\n\n'''Euphemia Chalmers Millais, Lady Millais''' (''n\u00e9e'' '''Gray'''; 7 May 1828 \u2013 23 December 1897) was an English painter and the wife of  [[Pre-Raphaelite Brotherhood|Pre-Raphaelite]] painter [[John Everett Millais]]. She had previously been married to the critic [[John Ruskin]], but the marriage was annulled, and she left him without it having been consummated. This famous Victorian \"[[love triangle]]\" has been dramatised in plays, films and an opera.\n\n==Early life==\nEuphemia Chalmers Gray, initially known by the pet name of \"Phemy\", later as \"Effie,\" was born on 7 May 1828 to Sophia Margaret Gray and George Gray in [[Perth, Scotland|Perth]], [[Perthshire]], [[Scotland]].  Her sisters [[Sophie Gray]] and Alice often modeled for [[John Everett Millais]].\n\n==Relationship with John Ruskin and John Everett Millais==\n[[File:Gray millais 1865.jpg|thumbnail|Albumen print photograph by [[Lewis Carroll]] from 21 July 1865 depicting Effie Gray, [[John Everett Millais]], and their daughters Effie and Mary at 7 Cromwell Place, signed \"Effie C. Millais\".]]\nGray's family knew Ruskin's father, and they encouraged a match between Ruskin and Gray. Ruskin wrote the fantasy novel ''[[The King of the Golden River]]'' for her in 1841, when she was twelve years old. She married Ruskin when she was only 20 years old.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|title=Pre-Raphaelite Girl Gang|last=Walker|first=Kirsty Stonell|publisher=Unicorn|year=2018|isbn=|location=|pages=20}}</ref> After their marriage in 1848,<ref>{{cite book|title=The Order of Release: The Story of John Ruskin, Effie Gray and John Everett Millais Told for the First Time in their Unpublished Letters|year=1948|publisher=J. Murray|location=University of Michigan|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=jU4RAAAAMAAJ&q=ruskin+gray+marriage&dq=ruskin+gray+marriage&hl=en&ei=TBO8TqmVJert0gG124jfCQ&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=1&ved=0CDEQ6AEwAA|editor=James, William Milbourne|page=1}}</ref> they travelled to Venice, where Ruskin was researching his book ''[[The Stones of Venice (book)|The Stones of Venice]]''. In Perth, Scotland, they lived in Bowerswell, the house where Ruskin's grandfather had killed himself by cutting his throat in 1817.<ref name=\"Garnett2012\">{{cite book|author=Henrietta Garnett|title=Wives and Stunners: The Pre-Raphaelites and Their Muses|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xshaKqrZClAC&pg=PP227|date=30 August 2012|publisher=Pan Macmillan|isbn=978-0-230-76754-6|pages=227\u2013etc}}</ref>\n\nTheir different personalities were thrown into sharp relief by their contrasting priorities. For Effie, Venice provided an opportunity to socialise while Ruskin was engaged in solitary studies. In particular, he made a point of drawing the [[Ca' d'Oro]] and the [[Doge's Palace, Venice|Palazzo Ducale]] (Doge's Palace), because he feared they would soon be destroyed by the occupying Austrian troops. One of the troops, Lieutenant Charles Paulizza, made friends with Effie, apparently with no objection from Ruskin. Her brother, among others, later claimed that Ruskin was deliberately encouraging the friendship to compromise her, as an excuse to separate.\n\nWhen she met Millais five years later, she was still a virgin, as Ruskin had persistently put off [[consummate|consummating]] the marriage. Gray and Ruskin had agreed upon abstaining from sex for five years to allow Ruskin to focus on his studies.<ref name=\":0\" /> Another reason may have involved his disgust with some aspect of her body. As she later wrote to her father,\n\n<blockquote>He alleged various reasons, hatred to children, religious motives, a desire to preserve my beauty, and, finally this last year he told me his true reason...  that he had imagined women were quite different to what he saw I was, and that the reason he did not make me his Wife was because he was disgusted with my person the first evening.<ref name=\"Hewison1979\">{{cite book|author=Robert Hewison|title=John Ruskin|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=1XjntfarTykC&pg=PA201|year=1979|publisher=Ardent Media|pages=201\u2013202|id=GGKEY:8PSQ7NGSATA}}</ref></blockquote>\n\nRuskin confirmed this in his statement to his lawyer during the annulment proceedings: \"It may be thought strange that I could abstain from a woman who to most people was so attractive. But though her face was beautiful, her person was not formed to excite passion. On the contrary, there were certain circumstances in her person which completely checked it.\"<ref>Lutyens, M., ''Millais and the Ruskins'', p.191</ref> The reason for Ruskin's disgust with \"circumstances in her person\" is unknown. Various suggestions have been made, including revulsion at either her pubic hair,<ref>Phyllis Rose (1983) ''Parallel Lives''; Franny Moyle (2009) ''Desperate Romantics''</ref> or menstrual blood.<ref>Peter Fuller, ''Theoria: Art and the Absence of Grace'', Chatto & Windus, 1988, pp.11\u201312; [[Suzanne Fagence Cooper]] (2010) ''The Model Wife: The Passionate Lives of Effie Gray, Ruskin and Millais''</ref> Robert Brownell, on the contrary, in his analysis ''Marriage of Inconvenience'', argues that Ruskin's difficulty with the marriage was financial and related to concerns that Effie and her less affluent family were trying to tap into Ruskin's considerable wealth.<ref>{{cite journal |url = https://www.theguardian.com/books/2013/mar/29/ruskin-effie-marriage-inconvenience-brownell|first = Michael|last = Prodger|date = 29 March 2013|accessdate = 24 March 2015|title = John Ruskin's marriage: What really happened|magazine = Guardian}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Millais Waterfall 1935-53.jpg|thumb|''Waterfall'', or ''Effie at Glenfinlas'', 1853, by Millais]]\nWhile married to Ruskin, she modelled for Millais' painting ''[[The Order of Release]]'', in which she was depicted as the loyal wife of a Scottish rebel who has secured his release from prison. She then became close to Millais when he accompanied the couple on a trip to Scotland in order to paint Ruskin's portrait according to the critic's artistic principles. During this time, spent in [[Brig o' Turk]] in the [[Trossachs]], they fell in love. While working on the portrait of her husband, Millais made many drawings and sketches of her. He also sent humorous cartoons of himself, Effie and Ruskin to friends. She copied some of his works.\n\nAfter their return to London, she left Ruskin, nominally to visit her family. She sent back her wedding ring with a note announcing her intention to file for an [[annulment]]. With the support of her family and a number of influential friends, she successfully pursued the case, causing a major public scandal, and their marriage was annulled on the grounds of 'incurable impotency' in 1854.<ref>National Records of Scotland, Annulment recorded in Kinnoull Kirk Session Minutes (NRS ref. CH2/948/7), 1854, pp.223\u2013227.</ref>\n\nIn 1855, she married John Millais and they had eight children together: Everett, born in 1856; George, born in 1857; Effie, born in 1858; Mary, born in 1860; Alice, born in 1862; Geoffroy, born in 1863; John in 1865; and Sophie in 1868. Their youngest son, [[John Guille Millais]], was a notable bird artist and gardener. She also modelled for a number of her husband's works, notably ''[[Peace Concluded]]'' (1856), which idealises her as an icon of beauty and fertility.\n\nWhen Ruskin later sought to become engaged to a teenage girl, [[Rose La Touche]], Rose's parents were concerned. They wrote to Gray to ask about the marriage; she replied by describing Ruskin as an oppressive husband. The engagement was broken off.\n\n==Influence on Millais==\n[[File:EFFIE.jpg|thumb|200px|Gray in middle age, painted by Millais. She is holding a copy of the ''[[Cornhill Magazine]]''.]]\nAfter his marriage, Millais began to paint in a broader style, which Ruskin condemned as a \"catastrophe\".  Marriage had given him a large family to support, and it is speculated that he tried to churn out popular works for financial gain although this is unconfirmed.\n\nEffie was an effective manager of Millais' career and often collaborated with him in choosing his subjects. Her journal indicates her high regard for her husband's art, and his works are still recognisably Pre-Raphaelite in style several years after his marriage.\n\nHowever, Millais eventually abandoned the Pre-Raphaelite obsession with detail and began to paint in a looser style which produced more paintings for the time and effort. Many paintings were inspired by his family life with his wife, often using his children and grandchildren as models. Millais also used his sister-in-law, [[Sophie Gray]], then in her early teens, as the basis of some striking images in the mid to late 1850s, provoking suggestions of a mutual infatuation.<ref name=Cooper>Suzanne Fagence Cooper (2010) ''The Model Wife: The Passionate Lives of Effie Gray, Ruskin and Millais''</ref>\n\n==Later life==\n[[File:Euphemia Millais Gray.jpg|thumb|Euphemia Millais Gray, Perth, Scotland]]\nThe [[annulment]] from Ruskin barred her from events at which [[Queen Victoria]] was present. Both she and her husband were considerably bothered, as she had been socially very active, although many in society were still prepared to receive her and to press her case sympathetically.<ref name=Cooper/> Eventually, when Millais was dying, the queen relented through the intervention of her daughter [[Princess Louise, Duchess of Argyll|Princess Louise]], allowing Gray to attend an official function. Sixteen months after Millais' death, Effie died at Bowerswell on 23 December 1897<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=mFKRlPTPTKkC&pg=PA251|title=The Order of Release \u2013 The Story of John Ruskin, Effie Gray and John Everett Millias|first=W.|last=James|isbn=978-1-4437-0293-5|publisher=Read|year=2008|page=251|accessdate=27 February 2010}}</ref> and was buried in Kinnoull churchyard, Perth, which is depicted in Millais's painting ''The Vale of Rest''.\n[[File:Carteret Millais, Perth, Scotland.jpg|thumb|Carteret Millais, Perth, Scotland]]\n\n== In drama and literature ==\n{{Commons category}}\nHer marriage to Ruskin and subsequent romance with Millais have been dramatised on many occasions:\n\n*''The Love of John Ruskin'' (1912), a silent movie about Ruskin, Gray and Millais.\n*''[[The Love School]]'' (1975), a BBC series about the Pre-Raphaelites, starring [[Anne Kidd]] (Gray), [[David Collings]] (Ruskin), and [[Peter Egan]] (Millais).\n*''John Ruskin's Wife'' (1979), a novel about the relationship by Eva McDonald.\n*''Dear Countess'' (1983), a radio play by [[Elizabeth Morgan (actress)|Elizabeth Morgan]], with [[Derek Jacobi]] (Ruskin), Bridget McCann (Gray), [[Timothy West]] (Old Mr Ruskin) [[Michael Fenner]] (Millais). The author played Ruskin's mother.\n*''[[The Passion of John Ruskin]]'' (1994), a short film directed by [[Alex Chappel]], starring [[Mark McKinney]] (Ruskin), [[Neve Campbell]] (Gray) and [[Colette Stevenson]] (Gray's voice).\n*''Modern Painters'' (1995), an opera about Ruskin, Gray and Millais, music by David Lang, libretto by Manuela Hoelterhoff.\n*''Parrots and Owls'', (1994) a radio play by [[John Purser]] about the [[O'Shea brothers]] in which Gray appears as a friend of James O'Shea and her marital problems are discussed.\n*''[[The Countess (play)|The Countess]]'' (1995), a play written by [[Gregory Murphy]] concentrating on the breakdown of the marriage between Ruskin and Gray.\n* ''The Order of Release'' (1998), a radio play by [[Robin Brooks]] about Ruskin ([[Bob Peck]]), Gray ([[Sharon Small]]) and Millais ([[David Tennant]]).\n*''The Woman Who Gave Birth to Rabbits'' (2002), a collection of short stories by [[Emma Donoghue]], contains a story \"Come, Gentle Night\" about Ruskin and Gray's wedding night.\n* ''Mrs Ruskin'' (2003), a play by [[Kim Morrissey]] about the breakdown of the marriage and Gray's fraught relationship with Ruskin's domineering mother.\n* ''[[Desperate Romantics]]'' (2009), a six-part [[BBC]] television drama serial about the Pre-Raphaelite Brotherhood. She is played by [[Zoe Tapper]].\n* ''[[Effie Gray (film)|Effie Gray]]'' (2014), a film produced by [[Emma Thompson]] with [[Dakota Fanning]] as Effie, [[Tom Sturridge]] as Millais and [[Greg Wise]] as Ruskin.<ref>[http://www.deadline.com/2011/08/dakota-fanning-and-emma-thompson-team-for-1850s-victorian-drama-effie/ Dakota Fanning and Emma Thompson Team for 1850s Victorian Drama \"Effie\"]</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://effiegraymovie.com A movie about Effie Gray]\n*[https://www.npg.org.uk/collections/search/person/mp03082/euphemia-effie-chalmers-ne-gray-lady-millais?search=sas&sText=Euphemia+Millais+Gray Portraits of Effie Gray in the National Portrait Gallery]\n*[http://www.preraphaelites.org Birmingham Museums & Art Gallery's Pre-Raphaelite Online Resource]\n*[http://preraphaelitesisterhood.com/what-is-the-pre-raphaelite-woman/ An overview of the women involved in the Pre-Raphaelite circle]\n\n{{Pre-Raphaelite Brotherhood}}\n{{John Everett Millais}}\n{{John Ruskin}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gray, Effie}}\n[[Category:1828 births]]\n[[Category:1897 deaths]]\n[[Category:British artists' models]]\n[[Category:John Ruskin]]\n[[Category:People from Perth, Scotland]]\n[[Category:Pre-Raphaelite Brotherhood artists' models]]\n[[Category:Scottish female models]]\n[[Category:Women of the Victorian era]]\n[[Category:Wives of baronets]]\n[[Category:Millais family]]\n", "name_user": "GalaxyDog", "label": "safe", "comment": "removed unnecessary space", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Effie_Gray"}
{"title_page": "Equestrian statue of Philip Sheridan", "text_new": "{{Good article}}\n{{Infobox Monument\n|monument_name  = ''General Philip Sheridan''\n|image          = [[File:Philip Sheridan Statue.JPG|275px]]\n|location       = [[Sheridan Circle]], [[Washington, D.C.]], United States\n|designer       = [[Gutzon Borglum]] (sculptor)<br />Henry Winslow (architect)\n|material       = [[Bronze sculpture|Bronze]] (sculpture)<br />Granite (base)\n|height         = {{convert|10|ft}}\n|width          = {{convert|5|ft}}\n|length         = {{convert|12|ft}}\n|open           = November 25, 1908\n|dedicated_to   = [[Philip Sheridan]]\n|coordinates    = {{Coord|38.912171|-77.0506|type:landmark_region:US_dim:6|display=inline,title}}\n{{Infobox NRHP \n|embed          = yes\n|nrhp_type      = cp | nocat = yes\n|partof         = [[Civil War Monuments in Washington, D.C.]]\n|partof_refnum  = \n|added          = September 20, 1978<ref name=dcinventory>{{cite web|url=http://planning.dc.gov/sites/default/files/dc/sites/op/publication/attachments/Inventory%202009%200%20Alpha%20Version%2003%2011.pdf |title=District of Columbia Inventory of Historic Sites |publisher=District of Columbia Office of Planning \u2013 Historic Preservation Office |date=September 30, 2009 |accessdate=November 11, 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141105032209/http://planning.dc.gov/sites/default/files/dc/sites/op/publication/attachments/Inventory%202009%200%20Alpha%20Version%2003%2011.pdf |archivedate=November 5, 2014 }}</ref>\n|governing_body = [[National Park Service]]\n|refnum         = 78000257<ref name=nris>{{NRISref|version=2010a}}</ref>\n}}\n}}\n'''''General Philip Sheridan''''' is a [[bronze sculpture]] that honors [[American Civil War|Civil War]] general [[Philip Sheridan]].  The monument was sculpted by [[Gutzon Borglum]], best known for his design of [[Mount Rushmore]]. Dedicated in 1908, dignitaries in attendance at the unveiling ceremony included President [[Theodore Roosevelt]], members of the President's [[Cabinet of the United States|cabinet]], high-ranking military officers and veterans from the Civil War and [[Spanish\u2013American War]]. The [[equestrian statue]] is located in the center of [[Sheridan Circle]] in the [[Sheridan-Kalorama]] neighborhood of [[Washington, D.C.]] The bronze statue, surrounded by a plaza and park, is one of [[Civil War Monuments in Washington, D.C.|eighteen Civil War monuments]] in Washington, D.C., which were collectively listed on the [[National Register of Historic Places]] in 1978.  The sculpture and surrounding park are owned and maintained by the [[National Park Service]], a federal agency of the [[Department of the Interior|Interior Department]].\n\n==History==\n\n===Background===\n[[Philip Sheridan]] was a career [[United States Army]] officer who was instrumental in securing [[Union Army|Union]] successes during the [[Valley Campaigns of 1864]], most notably the [[Battle of Cedar Creek]].  Many of the Union generals would eventually be memorialized in [[Washington, D.C.]], with statues spread throughout the city.  While looking at one of his comrade's equestrian sculptures, Sheridan was not impressed with the depiction of the man and horse.  He reportedly told his wife \"Whatever you do after I'm gone, don't put me on a horse like that.\"  Following her husband's death in 1888, when an equestrian sculpture of her husband was being planned, Irene Sheridan insisted the horse be as \"proud and courageous as its rider.\"<ref name=jacob>{{cite book | author=Jacob, Kathryn Allamong | title=Testament to Union: Civil War Monuments in Washington, Part 3 | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=M6HIB4fNjGoC&lpg=PA71&ots=kteSt_qrPZ&dq=Grand%20Army%20of%20the%20Republic%20Memorial%20%28Stephenson%29&pg=PA134#v=onepage&q=Sheridan&f=false | location=Baltimore | publisher=JHU Press | pages=134\u2013138 | date=1998 | isbn=9780801858611 | accessdate=November 11, 2014 }}</ref>\n\nOn March 2, 1889, Congress authorized the erection of a memorial to Sheridan and appropriated $50,000 for its construction.<ref name=smithsonian/><ref name=greiner>{{cite book | author=Greiner, Henry C. | title=General Phil Sheridan as I knew him, playmate \u2013 comrade \u2013 friend | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=cJwvAAAAYAAJ&dq=Philip%20Sheridan%20Gutzon&pg=PA423#v=onepage&q=Philip%20Sheridan%20Gutzon&f=false | location=Chicago | publisher=J.S. Hyland and Company | pages=423\u2013425 | date=1908 | oclc=2076519 | accessdate=November 11, 2014 }}</ref>   The original sculptor chosen to complete the project was Sheridan's friend [[John Quincy Adams Ward]], who had completed other works in Washington, D.C., including ''[[Major General George Henry Thomas]]'' and the [[James A. Garfield Monument]].  Ward signed a contract with the Sheridan monument commission in 1892 which called for the equestrian statue to be completed by 1898.<ref name=jacob/>  He submitted a sketch of the model in 1892, but that design was not approved.<ref name=smithsonian/>  Not only did Ward not complete the work by 1898, he had only completed a life-size [[Study (art)|study]] of Sheridan's head by 1903.  Ward finally completed a model of Sheridan, but when Irene and her son, Philip Sheridan Jr., visited Ward's studio in [[New York City]] to see the model, they both hated it.  He was depicted as a stout older officer atop a stilted horse.  The commission eventually cancelled the contract with Ward in 1905.  His model of Sheridan was eventually cast in 1916 and stands in front of the [[New York State Capitol]].<ref name=jacob/>\n[[File:General Philip Sheridan Memorial - neigh.JPG|thumb|upright|Closeup of the statue]]\n[[Gutzon Borglum]] had closely followed the events surrounding Ward's procrastination and firing as the two men had an argumentative past.  Borglum was convinced he could do a better job with the design and he also needed the money.  He set out to study as much as possible about Sheridan's life by reading his memoirs and biographies.  Borglum was able to secure an invitation to a Washington, D.C. party that Irene attended.  He sat next to her and invited Irene to his studio in New York.  Borglum set out models of horses throughout the studio before she arrived and surprised Irene by how much he know about her husband.  At the behest of Irene, on July 2, 1907, Borglum received a contract to sculpt the memorial.<ref name=jacob/><ref name=smithsonian/>  He was a [[Danish American]] artist who was greatly influenced by French sculptor [[Auguste Rodin]].<ref name=wapo>{{cite news | last=Richard | first=Paul | date=July 3, 2005 | title=From the Collection: Washington's Prize Possessions | url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2005/07/01/AR2005070100338.html | newspaper=The Washington Post | accessdate=November 11, 2014 }}</ref>  Borglum is best known for his carvings at [[Mount Rushmore]] and [[Stone Mountain]].  The Sheridan sculpture is his only equestrian monument in Washington, D.C.<ref name=washtimes>{{cite news | last=Longaker | first=Mark | date=May 23, 2007 | title=Men on horseback dominate memorials | url=http://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2007/may/23/20070523-102441-7610r/?page=all | newspaper=The Washington Times | accessdate=November 11, 2014 }}</ref>  Borglum's other works in Washington, D.C. include ''[[Rabboni (sculpture)|Rabboni]]'' at [[Rock Creek Cemetery]] and several statues in the [[National Statuary Hall Collection]] in the [[United States Capitol]].<ref name=otherworks>{{cite web | url=http://siris-artinventories.si.edu/ipac20/ipac.jsp?session=G4L57D8992417.3630&profile=ariall&uri=link=3100006~!1133~!3100001~!3100002&aspect=Browse&menu=search&ri=1&source=~!siartinventories&term=Borglum%2C+Gutzon%2C+1867-1941%2C+sculptor.&index=AUTHOR | title=Borglum, Gutzon, 1867\u20131941, sculptor. | publisher=Smithsonian American Art Museum | accessdate=November 11, 2014 }}</ref>\n\nOn January 17, 1908, Borglum's design received approval by the Sheridan monument commission, including then-Secretary of War [[William Howard Taft]], General [[Henry Clark Corbin|Henry C. Corbin]], and Brigadier General Michael V. Sheridan, Philip Sheridan's brother.  Irene also approved the design and chose the memorial site.<ref name=tribune>{{cite news | date=January 26, 1908 | title=Phil Sheridan Statue: Monument of the Cavalry Leader for the Nation's Capital | url=http://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn83030214/1908-01-26/ed-1/seq-22/ | newspaper=New-York Tribune | accessdate=November 11, 2014 }}</ref><ref name=districtnom>{{cite web | url={{NRHP url|id=89001743}} | title=National Register of Historic Places Registration Form | publisher=National Park Service | page=9 | accessdate=November 11, 2014 }}</ref>  She lived at 2211 [[Massachusetts Avenue (Washington, D.C.)|Massachusetts Avenue]] NW (currently offices for the [[Embassy of Greece, Washington, D.C.|Embassy of Greece]]), a short distance from Sheridan Circle and the sculpture.<ref name=irene>{{cite web | url=http://www.mfa.gr/usa/en/the-embassy/history/the-building.html | title=The Building | publisher=Embassy of Greece in Washington, D.C. | accessdate=November 11, 2014 }}</ref>  As Borglum worked on the sculpture, he would talk to Sheridan's friends, sketch Sheridan's artifacts, and visit Irene.  Since Philip Jr. bore a very close resemblance to his father, Borglum used him as a model for the sculpture.  When the artwork was completed, Irene, Philip Jr., and Sheridan's three daughters loved the finished result.<ref name=jacob/>  The sculpture depicts Sheridan riding his horse, Rienzi, as he assembles his troops during the Battle of Cedar Creek on October 19, 1864.  He had raced {{convert|20|mile}} from [[Winchester, Virginia|Winchester]], [[Virginia]], to reach the battle.  Following the Union victory, Sheridan renamed the horse Winchester.  After Winchester died in 1878, Sheridan had him preserved and mounted.  The horse is now on display at the [[National Museum of American History]].<ref name=modany>{{cite web | last=Modany | first=Angela | url=http://americanhistory.si.edu/blog/2012/04/the-war-horse-of-the-civil-war.html | title=The \"War Horse\" of the Civil War | publisher=National Museum of American History | date=April 4, 2012 | accessdate=November 11, 2014 }}</ref>  Congress paid for the plaza, base, and preparation of the memorial site, while veterans of the [[Army of the Cumberland]] paid for the statue.<ref name=statuenom>{{cite web | last=Scott | first=Gary | url={{NRHP url|id=78000257}} | title=National Register of Historic Places Inventory\u2014Nomination Form | publisher=National Park Service | date=September 19, 1977 | page=9 | accessdate=November 11, 2014 }}</ref>  Architect Henry Winslow designed the base and setting.  The stonework was provided by the Mohegan Granite Company of New York while the Malnati Stone Company of Washington, D.C. set the stones in place.<ref name=smithsonian/>\n\n===Dedication===\n[[File:The National Memorial for General Phil. Sheridan is to be unveiled at Washington this week LOC 3707378358.jpg|thumb|upright|Illustrated supplement in the ''New-York Tribune'' announcing the dedication of the General Sheridan monument. November 22, 1908.]]\nThe Sheridan memorial was dedicated on November 25, 1908.  A large crowd was present with many dignitaries in attendance, including President [[Theodore Roosevelt]], military officers, diplomats, and veterans of the Civil War and [[Spanish\u2013American War]].  A processions of troops led by Brigadier General [[J. Franklin Bell]] paraded past the crowd and dignitaries while the [[United States Marine Band]] played music.  Secretary of War [[Luke Edward Wright|Luke E. Wright]] presided over the dedication ceremony and [[Denis J. O'Connell]], rector of [[The Catholic University of America]], delivered the invocation.  Roosevelt, Brigadier General [[Horace Porter]], and Wright gave eulogies of Sheridan.  Roosevelt gave a short speech praising Sheridan's valiant acts while Porter's speech was an in depth review of Sheridan's life, including his days at [[West Point]] and his campaigns during the Civil War and [[American Indian Wars]].  After Irene and Philip Jr. removed the covering of the statue, the crowd cheered loudly and many began to recite [[Thomas Buchanan Read]]'s poem, ''Sheridan's Ride''.<ref name=jacob/>\n\n===Historic designation===\nAlong with [[Civil War Monuments in Washington, D.C.|seventeen other Civil War monuments]], ''General Philip Sheridan'' was added to the [[National Register of Historic Places]] (NRHP) on September 20, 1978, and the District of Columbia Inventory of Historic Sites on March 3, 1979.  The Sheridan monument is also designated a [[contributing property]] to the [[Massachusetts Avenue Historic District (Washington, D.C.)|Massachusetts Avenue Historic District]], listed on the NRHP in 1974, and the [[Sheridan-Kalorama Historic District]], listed on the NRHP in 1989.<ref name=dcinventory/>  The sculpture and the surrounding park are owned and maintained by the [[National Park Service]], a federal agency of the [[United States Department of the Interior|Interior Department]].<ref name=smithsonian/>\n\n==Design and location==\n[[File:Sheridan Statue, Washington, D.C. npcc.jpg|thumb|right|The Sheridan memorial in 1916|alt=|left]]\nThe bronze equestrian sculpture is at the center of Sheridan Circle, a traffic circle located at the intersection of 23rd Street, R Street and Massachusetts Avenue NW within the [[Embassy Row]] section of the [[Sheridan-Kalorama]] neighborhood.<ref name=dcinventory/><ref name=survey>{{cite book | title=Washington West Quadrangle, District of Columbia\u2013Maryland\u2013Virginia | publisher=United States Department of the Interior | author=United States Geological Survey | year=2011 | location=Reston, Virginia | pages=1 : 24,000. 7.5 Minute Series (Topographic) | OCLC=777027791 }}</ref> It measures {{convert|10|ft}} high and {{convert|12|ft}} long while the rectangular granite base measures {{convert|3|ft}} high.  The horse is slightly reared back while standing on a rocky surface.  Sheridan is turned to his right with his right arm extended behind him. The right hand is holding his hat while his left hand holds the horse's reins.  Sheridan is wearing a military uniform with a long coat belted at the waist and is portrayed with a moustache and wavy hair.  The sculpture is surrounded by a plaza measuring {{convert|37|ft}} long with five steps on the front and back leading to the sculpture.  Curved benches run along the interior of the plaza facing the sculpture while the exterior of the plaza features two pairs of lion head fountain spouts.  Water poured from the spouts into square basins, but this feature is no longer working.<ref name=smithsonian>{{cite web | url=http://siris-artinventories.si.edu/ipac20/ipac.jsp?&profile=all&source=~!siartinventories&uri=full=3100001~!16268~!0#focus | title=General Philip Sheridan, (sculpture). | publisher=Smithsonian American Art Museum | accessdate=November 11, 2014 }}</ref>\n\nInscriptions on the monument include the following:<ref name=smithsonian/>\n* <small>GUTZON BORGLUM 1908</small> (left side of the sculpture)\n* <small>GORHAM CO FOUNDERS</small> (right side of the sculpture near the base)\n* <small>SHERIDAN</small> (front side of the base)\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Visual arts|United States}}\n* [[List of equestrian statues in the United States]]\n* [[List of public art in Washington, D.C., Ward 2]]\n* [[Outdoor sculpture in Washington, D.C.]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Commons category inline}}\n\n{{Gutzon Borglum}}\n{{Public art in Washington, D.C.}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Philip Sheridan, General}}\n[[Category:1908 establishments in Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:1908 sculptures]]\n[[Category:Bronze sculptures in Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:Embassy Row|Sheridan]]\n[[Category:Equestrian statues in Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:Historic district contributing properties in Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:Civil War Monuments in Washington, D.C.|Sheridan]]\n[[Category:Sculptures by Gutzon Borglum]]\n[[Category:Outdoor sculptures in Washington, D.C.]]\n", "text_old": "{{Good article}}\n{{Infobox Monument\n|monument_name  = ''General Philip Sheridan''\n|image          = [[File:Philip Sheridan Statue.JPG|275px]]\n|location       = [[Sheridan Circle]], [[Washington, D.C.]], United States\n|designer       = [[Gutzon Borglum]] (sculptor)<br />Henry Winslow (architect)\n|material       = [[Bronze sculpture|Bronze]] (sculpture)<br />Granite (base)\n|height         = {{convert|10|ft}}\n|width          = {{convert|5|ft}}\n|length         = {{convert|12|ft}}\n|open           = November 25, 1908\n|dedicated_to   = [[Philip Sheridan]]\n|coordinates    = {{Coord|38.912171|-77.0506|type:landmark_region:US_dim:6|display=inline,title}}\n{{Infobox NRHP \n|embed          = yes\n|nrhp_type      = cp | nocat = yes\n|partof         = [[Civil War Monuments in Washington, D.C.]]\n|partof_refnum  = \n|added          = September 20, 1978<ref name=dcinventory>{{cite web|url=http://planning.dc.gov/sites/default/files/dc/sites/op/publication/attachments/Inventory%202009%200%20Alpha%20Version%2003%2011.pdf |title=District of Columbia Inventory of Historic Sites |publisher=District of Columbia Office of Planning \u2013 Historic Preservation Office |date=September 30, 2009 |accessdate=November 11, 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141105032209/http://planning.dc.gov/sites/default/files/dc/sites/op/publication/attachments/Inventory%202009%200%20Alpha%20Version%2003%2011.pdf |archivedate=November 5, 2014 }}</ref>\n|governing_body = [[National Park Service]]\n|refnum         = 78000257<ref name=nris>{{NRISref|version=2010a}}</ref>\n}}\n}}\n'''''General Philip Sheridan''''' is a [[bronze sculpture]] that honors [[American Civil War|Civil War]] general [[Philip Sheridan]].  The monument was sculpted by [[Gutzon Borglum]], best known for his design of [[Mount Rushmore]]. Dedicated in 1908, dignitaries in attendance at the unveiling ceremony included President [[Theodore Roosevelt]], members of the President's [[Cabinet of the United States|cabinet]], high-ranking military officers and veterans from the Civil War and [[Spanish\u2013American War]]. The [[equestrian statue]] is located in the center of [[Sheridan Circle]] in the [[Sheridan-Kalorama]] neighborhood of [[Washington, D.C.]] The bronze statue, surrounded by a plaza and park, is one of [[Civil War Monuments in Washington, D.C.|eighteen Civil War monuments]] in Washington, D.C., which were collectively listed on the [[National Register of Historic Places]] in 1978.  The sculpture and surrounding park are owned and maintained by the [[National Park Service]], a federal agency of the [[Department of the Interior|Interior Department]].\n\n==History==\n\n===Background===\n[[Philip Sheridan]] was a career [[United States Army]] officer who was instrumental in securing [[Union Army|Union]] successes during the [[Valley Campaigns of 1864]], most notably the [[Battle of Cedar Creek]].  Many of the Union generals would eventually be memorialized in [[Washington, D.C.]], with statues spread throughout the city.  While looking at one of his comrade's equestrian sculptures, Sheridan was not impressed with the depiction of the man and horse.  He reportedly told his wife \"Whatever you do after I'm gone, don't put me on a horse like that.\"  Following her husband's death in 1888, when an equestrian sculpture of her husband was being planned, Irene Sheridan insisted the horse be as \"proud and courageous as its rider.\"<ref name=jacob>{{cite book | author=Jacob, Kathryn Allamong | title=Testament to Union: Civil War Monuments in Washington, Part 3 | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=M6HIB4fNjGoC&lpg=PA71&ots=kteSt_qrPZ&dq=Grand%20Army%20of%20the%20Republic%20Memorial%20%28Stephenson%29&pg=PA134#v=onepage&q=Sheridan&f=false | location=Baltimore | publisher=JHU Press | pages=134\u2013138 | date=1998 | isbn=9780801858611 | accessdate=November 11, 2014 }}</ref>\n\nOn March 2, 1889, Congress authorized the erection of a memorial to Sheridan and appropriated $50,000 for its construction.<ref name=smithsonian/><ref name=greiner>{{cite book | author=Greiner, Henry C. | title=General Phil Sheridan as I knew him, playmate \u2013 comrade \u2013 friend | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=cJwvAAAAYAAJ&dq=Philip%20Sheridan%20Gutzon&pg=PA423#v=onepage&q=Philip%20Sheridan%20Gutzon&f=false | location=Chicago | publisher=J.S. Hyland and Company | pages=423\u2013425 | date=1908 | oclc=2076519 | accessdate=November 11, 2014 }}</ref>   The original sculptor chosen to complete the project was Sheridan's friend [[John Quincy Adams Ward]], who had completed other works in Washington, D.C., including ''[[Major General George Henry Thomas]]'' and the [[James A. Garfield Monument]].  Ward signed a contract with the Sheridan monument commission in 1892 which called for the equestrian statue to be completed by 1898.<ref name=jacob/>  He submitted a sketch of the model in 1892, but that design was not approved.<ref name=smithsonian/>  Not only did Ward not complete the work by 1898, he had only completed a life-size [[Study (art)|study]] of Sheridan's head by 1903.  Ward finally completed a model of Sheridan, but when Irene and her son, Philip Sheridan Jr., visited Ward's studio in [[New York City]] to see the model, they both hated it.  He was depicted as a stout older officer atop a stilted horse.  The commission eventually cancelled the contract with Ward in 1905.  His model of Sheridan was eventually cast in 1916 and stands in front of the [[New York State Capitol]].<ref name=jacob/>\n[[File:General Philip Sheridan Memorial - neigh.JPG|thumb|upright|Closeup of the statue]]\n[[Gutzon Borglum]] had closely followed the events surrounding Ward's procrastination and firing as the two men had an argumentative past.  Borglum was convinced he could do a better job with the design and he also needed the money.  He set out to study as much as possible about Sheridan's life by reading his memoirs and biographies.  Borglum was able to secure an invitation to a Washington, D.C. party that Irene attended.  He sat next to her and invited Irene to his studio in New York.  Borglum set out models of horses throughout the studio before she arrived and surprised Irene by how much he know about her husband.  At the behest of Irene, on July 2, 1907, Borglum received a contract to sculpt the memorial.<ref name=jacob/><ref name=smithsonian/>  He was a [[Danish American]] artist who was greatly influenced by French sculptor [[Auguste Rodin]].<ref name=wapo>{{cite news | last=Richard | first=Paul | date=July 3, 2005 | title=From the Collection: Washington's Prize Possessions | url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2005/07/01/AR2005070100338.html | newspaper=The Washington Post | accessdate=November 11, 2014 }}</ref>  Borglum is best known for his carvings at [[Mount Rushmore]] and [[Stone Mountain]].  The Sheridan sculpture is his only equestrian monument in Washington, D.C.<ref name=washtimes>{{cite news | last=Longaker | first=Mark | date=May 23, 2007 | title=Men on horseback dominate memorials | url=http://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2007/may/23/20070523-102441-7610r/?page=all | newspaper=The Washington Times | accessdate=November 11, 2014 }}</ref>  Borglum's other works in Washington, D.C. include ''[[Rabboni (sculpture)|Rabboni]]'' at [[Rock Creek Cemetery]] and several statues in the [[National Statuary Hall Collection]] in the [[United States Capitol]].<ref name=otherworks>{{cite web | url=http://siris-artinventories.si.edu/ipac20/ipac.jsp?session=G4L57D8992417.3630&profile=ariall&uri=link=3100006~!1133~!3100001~!3100002&aspect=Browse&menu=search&ri=1&source=~!siartinventories&term=Borglum%2C+Gutzon%2C+1867-1941%2C+sculptor.&index=AUTHOR | title=Borglum, Gutzon, 1867\u20131941, sculptor. | publisher=Smithsonian American Art Museum | accessdate=November 11, 2014 }}</ref>\n\nOn January 17, 1908, Borglum's design received approval by the Sheridan monument commission, including then-Secretary of War [[William Howard Taft]], General [[Henry Clark Corbin|Henry C. Corbin]], and Brigadier General Michael V. Sheridan, Philip Sheridan's brother.  Irene also approved the design and chose the memorial site.<ref name=tribune>{{cite news | date=January 26, 1908 | title=Phil Sheridan Statue: Monument of the Cavalry Leader for the Nation's Capital | url=http://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn83030214/1908-01-26/ed-1/seq-22/ | newspaper=New-York Tribune | accessdate=November 11, 2014 }}</ref><ref name=districtnom>{{cite web | url={{NRHP url|id=89001743}} | title=National Register of Historic Places Registration Form | publisher=National Park Service | page=9 | accessdate=November 11, 2014 }}</ref>  She lived at 2211 [[Massachusetts Avenue (Washington, D.C.)|Massachusetts Avenue]] NW (currently offices for the [[Embassy of Greece, Washington, D.C.|Embassy of Greece]]), a short distance from Sheridan Circle and the sculpture.<ref name=irene>{{cite web | url=http://www.mfa.gr/usa/en/the-embassy/history/the-building.html | title=The Building | publisher=Embassy of Greece in Washington, D.C. | accessdate=November 11, 2014 }}</ref>  As Borglum worked on the sculpture, he would talk to Sheridan's friends, sketch Sheridan's artifacts, and visit Irene.  Since Philip Jr. bore a very close resemblance to his father, Borglum used him as a model for the sculpture.  When the artwork was completed, Irene, Philip Jr., and Sheridan's three daughters loved the finished result.<ref name=jacob/>  The sculpture depicts Sheridan riding his horse, Rienzi, as he assembles his troops during the Battle of Cedar Creek on October 19, 1864.  He had raced {{convert|20|mile}} from [[Winchester, Virginia|Winchester]], [[Virginia]], to reach the battle.  Following the Union victory, Sheridan renamed the horse Winchester.  After Winchester died in 1878, Sheridan had him preserved and mounted.  The horse is now on display at the [[National Museum of American History]].<ref name=modany>{{cite web | last=Modany | first=Angela | url=http://americanhistory.si.edu/blog/2012/04/the-war-horse-of-the-civil-war.html | title=The \"War Horse\" of the Civil War | publisher=National Museum of American History | date=April 4, 2012 | accessdate=November 11, 2014 }}</ref>  Congress paid for the plaza, base, and preparation of the memorial site, while veterans of the [[Army of the Cumberland]] paid for the statue.<ref name=statuenom>{{cite web | last=Scott | first=Gary | url={{NRHP url|id=78000257}} | title=National Register of Historic Places Inventory\u2014Nomination Form | publisher=National Park Service | date=September 19, 1977 | page=9 | accessdate=November 11, 2014 }}</ref>  Architect Henry Winslow designed the base and setting.  The stonework was provided by the Mohegan Granite Company of New York while the Malnati Stone Company of Washington, D.C. set the stones in place.<ref name=smithsonian/>\n\n===Dedication===\n[[File:The National Memorial for General Phil. Sheridan is to be unveiled at Washington this week LOC 3707378358.jpg|thumb|upright|Illustrated supplement in the ''New-York Tribune'' announcing the dedication of the General Sheridan monument. November 22, 1908.]]\nThe Sheridan memorial was dedicated on November 25, 1908.  A large crowd was present with many dignitaries in attendance, including President [[Theodore Roosevelt]], military officers, diplomats, and veterans of the Civil War and [[Spanish\u2013American War]].  A processions of troops led by Brigadier General [[J. Franklin Bell]] paraded past the crowd and dignitaries while the [[United States Marine Band]] played music.  Secretary of War [[Luke Edward Wright|Luke E. Wright]] presided over the dedication ceremony and [[Denis J. O'Connell]], rector of [[The Catholic University of America]], delivered the invocation.  Roosevelt, Brigadier General [[Horace Porter]], and Wright gave eulogies of Sheridan.  Roosevelt gave a short speech praising Sheridan's valiant acts while Porter's speech was an in depth review of Sheridan's life, including his days at [[West Point]] and his campaigns during the Civil War and [[American Indian Wars]].  After Irene and Philip Jr. removed the covering of the statue, the crowd cheered loudly and many began to recite [[Thomas Buchanan Read]]'s poem, ''Sheridan's Ride''.<ref name=jacob/>\n\n===Historic designation===\nAlong with [[Civil War Monuments in Washington, D.C.|seventeen other Civil War monuments]], ''General Philip Sheridan'' was added to the [[National Register of Historic Places]] (NRHP) on September 20, 1978, and the District of Columbia Inventory of Historic Sites on March 3, 1979.  The Sheridan monument is also designated a [[contributing property]] to the [[Massachusetts Avenue Historic District (Washington, D.C.)|Massachusetts Avenue Historic District]], listed on the NRHP in 1974, and the [[Sheridan-Kalorama Historic District]], listed on the NRHP in 1989.<ref name=dcinventory/>  The sculpture and the surrounding park are owned and maintained by the [[National Park Service]], a federal agency of the [[United States Department of the Interior|Interior Department]].<ref name=smithsonian/>\n\n==Design and location==\n[[File:Sheridan Statue, Washington, D.C. npcc.jpg|thumb|right|The Sheridan memorial in 1916|alt=|left]]\nThe bronze equestrian sculpture is at the center of Sheridan Circle, a traffic circle located at the intersection of 23rd Street, R Street and Massachusetts Avenue NW within the [[Embassy Row]] section of the [[Sheridan-Kalorama]] neighborhood.<ref name=dcinventory/><ref name=survey>{{cite book | title=Washington West Quadrangle, District of Columbia\u2013Maryland\u2013Virginia | publisher=United States Department of the Interior | author=United States Geological Survey | year=2011 | location=Reston, Virginia | pages=1 : 24,000. 7.5 Minute Series (Topographic) | OCLC=777027791 }}</ref> It measures {{convert|10|ft}} high and {{convert|12|ft}} long while the rectangular granite base measures {{convert|3|ft}} high.  The horse is slightly reared back while standing on a rocky surface.  Sheridan is turned to his right with his right arm extended behind him. The right hand is holding his hat while his left hand holds the horse's reins.  Sheridan is wearing a military uniform with a long coat belted at the waist and is portrayed with a moustache and wavy hair.  The sculpture is surrounded by a plaza measuring {{convert|37|ft}} long with five steps on the front and back leading to the sculpture.  Curved benches run along the interior of the plaza facing the sculpture while the exterior of the plaza features two pairs of lion head fountain spouts.  Water poured from the spouts into square basins, but this feature is no longer working.<ref name=smithsonian>{{cite web | url=http://siris-artinventories.si.edu/ipac20/ipac.jsp?&profile=all&source=~!siartinventories&uri=full=3100001~!16268~!0#focus | title=General Philip Sheridan, (sculpture). | publisher=Smithsonian American Art Museum | accessdate=November 11, 2014 }}</ref>\n\nInscriptions on the monument include the following:<ref name=smithsonian/>\n* <small>GUTZON BORGLUM 1908</small> (left side of the sculpture)\n* <small>GORHAM CO FOUNDERS</small> (right side of the sculpture near the base)\n* <small>SHERIDAN</small> (front side of the base)\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Visual arts|United States}}\n* [[List of equestrian statues in the United States]]\n* [[List of public art in Washington, D.C., Ward 2]]\n* [[Outdoor sculpture in Washington, D.C.]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Commons category inline|General Philip Sheridan Memorial}}\n\n{{Gutzon Borglum}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Philip Sheridan, General}}\n[[Category:1908 establishments in Washington, D.C.]]